<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls vs. Yen, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Monday as Tokyo  
stocks rallied amid more indications the Japanese economy has begun 
a slow recovery from its worst recession in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also slid against the euro as Germany reported a  
greater-than-expected increase in manufacturing orders in January. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0935, up  
from $1.0901 on Friday. The dollar was quoted at 117.82 Japanese 
yen, down from 118.78 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders sent the dollar lower against the yen Monday after the  
Ministry of Finance reported that Japan's current account surplus 
for January rose 72.2 percent from year-ago levels. 
</P>
<P>
	The report helped lift Tokyo share prices, which also drew a  
boost from reports that Nissan Motor, suffering from a staggering 
debt load, is close to a deal that would allow French automaker 
Renault to take up to a 40 percent stake in Japan's No. 2 
automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	``A 290-point rise in the Nikkei overnight has underpinned the  
perception that the Japanese economy may have turned the corner,'' 
said Michael Lewis, currency economist at Deutsche Bank in London. 
Japan's benchmark Nikkei stock index rose 1.9 percent Monday to 
close at 15,779 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4653 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4633, and 1.5266 Canadian dollars, up from 1.5235. The British 
pound fell to $1.6228 from $1.6313. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro no longer  
are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7886 German 
marks, down from 1.7940; 5.9988 French francs, down from 6.0168; 
and 1,769.91 Italian lire, down from 1,776.20. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
