<HEADLINE> PC Bargains Bar Is Set Even Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Lately, PC retailing has adopted a new theme song, ``The Limbo  
Rock.'' That's because many sellers have lowered the price bar on 
some very good systems. 
</P>
<P>
	And it's sweet music indeed to the shopper looking for a first --  
or additional -- PC. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider Apple, not always a low-cost leader in the past. Its  
popular iMac was $1,299 before Christmas but is now $999. And some 
retailers are throwing in a color inkjet. 
</P>
<P>
	On the PC side, here's what a major New York area electronics  
retailer offers for $788: 
</P>
<P>
	IBM 400 megahertz Pentium II with MMX, 128 megabytes of RAM, a  
6.4-gigabyte hard drive, 40-speed CD-ROM, 56-kilobits-per-second 
modem, 17-inch monitor, 16-bit sound card and a Hewlett Packard 
420c color printer. A bonus package includes a joystick, Windows 98 
instructional video, multimedia speakers, a Seiko electronic 
organizer, some bundled software, and even a cell phone (if you buy 
a year's service). 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, bargains include a $688 Compaq with a 350-megahertz  
Pentium II chip, 64 megabytes of RAM and a 17-inch monitor. What's 
more, some systems at around $1,000 include DVD-ROM drives, which 
play full-length, full-screen movies as well as perform traditional 
CD-ROM chores. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of this is fueled by the pace of chip development, which  
puts the newest, hottest chip into the marketplace before the 
previous newest, hottest chip has had a chance to cool to room 
temperature. This may be tough on the nerves of manufacturers and 
retailers, but it's a boost for consumers, since even the 
``obsolete'' chip is often far more powerful than most ordinary 
applications can ever use. 
</P>
<P>
	Peripherals are also taking a price plunge. A 4,800-DPI (dots  
per inch) flatbed color scanner costs $28 after a $30 rebate. A 
40-speed CD-ROM runs $45-$80, 56-kilobit V.90 modems are below 
$100, and six-gigabyte hard drives go for around $150 -- offering 
roughly 300 times the storage at one-third the cost of the early PC 
hard drives. 
</P>
<P>
	A megabyte of memory once cost $40 to $50; now, $50 buys 32  
megabytes. 
</P>
<P>
	In the midst of all this consumer happiness, there are still  
some bumps in the road. If a deal seems too good to be true -- well 
below everyone else's -- it probably is, especially if it's from a 
new or unknown small retailer or mail-order firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The April issue of PC World magazine has an excellent article on  
stolen and counterfeit chips. It points out that what you think is 
a top-of-the-line chip might be an older one that has been 
relabeled. The article is worth a look. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the magazine itself is worth a look. PC World has been  
doing a solid, consistent job of seeing things from a consumer's 
viewpoint, with focused articles that explain the jargon clearly. 
The $5.99 cover price could jolt someone who remembers 5-cent comic 
books, but subscribers pay substantially less. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Questions and comments are welcome. E-mail via the Internet to  
lblasko@ap.org, or by regular mail to Larry Blasko, AP, 50 
Rockefeller Plaza, New York, NY 10020. 


</P>
</TEXT>
