<HEADLINE> Ex-Chicago Alderman Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Former Alderman Larry Bloom, known as a stickler  
for ethics while he served on the City Council, was sentenced 
Monday to six months in federal prison and fined $5,000 for 
cheating on his taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloom pleaded guilty in December to reporting $9,000 -- including  
a $6,000 payoff he took from a corrupt contractor -- as rental 
income in claiming a tax loss for his real estate company. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors dropped other corruption charges against him  
that arose in their City Hall investigation called Operation Silver 
Shovel. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloom was elected alderman as an anti-corruption candidate in  
1979 and ran unsuccessfully on the same issue for mayor in 1989 and 
city treasurer in 1995. He left the council that year. 
</P>
<P>
	He admitted that in 1994 he took $6,000 from the government's  
mole, John Christopher. In exchange for some of the money, Bloom 
agreed to help Christopher get city-funded services for 
rock-crushing business. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloom also admitted disguising the source of a $10,000 campaign  
contribution from Christopher on his campaign disclosure form. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
