<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cold Virus May Cause Heart Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A respiratory virus responsible for the common  
cold can infect adult hearts in rare cases, causing damage that can 
lead to heart failure and sudden death, researchers reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The study linked some adenoviruses, which can cause upper  
respiratory infections, to a condition in adults called left 
ventricular dysfunction. Earlier studies found that some 
adenoviruses cause LVD in children. 
</P>
<P>
	The study's lead author, Jeffrey Towbin of Baylor College of  
Medicine in Houston, said less than 1 percent of those who get a 
viral infection with flu- or cold-like symptoms will be at risk for 
heart damage from infection. 
</P>
<P>
	Patients with LVD have a swollen left ventricle that is  
squeezing poorly, leading to disabling and eventually fatal heart 
failure and possibly sudden death. The symptoms can include fatigue 
or shortness of breath. 
</P>
<P>
	The heart condition can be revealed by a physical exam or chest  
X-ray. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have a cold and you get better and then, two to four  
weeks later, you feel bad again, it's probably worth contacting 
your physician,'' said Towbin, professor of pediatrics, molecular 
and human genetics and cardiovascular sciences. ``If you don't have 
fever or a runny nose again and if it persists more than a couple 
of days, there may be something going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The study was published in today's issue of Circulation, a  
journal of the American Heart Association. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, there are two to eight cases of LVD per  
100,000 people each year, according to the heart association. An 
estimated 40 out of every 100,000 Americans suffer from the 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	LVD can also be caused by heart disease, genetic defects, or  
tissue damage from using cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one study has shown that young adults who develop LVD  
have a 50 percent chance of dying in the next seven years, said Dr. 
Steven Lipshultz, chief of pediatric cardiology at the University 
of Rochester Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	In the study, researchers studied tissue samples from the hearts  
of 94 adults ages 17 to 76 whose LVD resulted from an unknown 
cause. They found genetic evidence of adenoviruses in 12 of the 
patients. 
</P>
<P>
	Lipshultz said the findings could lead to the development of a  
vaccine to protect the heart against adenoviruses. There is a 
vaccine for some adenoviruses, but it is not widely used and may 
not be effective against the types that cause LVD. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
