<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gene Research Sites Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The National Institutes of Health on Monday  
named the three sites where researchers will participate in a 
project aimed at deciphering the genetic code hidden in genes. 
</P>
<P>
	Research of the human genome -- all of the DNA in our chromosomes  
-- will be conducted at the Washington University School of Medicine 
in St. Louis, Baylor College of Medicine in Houston and the 
Whitehead Institute in Cambridge, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	The project will help figure out the basic units of heredity. It  
will then focus on how genes determine physical characteristics, 
the way babies develop and what diseases people get. Finally, the 
project will focus on ways to prevent the estimated 4,000 genetic 
diseases in humans. 
</P>
<P>
	The three sites will share $81.6 million in funding over the  
next 12 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The NIH support, which comes from the National Human Genome  
Research Institute, will enable the sites to contribute to a 
working draft of at least 90 percent of the human genome by the 
spring of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Project researchers had originally hoped to sequence the genetic  
code of 3 billion chemical units by 2005. Because of technological 
advances, researchers say a complete sequence could be deciphered 
by 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	The gene research project began informally in 1980. It was  
officially launched in 1990 with the backing of the NIH and the 
Department of Energy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
