<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ill. Clinic Gets Suspicious Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- About 40 people were evacuated from a Planned  
Parenthood clinic in downtown Chicago Monday after workers received 
a suspicious package in the mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Bomb experts who X-rayed the package say it appeared to be a  
vial of liquid, said Lt. Gary Szparkowski, a police spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The vial was inside a sealed envelope and may have been leaking,  
he said. Police said it may take several days to determine the 
contents of the vial. 
</P>
<P>
	A portion of the street in front of the clinic was closed down  
for emergency crews, and about 40 workers were evacuated, he said. 
They were later allowed to return. 
</P>
<P>
	Szparkowski called the street closure and evacuation ``more  
precautionary than anything else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Steve Trombley, president and CEO of Chicago's Planned  
Parenthood, said he believed the package was linked to other ones 
received by clinics around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, Planned Parenthood clinics in Kansas City, Mo.,  
Manchester, N.H., Sioux Falls, S.D., and Burlington, Vt., and 
abortion clinics in Washington, Milwaukee, Cincinnati and Rapid 
City, S.D., reported receiving suspicious packages, many purporting 
to be the potentially deadly bacterium anthrax. The threats turned 
out to be false. 
</P>
<P>
	The mailing followed a bomb that exploded outside an Asheville,  
N.C., abortion clinic over the weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
