<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La. Church Empty After Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GONZALES, La. (AP) -- It might have been any other Sunday at  
church. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of New St. John Fellowship greeted each other with warm  
handshakes. Children dressed in their best submitted to last-minute 
adjustments from their mothers. 
</P>
<P>
	But it wasn't a usual worship service. The congregation was  
gathered miles away from their usual home, leaving empty the little 
white church where three people died in a hail of bullets last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 members of the congregation shook off a damp winter  
chill and bad memories during the two-hour service at the Gonzales 
Civic Center. There were rollicking spirituals, tears and shouts of 
``Amen!'' and pastor Clarence Stephens' admonishment to members to 
keep the faith. 
</P>
<P>
	He likened the violence that interrupted Wednesday's Bible study  
to a storm sent by God as a test. 
</P>
<P>
	``A pre-warned storm shows how well you can prepare,'' Stephens  
shouted. ``But an unexpected storm -- follow me now -- an unexpected 
storm will show your true strengths and weaknesses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shon Miller, in his 20s, from Gonzales faces charges of  
first-degree murder and attempted murder. Police said he burst into 
the church and opened fire into the pews, killing his wife, Carla 
Vessel Miller, 24, and son, Shon Jr., 2. 
</P>
<P>
	A 19-year-old church member, Vaniaro Jackson, also was killed,  
apparently a random victim. Carla Miller's mother, Mildred Vessel, 
53, ambushed in her car near the church before the other killings, 
also died. 
</P>
<P>
	Church leaders decided last week they would hold no more  
services in the building where the shootings occurred. They are 
raising money to complete electrical work and other interior 
details on a new building nearby, but that could take months. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the congregation was trying to adjust to new  
surroundings. 
</P>
<P>
	Brenda Larks had charge of the smallest children. There were 11  
of them, some toddlers, some as old as 7. Nine of them were in the 
church Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Larks led the children through Bible verses, then asked them  
what they should do in light of last week's violence. One said, 
``Pray.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's right,'' Ms. Larks said. ``Everybody that got shot --  
we've got to pray for them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
