<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher Monday,  
with the key index surging in Tokyo on reports that Nissan Motor 
Co. is about to forge an alliance with French carmaker Renault. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 290.74  
points, or 1.88 percent, to close at 15,779.60. On Friday, the 
average closed down 13.28 points, or 0.09 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices opened lower after the Japanese government released  
data Friday showing that the country's economy shrank 0.8 percent 
in the October-December quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But the market soon shook off the grim news when troubled Nissan  
Motor's share price surged on speculation that the company is close 
to a deal with Renault. News reports said that the pact would allow 
Renault to take a stake of up to 40 percent in Nissan and supply 
three board members. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Nissan Motor, Japan's second largest automaker, said  
in a statement that the two companies are studying the possibility 
of a tie-up, but that no formal proposal for an alliance had been 
received from Renault. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 118.42 yen in the  
afternoon, down 1.62 yen from late Friday in Tokyo, and also below 
its late New York level of 118.78 yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai share prices also surged, with the main index rising 4.4  
percent in reaction to Friday's passage by the Thai senate of a 
long-awaited bankruptcy bill, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index rose 15.09 points to  
360.88. 
</P>
<P>
	The bankruptcy bill is aimed at speeding up Thailand's  
bankruptcy process and making it easier for financial institutions 
to recover problem loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucking the trend was the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange, where  
shares finished sharply lower as concerns about the health of the 
Malaysian economy blunted relief over Prime Minister Mahathir 
Mohamad's victory in the Sabah state election, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Malaysian benchmark Composite Index slumped 2 percent, or  
10.34 points, to 518.45. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed at a 12-week high as continued  
buying in semiconductor stocks pulled the main index above the key 
6,500-point mark. The Weighted Stock Price Index rose 135.59 points 
or 2.1 percent, to 6,598.32. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: A surge in banks, energy and and utilities stocks drove  
the Australian share market to a new closing high Monday and its 
third consecutive record finish. The All Ordinaries Index rose 28.2 
points, or 1 percent, to 2,989.5. 
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG: Share prices closed higher for the second consecutive  
session in light trading. The blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 35.10 
points, or 0.3 percent, closing at 10,836.86. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed higher in relatively  
light trading. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 10.22 
points, or 0.4 percent, to 2,166.76. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed lower in thin trading. The  
Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 3.96 points, or 0.2 percent, 
to 1,941.34. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed higher for the third consecutive day.  
The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 1.22 points, or 0.2 
percent, to 592.02. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mixed in sluggish trading. The  
Straits Times Index rose 0.6 percent, or 8.45 points, to 1,494.19. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian share prices closed lower after the  
government's decision to close 38 banks on Saturday failed to lift 
market sentiment. The Composite Index fell 3.619 points, or 0.9 
percent, to 372.318. 

</P>
</TEXT>
