<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Gain / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Defying Japan's moribund economy, Tokyo stocks  
rallied today when Nissan Motor's share price surged on reports the 
automaker was close to a tie up with Renault. The dollar dropped 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 290.74 points,  
or 1.88 percent, to close the day's session at 15,779.60 points at. 
On Friday, the average closed down 13.28 points, or 0.09 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 118.42 yen in the afternoon, down 1.62 yen  
from late Friday in Tokyo, and also below its late New York level 
of 118.78 yen on Friday. The greenback ranged in value from 117.92 
yen to 119.45 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 129.44 yen, down  
from 131.35 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices started lower after the  
government released data Friday showing that Japan's economy shrank 
0.8 percent in the October-December quarter of 1998, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the market soon shook off the grim news when troubled Nissan  
Motor's share price surged on speculation that the company is close 
to a deal with French automaker Renault. News reports said that the 
pact would allow Renault to take a stake of up to 40 percent in 
Nissan and supply three board members. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Nissan Motor said in a statement that the two companies  
are studying the possibility of a tie-up, but that no formal 
proposal for an alliance had been received from Renault. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sentiment has improved, making it difficult to sell,'' said  
Kazunori Shimono, manager of futures and options at Ryoko 
Securities, though there were no fresh factors other than the 
Nissan news. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancers overwhelmed retreaters 810 to 401, while 111 issues  
were unchanged. Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock 
Exchange was estimated at 741.49 million shares, down from 1.19 
billion shares Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section gained 15.57 points, or 1.30 percent, to 1,211.18 
points. The TOPIX closed down 0.57 points, or 0.05 percent, on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the foreign exchange market, the dollar remained under  
selling pressure against the yen after the Japanese currency moved 
higher against the euro on Friday, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar got a little help from Vice Finance Minister for  
International Affairs Eisuke Sakakibara, who said that excessive 
yen strength was not welcome, and that the Bank of Japan agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, overseas players and Japanese trust banks,  
heartened in part by strength in Japanese stock prices, sold the 
dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	``Market players have taken the view that there is room for the  
dollar to fall further,'' said Shuji Takano, assistant manager of 
foreign exchange at ABN AMRO Bank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Also weighing on the dollar was the sharp rise in Japan's  
current account surplus for January. The Ministry of Finance said 
today that the nation's current account surplus for January rose 
72.2 percent from the year-earlier month to $6.82 billion, before 
adjustment for seasonal factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese  
government bond rose to 1.785 percent, driving its price down to 
100.11 yen. On Friday, it settled at 1.715 percent and its price 
stood at 100.67 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
