<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HMO Group Requiring Outside Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- HMOs must let patients appeal denials of care  
to outside experts if they want a seal of approval from the 
nation's largest accrediting group. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the latest in a string of private initiatives boosting the  
idea of external reviews, which both supporters and critics of 
managed care have come to support as a way to assure consumers they 
won't be unfairly denied treatment for financial reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Committee on Quality Assurance, which accredits  
about half of the nation's health maintenance organizations, plans 
to require these independent reviews beginning next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress is in the midst of considering regulations for HMOs,  
and mandatory external review is among the most popular provisions. 
Even business leaders who disdain federal mandates acknowledge that 
many consumer complaints could be resolved if they could be taken 
to independent experts who do not work for the HMO. 
</P>
<P>
	Some opponents of HMO regulations also have come to support  
external review as a way of arguing against more burdensome federal 
regulations, such as new rights to sue HMOs in court. 
</P>
<P>
	The accreditation group planned to release proposed details  
Tuesday for public comment, part of a set of requirements HMOs must 
meet in order to win accreditation. Many large employers look for 
the accreditation in choosing an HMO for their workers. The 
committee will issue final rules by July and they will take effect 
in July 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Other new proposals for accreditation include requiring HMOs to  
consult the proper specialists in reviewing complaints during the 
internal appeal that precedes any external review. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also wants to require HMOs to allow patients to  
stay with their doctors during a course of treatment for up to 90 
days, even if the doctor is dropped from the health plan's network. 
</P>
<P>
	Virtually all HMOs allow patients to appeal decisions denying  
payment for care, but often the reviews are handled by people who 
work for the insurance company. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, though, some large insurance companies,  
including Aetna-U.S. Healthcare, have said they will allow their 
customers to appeal to outside boards that will have final say over 
what is covered. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last month, the HMO trade group, the American Association  
of Health Plans, said it will urge its members to adopt external 
appeals. The group also said it could accept federal legislation 
requiring it. 
</P>
<P>
	The quality committee said it hopes to move the debate along.  
``It's obviously something that's in the wind,'' said Margaret E. 
O'Kane, the group's president. 
</P>
<P>
	More importantly, O'Kane said, the group wants to assure that  
HMO appeal processes are done right. 
</P>
<P>
	``As usual, the devil is in the details,'' she said. ``We want  
to be sure that ... it's really an independent and credible 
process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The HMO trade group said it is also concerned about the details,  
though it supports the idea in concept. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is another important private-sector voice lending its  
support to the idea of outside review,'' said Susan Pisano, 
spokeswoman for AAHP. 
</P>
<P>
	About 18 states already require health plans operating inside  
their borders to offer external appeals, but those requirements 
only apply to plans regulated by states. Many large employers use 
health plans that fall under federal regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Committee for Quality Assurance accredits about 310  
of the nation's 630 HMOs and point-of-service health plans, 
including the largest. Those 310 plans serve about three-quarters 
of all Americans in HMOs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 12:55:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybean, Grain Futures Drop / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and grain futures prices settled mostly  
lower Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Dry weather in South America played a large role in pressuring  
futures prices, analysts said. Good weather would allow farmers 
there to harvest large corn and soybean crops in Argentina and 
Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	A strengthening Brazilian currency also could cause Brazilian  
farmers to sell quickly, further increasing the supply and causing 
worldwide prices to drop further, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Anemic corn and soybeans prices put some pressure on wheat  
futures early in the day -- though technical factors erased much of 
the losses by closing time. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for May delivery fell 1/4 cent to $2.72 1/4 a bushel; May corn  
fell 2 3/4 cents to 2.20 a bushel; May oats dropped 1 1/4 cents to $1.09 3/4 
a bushel, and May soybeans were down 3 1/2 cents to $4.71 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, beef and pork futures finished lower on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle futures fell 0.80 cent to 66.35 cents a pound;  
March feeder cattle dropped 0.23 cent to 71.57 cents per pound; 
April lean hogs fell a cent to 41.07 cents a pound; and March pork 
bellies dropped 0.72 cent to 48 cents per pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
