<HEADLINE> Ciena To Buy 2 Communications Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINTHICUM, Md. (AP) -- Ciena Corp. is buying two optical  
communications companies for stock worth nearly $1 billion, the 
networking equipment maker announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lightera, based in Cupertino, Ca., builds optical switches and  
operating systems for fiber optic networks. Omnia of Marlborough, 
Mass., builds equipment that allows telephone companies to provide 
voice and data services through fiber optic networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are privately-held companies.  
</P>
<P>
	Ciena, based in Linthicum, Md., makes devices that enable fiber  
optic lines to carry more data. The company will issue 20.6 million 
shares to acquire Lightera and 16 million shares to acquire Omnia. 
</P>
<P>
	The deals come about six months after Tellabs Inc. called off an  
agreement to acquire Ciena, blaming a series of financial setbacks 
at Ciena. 
</P>
<P>
	Ciena's stock closed down $2.06 1/4 a share, or more than 7  
percent, at $24.75 in trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. The stock 
fell from a high of $92.37 5/8 last July to a low of $8.12 1/2 after the 
Tellabs deal unraveled. 

</P>
</TEXT>
