<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Wants Tougher Seat Belt Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- To prevent child deaths in car crashes, an  
expert panel recommended Monday that seat belt laws be strengthened 
and older children stay in booster seats longer before graduating 
to seat belts. 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater had asked the panel to  
come up with recommendations for children aged 4 through 15 because 
so many die in auto crashes while riding unrestrained. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, car crashes killed 1,627 children in that age group. Of  
those, 1,015 were unrestrained. Properly used booster seats and 
safety belts would have prevented about 500 of the deaths, said 
Phil Haseltine, head of the panel of government, medical, industry 
and consumer safety experts. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a crash, unrestrained kids become missiles flying about the  
vehicle interior,'' Haseltine said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another problem is that children often are not secured by  
restraints appropriate for their ages and weights, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel said children who have outgrown child seats should use  
booster seats at least to age 8. Only 5 percent of children ages 4 
to 8 currently ride in booster seats, which allow lap and shoulder 
belts to be positioned properly over a child's hips and chest. 
</P>
<P>
	``Parents frequently do not know what a booster seat is,''  
Haseltine said. ``Retail sales (of booster seats) are so low some 
manufacturers don't want to stock them on their shelves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christine Guarino of Germantown, Md., always placed her  
5-year-old son, Stephen, in a booster seat. In February, a dump 
truck tore into the right side of her minivan near Stephen. The 
crash left the boy's right leg resting against the truck's bumper, 
Mrs. Guarino said, but his booster seat protected him from injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was still in his car seat, safe as can be,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The panel also recommended that:  
</P>
<P>
	--States tighten seat belt laws and enforce them so that children  
must buckle up. 
</P>
<P>
	In all 50 states, laws require children to be restrained in  
vehicles but normally target children only to ages 4 or 5. In 
contrast, although the government recommends that all children 
under age 13 ride in back seats, most states lack seat belt laws 
requiring older children to be restrained in the back. 
</P>
<P>
	--A crash dummy representing a 10-year-old dummy should be  
developed to help understand child injuries better. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel said Congress should increase the federal motor fuel  
tax by one-half of a cent, generating $750 million to pay for 
research and other safety programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
