<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Burlington To Buy Denim Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Textile giant Burlington Industries,  
which produces fabric for all the major jeans retailers, will now 
sew denim clothes as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's denim subsidiary announced Monday it has agreed to  
buy a new jeans sewing facility from Lucky Star Industries in 
Mexico for an undisclosed price. 
</P>
<P>
	While Burlington has contracted work with outside garment makers  
to turn their denim into clothing for retailers in the past, the 
plant would become the first Burlington facility to actually sew 
clothing in-house. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant in Aguascalientes, Mexico opened early last year and  
is expected to be in full production by the end of 1999. At full 
capacity it will employ about 1,200 people. The transaction is 
expected to be completed by the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	Dutch Leonard, president of Burlington Global Denim, said the  
garments produced by Burlington products should compete effectively 
against Asian imports. 
</P>
<P>
	Less expensive Asian jeans sold in the U.S. in part prompted  
Burlington in January to announce denim plant closings in 
Mooresville and Hillsville, Va. The two plants were among seven to 
be closed nationwide in moves that will eliminate 2,900 positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Burlington Global Denim also produces denim at a plant in  
Stonewall, Miss., and another in Mexico. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
