<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montana Man Dominating Iditarod </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNALAKLEET, Alaska (AP) -- Were the 1999 Iditarod Trail Sled Dog  
Race a political campaign, the vanquished already would have made 
their concession speeches to Doug Swingley. 
</P>
<P>
	Short of a catastrophe in the next day, Swingley will claim his  
second Iditarod title. For everyone else, the race now is to decide 
where they fit in behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	Swingley, from Lincoln, Mont., crossed ice-covered Norton Bay  
and pulled into the village of Koyuk at 10:55 a.m. Alaska time 
(2:55 p.m. EST) Monday. Koyuk is about 170 miles from the 
Iditarod's finish line in Nome. 
</P>
<P>
	At his current pace, Swingley could reach Nome as soon as  
Tuesday evening and claim the $54,000 paycheck and new pickup truck 
that goes to the winner of the 1,100-mile race across the Alaska 
wilderness. 
</P>
<P>
	He was more than nine hours in front of Martin Buser of Big  
Lake, Alaska, who arrived in Shaktoolik at 9:20 a.m. with nine 
dogs. Shaktoolik, on the Bering Sea coast, is about 60 miles from 
Koyuk. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time a winner finished that far in front of the  
runner-up was 1992, when Buser reached Nome 10 hours ahead of 
four-time champion Susan Butcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not many Iditarods where a guy finds himself this far  
out in front, and not having anybody breathing down his throat,'' 
Swingley said late Sunday just before leaving Unalakleet, 100 miles 
from Koyuk, with a team of 12 dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Buser had an eight-hour cushion for second place, but third  
through 14th positions all were up for grabs Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	While the thrill's not the same as winning, there's a powerful  
incentive for mushers to move up. Third place pays about $41,000, 
while 14th pays about $11,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Swenson of Two Rivers, Alaska, currently running third,  
said Monday he was feeling some pressure from behind. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're creeping up,'' he said, pulling on his heavy boots as  
a first step to leaving Unalakleet. ``You don't see them for days, 
and then all of a sudden they're right here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Jeff King of Denali Park, Alaska, was fourth  
into Unalakleet at about 10 a.m., 90 minutes after Swenson. Within 
the next 90 minutes came four other Alaskans -- Paul Gebhardt of 
Kasilof, John Baker of Kotzebue, Vern Halter of Willow and Bill 
Cotter of Nenana. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker, Halter and Cotter were among a group of nine mushers who  
struck out from Kaltag in quick succession starting at 11 p.m. 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The mushers were tested on the 90 miles of sometimes-nasty trail  
from Kaltag to Unalakleet. As if climbing through a mountain pass 
into a headwind wasn't tough enough, they also had to slog through 
a stretch of overflow -- slushy snow calf-deep on top of a 
frozen-over river. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the worst overflow I've ever been in my life,'' said  
King, who likened it to sticky concrete. ``The dogs wouldn't go on 
it because it was so slippery, so I'd go on it and I'd break 
through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The overflow was the latest race challenge for the frontrunners.  
They hit badly rutted trail in the first 200 miles, followed by 
brutal cold, then cold along with a 20-mph headwind. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the overflow, Gebhardt said, ``I wouldn't call it icing on  
the cake because we still have to have a ground blizzard'' -- snow 
kicked up by strong winds that creates whiteout conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	While Swingley could be sleeping in a warm, comfortable bed by  
Tuesday, the back of the pack may have a week or more of mushing 
ahead of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Bringing up the rear was Shane Goosen, a rookie from Wasilla,  
Alaska. He was headed for Shageluk on Monday, about 500 miles from 
Nome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
