<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 22:42:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton-Congress Feud Fits Pattern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the long, unequal struggle between the  
White House and Congress over the power to send American troops to 
danger zones abroad, presidents insist they can act without asking. 
</P>
<P>
	And that they have done, since World War II.  
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's Kosovo peacekeeping mission fits the  
pattern, although it would begin with grudging House approval he 
didn't seek and didn't want debated in advance. The Senate may 
consider the Kosovo mission this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration was wary of House action, fearing that a  
rebuff would undermine Kosovo peace efforts in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	When he won, 219 to 191 Thursday night, Clinton said it was  
broad bipartisan support for the commitment he'd made a month 
before. It came with conditions -- including a report to Congress on 
how long the mission would last, a problem for Clinton since he set 
a deadline on another peacekeeping mission to the Balkans and 
couldn't meet it. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the approval nor the conditions are binding. It's a  
message, not a law. 
</P>
<P>
	But the three-year peace deal that would put a NATO force in  
Kosovo, including 4,000 Americans, still hasn't been settled. The 
Yugoslav side in the civil war is resisting, and Clinton said 
Monday that unless the Serbs yield, there would be little option 
but to punish them with airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	All of this comes at a difficult point for Clinton, with  
Republicans bearing down on criticism of his foreign policy over 
Chinese nuclear spying, Iraq and deployments in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	But he isn't yielding on his war powers. ``Every president has  
reserved the right to both receive the ... support or endure the 
opposition of Congress, but not to give up the constitutional 
responsibility to deploy United States forces in peacetime,'' he 
said. ``And I think my predecessors were right about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congresses have tried, fruitlessly, to find a way to share that  
power in the era of undeclared wars. There's a system on the books 
requiring approval to keep Americans in areas of possible conflict 
for more than three months after a president orders them there, but 
it never worked. 
</P>
<P>
	Hence the debate.  
</P>
<P>
	``What we have continually done over the past six or seven years  
is when the president has moved troops into someplace, we have 
acquiesced, just nodded our heads and done it,'' House Speaker 
Dennis Hastert said. Congress later has to appropriate the funds to 
pay for the missions, but at that point, the argument is that to 
deny it would be to withhold support from American troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidents, Clinton included, promise to consult with Congress  
on military missions abroad. But not to seek clearance. Clinton 
ordered airstrikes against Iraq two days before he was impeached on 
Dec. 19, raids that delayed that vote and led the House to adopt a 
resolution backing U.S. forces in action. 
</P>
<P>
	When Clinton sent peacekeeping forces to Bosnia in late 1995,  
Congress approved in a resolution agreeing ``notwithstanding 
reservations'' and pointedly calling it the president's commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	That measure also cited Clinton's pledge to have the troops out  
in a year, which remains unmet, as the administration acknowledged 
when the deadline came and went. The force has been cut by about 
two-thirds, but more than 6,200 Americans are still there. 
</P>
<P>
	On Kosovo, Clinton is being more cautious, noting that he is in  
``sort of a double bind,'' given that experience and the demands 
for a deadline now. ``The exit strategy should be defined by the 
missions,'' he said, and added: 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't intend to make an open-ended commitment.''  
</P>
<P>
	That is not easily avoided when trying to make peace among the  
ethnic enemies of what was Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	In the House debate on Kosovo, one Republican invoked the  
judgment of British Prime Minister Benjamin Disraeli, who said in 
1878 that Serbia, Bosnia, and other Balkan provinces were a region 
of ``political intrigues, constant rivalries, a total absence of 
public spirit, hatred of all races, animosities of rival religions, 
and an absence of any controlling power. ... 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing short of an army of 50,000 of the best troops would  
produce anything like order in these parts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO would have more than 60,000 in those parts, with both a new  
Kosovo peacekeeping mission and the multinational force in Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:43:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's EPA Optimistic on Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Though still mired in a severe slump, Japan's  
economy is close to bottoming out -- largely as a result of 
government support measures, the Economic Planning Agency said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In its March report on the economy, the EPA described overall  
conditions as ``extremely severe,'' but said the economy's 
``downward movement continues to slow to a halt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a big change,'' said Takashi Omori, director of the  
national economic division at the agency's research bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	The official optimism comes just days after the EPA announced  
Japan's economy shrank for an unprecedented fifth straight quarter 
in the last three months of 1998, confirming the country remains in 
its worst recession in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the severity of the gross domestic product data, the  
optimism of Tuesday's report was in line with growing notions among 
many officials and investors that the worst of Japan's economic 
malaise may be over. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA was joined Tuesday by the Bank of Japan, which also  
slightly upgraded its assessment of the Japanese economy in a 
monthly report, saying it ``appears to have stopped 
deteriorating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The BOJ, however, said consumer sentiment remained cautious and  
corporate capital expenditures are expected to continue falling in 
the near term. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is still difficult to expect an immediate, self-sustained  
recovery in private demand,'' the central bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	One sign has been a recent jump in stock prices. With its close  
Monday at 15,779.60, the benchmark Nikkei stock index has risen by 
about 1,600 points in little more than a week, partly due to 
budding optimism. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to rising public works outlays resulting from fiscal  
stimulus packages, which the EPA said have made public investment 
``solid,'' government efforts to lower both long- and short-term 
interest rates have been successful, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, the EPA's report Tuesday was cautious, generally  
balancing every optimistic sign with a dose of pessimism. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although some areas are bottoming out, we must watch  
cautiously before we can say that the economic situation will get 
better from now,'' Omori said. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA said personal consumption has almost stopped declining  
but remains weak due to ``sluggish'' income. Because many companies 
have recently cut back on overtime hours and reduced bonus 
payments, disposable income has fallen in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to a weak wage outlook, the employment situation  
remains severe, the EPA said. Despite signs that the recent decline 
in the number of employed workers may be leveling off, the jobless 
rate remains at a record-high 4.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA also noted that corporate bankruptcies are sharply down,  
reflecting the effects of a government-backed loan guarantee system 
for small- and medium-sized companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate bankruptcies fell to 955 in February, down 40 percent  
from a year earlier and 5 percent lower from January. It was the 
first time in more than six years that the number fell below 1,000, 
according to private credit research agency Teikoku Databank Ltd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
