<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Banks' Profits Up 4.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's commercial banks had a seventh  
straight year of record profits in 1998 as earnings rose 4.7 
percent to $61.9 billion, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings at the country's 8,774 commercial banks were boosted by  
fee income, the FDIC said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Healthy, profitable banks support the economic growth and  
prosperity we enjoy today,'' FDIC Chairwoman Donna Tanoue said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The report came a day after news that Fleet Financial Group Inc.  
plans to acquire BankBoston Corp. for $16 billion in stock in a 
deal that will create the nation's eighth-largest bank and the 
dominant lender in New England. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDIC noted that U.S. banks' record profits last year came  
despite restructuring expenses related to mergers of some big 
institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case of Fleet and BankBoston, the combined bank will be  
faced with overlapping branches and administrative operations, and 
executives said it may have to cut as many as 5,000 jobs from the 
banks' total work force of 59,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDIC said nationwide bank profits declined 2.5 percent in  
the fourth quarter of 1998 to $14.9 billion, weakened by continued 
lower earnings from foreign operations and the restructuring costs 
from mergers. 
</P>
<P>
	A basic yardstick of bank profitability -- return on assets -- was  
an average 1.11 percent in the October-December quarter, down from 
1.24 percent a year earlier. A majority of banks, 54.6 percent, 
reported lower returns on assets than in the fourth quarter of 
1997, the FDIC said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
