<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stojko Ready for World Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	When Elvis Stojko arrives in Finland for next week's World  
Figure Skating Championships, he expects to be at 99 percent of 
capacity. Considering where he has come from, that's encouraging. 
</P>
<P>
	Not so encouraging is that, even at 100 percent, he might not be  
able to handle a strong field of Russians. 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko, a three-time world champion from Canada, has competed  
only sporadically -- and not particularly well -- since severely 
tearing a groin muscle at the Nagano Olympics 13 months ago. That 
he is even back on the ice at all is a measure of his courage. 
</P>
<P>
	So give Stojko his due -- just challenging defending champion  
Alexei Yagudin and the other Russians will be a major achievement. 
</P>
<P>
	``My doctors say it usually takes two years to heal from that  
and I was back on the ice in six months,'' Stojko said Monday. ``It 
was a real struggle and it still is. The time I had off put me 
behind all season; I've been behind everybody and trying to catch 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	``But this season is not about the results, but where I want to  
be and making people understand how tough it is. This injury has 
taken other athletes out of their careers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko wouldn't let that happen. Sure, he could have turned pro  
and headed off to one of the tours. Indeed, he will skate in the 
John Hancock Champions on Ice show for most of the spring. 
</P>
<P>
	But he still feels an emptiness, partly from not winning Olympic  
gold -- Stojko was the silver medalist in the last two games -- and 
mainly from the way he was so limited on skating's biggest stage in 
Nagano. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it has helped being more mature,'' said Stojko, who  
finished third against a weak field at the Four Continents 
championship two weeks ago. ``You learn more patience and I know my 
body is healing better and faster when I am patient. The doctors 
said they were so surprised I was back on the ice in six months, 
and it was because of the patience. You learn from pushing too hard 
and learn your limit of where you can stress the point. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to really pace yourself, and on those days you feel  
good, you might start to push yourself and you can set yourself 
back. You are all pumped up during the season and you want to do 
it, and you have to back off and listen to your body and what it is 
telling yourself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko's body told him to ease into things, so he skipped  
several internationals, including the Grand Prix finals last week. 
He qualified for that event by finishing sixth in the points 
standings, with a fourth-place spot at Skate America and a second 
at Skate Canada. When fully healthy, Stojko might have won both 
competitions. 
</P>
<P>
	But the results weren't a disappointment to him.  
</P>
<P>
	``The public expects it and the critics expect it,'' he said of  
winning, ``but you put it aside and focus on what you have to get 
done. I had to, so to speak, get back on top of my game and feel 
good about skating. Then I can get back to the results. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can only do what you are capable of at this time.''  
</P>
<P>
	What is Stojko capable of in Helsinki?  
</P>
<P>
	``I will go for it,'' he said, ``and pull out all the stops.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
