<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. McCain Slams Clinton Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration's inability to run  
a foreign policy worthy of the world's only superpower has 
endangered national security and left the United States more 
vulnerable to aggression from China, Republican presidential 
hopeful Sen. John McCain said today. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first major foreign policy speech of his emerging  
campaign for the White House, McCain, R-Ariz., also lambasted the 
administration for a lack of long-term strategy in dealing with 
North Korea, Iraq and the recurring violence in the former 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's tendency has been to ``put off resolution of  
the most difficult problems, often substituting photo-op diplomacy 
for meaningful action,'' said McCain, a member of the Senate Armed 
Services Committee and decorated Vietnam War veteran. 
</P>
<P>
	``Often evident in administration policies is a mystifying  
uncertainty about how to act in a world where we are the only 
superpower,'' McCain said in a speech prepared for delivery at 
Kansas State University in Manhattan, Kan. ``Nowhere has this 
confusion been more evident than in our relationship with China.'' 
</P>
<P>
	America must engage China and work toward bringing it into the  
international community, McCain said, but ``we must also prepare 
for the other contingency, that China emerges as the primary threat 
to American interests and values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has sacrificed national security for the sake  
of engaging China, he contended, and that has ``left the United 
States more vulnerable to a ballistic missile attack.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House has drawn fire recently over the  
administration's handling of allegations that China stole missile 
technology from a federal nuclear weapons lab in the 1980s. The 
issue has renewed questions about whether Clinton's policy was 
tainted by alleged illegal campaign contributions and the transfer 
of satellite technology that may have been used by the Chinese 
military. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, who is expected to formally declare for the GOP  
presidential nomination this spring, gave few specifics of what 
policies his administration would pursue. He did embrace a popular 
defense issue of the moment in Washington, calling for creation of 
a defense against ballistic missiles. 
</P>
<P>
	In a patriotic appeal, McCain called the United States ``the  
indispensable nation because we have proven to be the greatest 
force for good in human history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And he said the United States should never cede its leadership  
in the world to the United Nations. ``It has its uses, but to 
confer on that diverse organization the leading responsibility for 
international stability, freedom and justice will quickly render it 
incapable of any task whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain called for a ``rogue state rollback'' policy, which, like  
the so-called Reagan Doctrine, would support ``indigenous and 
outside forces that desire to overthrow the odious regimes that 
rule'' Iraq, North Korea and other ``rogue'' nations. 
</P>
<P>
	And sounding a personal note, McCain said he would bring his  
experience -- as a Navy fighter pilot who was a prisoner of war in 
Vietnam for 5 1/2 years -- to the role of commander in chief. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have seen war. What are today horribly compelling televised  
images were once the whole of reality for me,'' he said. When 
American troops are lost in the service of foreign policy, 
``whether others were involved in the decision or not, the 
president will be lonely man in a dark room when the casualty 
reports come in.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
