<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Account Surplus Surges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's trade surplus climbed 72.2 percent in  
January compared to the same month last year, reflecting sluggish 
demand for imports as the country struggles to pull out of a 
prolonged recession. 
</P>
<P>
	The current account surplus -- Japan's broadest measure of trade  
-- jumped to a non-seasonally adjusted $6.78 billion in the first 
month of the year, the finance ministry said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the biggest surplus ever for January, beating the $6.53  
billion surplus at the outset of 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Japan said its current account surplus for all of  
1998 surged 38.7 percent to an unprecedented $133.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists say Japan's surplus, a constant source of friction  
with trading partners such as the United States, may continue to 
balloon as consumers shy away from imported goods amid the 
country's worst recession since World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks to us premature to say that the surplus has peaked,''  
said Richard Jerram, an economist in the Tokyo office of ING Baring 
Securities (Japan) Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the pace of growth in the surplus is expected to slow  
over the next six months or so as the economy begins to bottom out. 
</P>
<P>
	``The very severe recession we saw in 1998 is easing,'' Jerram  
said, adding that this should boost demand for imports in the 
coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports in January dropped 24.5 percent to $20.2 billion,  
offsetting a 10.9 percent fall in exports to $27.7 billion, the 
government said. 
</P>
<P>
	The surplus in trade and services alone soared by more than 20  
times the amount in January of 1998 to $3.57 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The current account, which measures trade in merchandise,  
services, tourism and investment, is calculated by determining the 
difference between Japan's income from foreign sources against 
payments on foreign obligations. It excludes net capital 
investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
