<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Oppose China's WTO Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After years of stalemate, the Clinton  
administration said Monday it is beginning to see progress in talks 
aimed at admitting China to the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	But key senators warned Monday of strong congressional  
opposition to China's membership in the Geneva-based organization 
that sets the rules for world trade unless the Asian giant does 
more to lower barriers to sales of American farm and manufacturing 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our farmers will lose if we let China in the WTO with the  
attitude that we'll work out the details later,'' Sen. Charles 
Grassley, R-Iowa, told a panel of administration officials working 
on the issue. ``That's just what happened with Japan in the 1950s 
and we're still fighting for market access.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee's trade  
subcommittee, summoned the administration officials before his 
panel to emphasize Congress' concern about the negotiations, which 
have dragged on for years. 
</P>
<P>
	Special Trade Negotiator Peter Scher said the U.S. team, led by  
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky, was encouraged by 
recent negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	``During those meetings, China demonstrated a greater  
appreciation of what constitutes a commercially meaningful 
agreement for the United States,'' Scher told the senators. ``We 
are now engaged in a more substantial negotiation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the pace of talks has picked up in recent weeks, both  
Scher and Under Secretary of State Stuart Eizenstat stressed that 
the administration was not trying to reach an agreement in time for 
an April visit to Washington by Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to reporters in Beijing, Zhu said Monday that China was  
prepared ``to make the biggest concessions'' possible to gain 
membership in the 134-nation WTO, an economic prize China has long 
sought. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has the ability to block China's WTO  
membership until the country agrees to reduce barriers to American 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations concern what concessions China will be willing  
to make to meet U.S. demands. America's trade deficit with China 
hit an all-time high of $57 billion last year, the largest 
imbalance the United States has ever suffered with any country 
other than Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Comments by various senators underscored their unhappiness with  
this widening deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., contended China was engaged in a  
``shell game and charade'' that is keeping American farm products 
out of the country, while Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., expressed fears 
that the administration might lower its demands to strike a deal 
with China. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the fight over WTO membership, U.S.-China  
relations are being roiled over allegations of new human rights 
abuses and charges that a suspected spy at the Los Alamos, N.M., 
national lab gave China sensitive nuclear weapons information. 
</P>
<P>
	To emphasize congressional concerns, two key senators sent a  
letter to colleagues seeking co-sponsors for legislation that would 
require congressional approval before the administration could give 
the go-ahead for China's membership in the WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	``The continuing problems with Chinese human rights violations,  
espionage and possible technology transfers suggest that this is 
not an appropriate time for China to enter the WTO,'' wrote Foreign 
Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and Fritz 
Hollings of South Carolina, the Commerce Committee's top Democrat, 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise; Dow Up 67 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average resumed its  
advance on 10,000 today as a new round of corporate mergers sent 
stock prices higher. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow was up 67.44 at 9,943.79. The  
index of blue-chip stocks has flirted with 10,000 in recent 
sessions, coming within 42 points of that milestone Friday before 
giving up ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly higher today.  
</P>
<P>
	After stocks sputtered in the first hour of trading, analysts  
said the market appeared to be awaiting a catalyst powerful enough 
to spark a strong run past 10,000. By midday, announcements of 
several big mergers provided that spark 
</P>
<P>
	The $16 billion acquisition of BankBoston Corp. by Fleet  
Financial Group Inc. added some punch to the financial services 
sector. Shares of BankBoston rose 1 1/16. Fleet, however, slipped 1 
15/16 to 42 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, chemical giant DuPont Co. said it will pay $7.7  
billion to acquire 80 percent of Pioneer Hi-Bred International 
Inc., the world's largest seed corn company. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline stocks benefited from a new round of fare increases,  
which will push up the price of a business fare about 1 percent and 
a leisure fare about 3 percent. UAL Corp., which also indicated its 
first-quarter earnings will top analysts' expectations, was up 4 3/4 
at 71 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks were among the decliners today, having rallied Friday  
as world oil producers agreed to cut their output. Chevron was off 
9/16 at 84 1/8, and Exxon was off 1/4 at 73 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 10.12 at 1,304.71, and  
the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was up 34.26 at 
2,415.79. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 7-to-6 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 325.6 million 
shares, slightly off Friday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 3.29 at 614.83, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 0.03 at 721.18. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks rallied sharply overnight in Japan, as the Nikkei reached  
its highest level since last summer, rising 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.2 percent,  
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down .1 percent and France's CAC-40 was 
down 0.4 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 18:12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Calipari Fired by Nets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	John Calipari was fired today as coach of the New Jersey Nets, a  
once-promising team that quickly became one of the NBA's worst this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nets, who traded for star guard Stephon Marbury four days  
ago, have lost seven straight games to fall to 3-17. Only the Los 
Angeles Clippers (1-19) have a worse record. 
</P>
<P>
	The dismissal had been expected ever since Calipari met with  
team owners Finn Wentworth and Lewis Katz on Sunday after a 102-76 
loss in Miami. Calipari didn't accompany the team to Toronto but 
traveled there separately Monday and met briefly with the players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't really dealt with what I feel,'' said Calipari, who  
also was fired as team vice president. ``I wish I had the 
opportunity to finish the contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're with a good group of guys, it's the best thing in  
the world. But if you're with a few that are bad, it can be 
misery,'' he added, without specifying the ``bad'' players. 
</P>
<P>
	Calipari, in his third season with the Nets, had two years and  
$6 million remaining on his five-year, $15 million contract. He was 
offered a consulting job with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nets also fired assistant coaches Johnny Davis, Kenny  
Gattison and Jack Haley. 
</P>
<P>
	Nets assistant Don Casey will take over as interim coach, with  
his first game Tuesday night against the Raptors. He was the head 
coach of the Clippers during the 1988-89 season and has spent the 
last three seasons as Calipari's top assistant. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough,'' Casey said. ``Cal brought me in from Boston, he  
worked very hard with high energy and it just didn't work out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A protege of Boston Celtics coach Rick Pitino, Calipari had been  
given power to change the Nets from a laughingstock into a winner, 
and made some progress. But the Nets never rediscovered the 
chemistry that made them one of the most exciting young teams in 
the league last season, although injuries hurt this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The problems began on opening night when point guard Sam Cassell  
severely sprained his ankle. He missed all but two games after that 
and the Nets' offense sputtered with Eric Murdock and later Doug 
Overton at the point. All-Star center Jayson Williams has played 
with a broken nose and a hand injury. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey made the playoffs for the first time since 1994 last  
season. Although the Nets were swept by title-bound Michael Jordan 
and the Chicago Bulls, they played well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm proud that this organization is now thought of as a  
legitimate organization that it's very close to being big-time,'' 
Calipari said. ``In two and half years, look where it is. Four or 
five years ago no one wanted to stay here and no one wanted to come 
here. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now you've got an organization that's primed and set to have  
success, and if it's not with me, I'm okay with that. I don't own 
the team. I accept that. But I think in the end we changed the 
losing culture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Jordan's retirement, the Nets were seen as a potential  
successor as Eastern Conference champions. They featured an 
up-tempo style anchored by Keith Van Horn, Williams, shooting guard 
Kerry Kittles and Cassell, who was traded in the Marbury deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Marbury was expected to lift the sagging team. He made a strong  
debut Sunday with 21 points and five assists, but it was not nearly 
enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should look in the mirror and see what we can do,'' Kittles  
said. ``This is a new start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers reported Monday the Nets were courting former Chicago  
Bulls coach Phil Jackson to coach the team. Todd Musburger, 
Jackson's agent, has said he did not know if Jackson was leaning 
toward returning to coaching next season, as he has said in the 
past, or sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	Calipari, who helped turn Massachusetts into a national power as  
a college coach, was hired by the Nets on June 7, 1996, taking over 
one of the league's worst teams. The Nets had gone 30-52 the 
previous two seasons under Butch Beard. 
</P>
<P>
	In two-plus seasons as Nets coach, Calipari had a record of  
72-112. After a 26-56 record in his first season, he guided the 
Nets to a 43-39 record last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this is the worse thing to happen to me and my family in  
our lifetime, I have been a very very blessed man,'' Calipari said. 
``I came in as a college coach and was given authority to turn 
around an organization, to build a team that we wanted on the 
floor. In short order we got to the playoffs and it looked like 
things were going to be bright, we hit a big bump in the road and 
could not overcome it, and I'm disappointed in that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A low point came in his first year, when he was fined $25,000 --  
the largest fine ever levied against a coach by the league -- for 
calling reporter Dan Garcia of The Star-Ledger of Newark a 
``Mexican idiot'' during a heated argument after a practice. The 
coach has since apologized, maintaining it was an ill-advised 
attempt at humor. 
</P>
<P>
	When he was hired, Calipari said, ``You can walk into this and  
say: `How do I want this situation viewed?' I have that 
opportunity. I want to bet on myself. I don't need to bet on 
anybody else. I know me. That's what I wanted to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his first pro job, he lost that bet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
