<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Market Open on Good Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. government bond markets will be open a  
half-day on Good Friday, a day financial markets typically are 
closed, to give investors a chance to react to the release of 
unemployment statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department is scheduled to release March employment  
figures April 2, which coincides with the Christian holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, bond markets have followed other financial markets  
in the United States and many other countries in closing all day on 
Good Friday. U.S. stock and commodity markets will be closed April 
2, although government offices and most banks will be open. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond markets, however, are especially sensitive to employment  
and wage figures in the report due April 2 because they can signal 
trends in inflation and interest rates. For that reason, the Bond 
Market Association on Monday confirmed an earlier decision 
recommending bond markets be open until noon EST on Good Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``These figures are particularly important to the market,'' said  
Scott C. Rankin, assistant general counsel at Bond Market 
Association. ``The market trades on those figures, so we thought it 
a prudent measure to allow an abbreviated schedule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Economists expect another strong employment report, which could  
prompt a selloff, said Mary Dennis, a senior economist at Merrill 
Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	``The employment report traditionally has been the No. 1  
economic report to move the bond market,'' she said. ``Strong, is 
not good for the bond market, it could lead to a little bit of a 
selloff ... but any selloff would probably be seen as buying 
opportunity.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
