<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A winter storm that dumped close to 2 feet of snow in the East  
and mid-Atlantic states by morning worked its way into New England 
on Monday, while the rest of the country enjoyed mostly calm 
weather. 
</P>
<P>
	The heaviest snow Monday afternoon was in coastal areas of  
Maine. Lighter snowfall lingered in parts of New Jersey, Virginia 
and Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm dumped close to 2 feet of snow in some areas,  
including Bedford, Pa., which had 18 inches of snow. The 
Pennsylvania cities of Lewistown and Somerset had 15 inches and 14 
inches, respectively. Berkeley Springs, W.Va., also had 14 inches 
while 12 inches was recorded in parts of New Jersey, Maryland and 
Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Accumulations up to a foot were reported elsewhere.  
</P>
<P>
	The storm, just days before the first day of spring, closed  
schools, knocked out power and delayed travel on roads and at 
airports. 
</P>
<P>
	The remainder of the country saw mostly quiet weather Monday,  
with clear skies in the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley, south and west 
through the Gulf Coast and Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures rose in most areas, melting snow leftover from  
weekend storms. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the western United States saw calm, clear weather,  
except in southwestern California, where clouds and rain showers 
were reported. Some mountain snowfall also was reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a morning low of 11  
degrees in Jackson, Wyo., to an afternoon high of 75 degrees in Key 
West, Fla. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
