<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Companies To Combine Voice, Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE (AP) -- A collaboration between four major high-tech  
companies will allow people to listen to their e-mail on the 
telephone and read their voice mail on the computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Nortel Networks, Hewlett-Packard Co., Intel Corp. and Microsoft  
Corp. said Monday that the new systems are the first marketable 
results of their efforts to converge computers and telephones. 
</P>
<P>
	Their products, unveiled at The Tech Museum of Innovation in San  
Jose, will allow business customers to combine voice traffic and 
corporate data in a single, digitized network. 
</P>
<P>
	The team effort is expected to help advance the introduction of  
corporate networks that use Internet protocols to combine voice and 
data in one transmission system. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers are probably going to take this for granted, much in  
the same way we take cell phones and Internet access for granted,'' 
said John Armstrong, a Dataquest analyst in San Jose, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Armstrong said the convergence of voice and data, and  
the fact that ``the blue chip companies of communication'' are 
working on it, is going to propel technology that has been talked 
about a lot but seen little in the general marketplace. 
</P>
<P>
	The products mark the first in what are expected to be a whole  
new line of systems that converge voice and data from the four 
large firms, as well as from competitors like Lucent Technologies 
and Cisco Systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say that more than $2 billion will be spent by 2003 on  
systems that bring telephone and data lines together. 
</P>
<P>
	A large hurdle toward developing the systems has been voice  
recognition technology, a type of software that recently has 
improved to more smoothly enable computers to understand a user's 
spoken words and convert them into written text. 
</P>
<P>
	By this summer, small and medium businesses should be able to  
buy Hewlett-Packard communications and messaging software that 
allow business travelers to listen to voice mail messages or view 
faxes on their personal computers. They can also check e-mail from 
car phones, sort and track telephone calls through their personal 
computer and forward voice mails to colleagues without picking up a 
phone. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate officials said that a key attraction of the system is  
that it enables telephone lines to stay up even if computers crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``We recognize that this needs to be as constantly available as  
the telephone,'' said Hewlett-Packard president Lewis Platt. 
</P>
<P>
	The converging technology is also being used to allow people  
buying products over the Internet to click on an icon and have a 
live sales person speaking to them on their monitor. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the four companies are creating two research and  
testing laboratories in Santa Clara, Calif., and Brampton, Ontario. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:14:55 </DATE_TIME>
