<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  MLB Spring Training Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Kevin Appier and Alex Fernandez showed off their  
surgically-repaired right shoulders once again for scouts Monday, 
while Kerry Wood flew back to Chicago to check on his injured 
elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, last year's NL Rookie of the Year and a key to the Cubs'  
pennant hopes, had an MRI exam, not knowing how seriously his arm 
was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday was a rough day,'' Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said.  
``We just crossed some fingers and hoped the news was not going to 
be bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood's test results are not expected until Tuesday, the Cubs  
said. He missed the last month of the regular season with a sore 
elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	At Dunedin, Fla., scouts from more than a dozen major-league  
teams watched Appier struggle for the first time this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Appier, who missed almost all of last season with the injured  
shoulder, labored through a brutal first inning where he threw 29 
pitches and gave up two hits, three walks and two runs in the 
Royals' 6-5 win in 10 innings over a split-squad of Toronto Blue 
Jays. 
</P>
<P>
	But then he settled down the next three innings and gave up just  
one hit, making sure the dozen or so scouts who were on hand will 
be back to see the next outing of the Royals' career strikeout 
leader -- assuming a deal's not made before then. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first inning was ugly,'' said Appier, 31, whose $4.8  
million contract is too rich for the Royals to afford. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was getting way ahead of myself. I had trouble with my  
rhythm and my stuff was really erratic and inconsistent. After 
that, I made an adjustment and I was able to stay back and improve 
quite a bit. It improved a lot, but not all the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Winter Haven, Fla., Fernandez allowed six runs -- five earned  
-- in 1 2-3 innings as the Florida Marlins lost to the Cleveland 
Indians 13-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez, who missed the 1998 season following rotator cuff  
surgery, had allowed only one run in his first two starts this 
spring. The Indians strung together five consecutive two-out hits, 
including Omar Vizquel's two-run double and Jim Thome's home run. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians were among several teams with scouts at the game to  
mark the progress of Fernandez, who may be traded by the Marlins 
for younger, less expensive players if he proves healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	At Tampa, Fla., Joe Torre told his New York Yankees team that he  
would undergo surgery for prostate cancer on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Torre told the club he would be back ``soon,'' there's no  
telling when the World Series champions will have him in the 
dugout. Speculation has ranged from opening day on April 5 at 
Oakland to the All-Star break. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no clue,'' the 58-year-old Torre said. ``I will be  
taking a little extra time. I want to make sure when I come back, 
I'm strong enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre plans to leave the Tampa area on Wednesday. He expects to  
be in the hospital for 3-4 days after the surgery, and has not 
decided where he will recuperate. 
</P>
<P>
	At Vero Beach, Fla., Gary Sheffield, who said last week he is  
considering retirement, has left the Los Angeles Dodgers for a few 
days to take care of some personal business. 
</P>
<P>
	But the team said Monday that Sheffield had planned the trip  
more than a month ago and that it was unrelated to his comments 
this weekend about possibly ending his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Dodgers have known about this since before spring  
training,'' said John Olguin, a team spokesman. ``He'll be back 
Tuesday evening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other games:  
</P>
<P>
                        *Red Sox 13, Pirates 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Fort Myers, Fla., Scott Hatteberg hit two three-run homers  
and Pedro Martinez struck out seven in four innings. 
</P>
<P>
                     *Devil Rays 9, Blue Jays (ss) 8    	
</P>
<P>
