<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Railroad Mulls Cell Phone Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- The smoking car on trains is a thing  
of the past, but could the talking car be a feature of the future? 
</P>
<P>
	The Metro-North Commuter Railroad is considering designating  
separate cars for cellular phone users, who often intrude on the 
reading, sleeping and thinking of their fellow travelers by talking 
loudly into their little phones. 
</P>
<P>
	``For reasons that we can't figure out, people are hollering  
into their cell phones,'' Metro-North spokesman Dan Brucker said 
Monday. ``They're talking as if this were the beginning of the 
telephony age and you had to shout.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The railroad, which takes passengers between Grand Central  
Terminal and New York City's northern suburbs, lately has been 
averaging half a dozen complaints per week about loud phone calls, 
Brucker said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's happened to me a couple of times,'' James Said of White  
Plains said as he waited for a train to take him to work in New 
York. ``If the train is noisy and they have to shout, they're being 
obnoxious and they don't know it. You have to give them a look.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One woman complained to the railroad after finding herself  
surrounded by five people on cell phones. Another passenger 
resorted to turning on a tape recorder in front of a lawyer who was 
talking loudly to clients. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your attorney-client privilege is no longer privileged,'' the  
rider said. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the railroad is just asking cell-phone talkers to keep  
their voices down. But Brucker said one solution being considered 
is ``having a train car dedicated to cellular phone users -- an 
all-talking train car, the way we used to have a smoking car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, this raises little problems like free-speech  
issues,'' Brucker said. ``How do we enforce it, tell people they 
can't talk?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Nightingale of Greenburgh said he doesn't use his cell  
phone while riding the train to and from work in the city, but he 
stood up for the rights of those who do. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just talking,'' he said. ``Last time I looked you were  
allowed to talk on the train.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 01:14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parental Kidnapping on the Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- At the National Center for Missing &AMP; Exploited  
Children, the number of reported cases of missing children has been 
holding steady in virtually every category: runaways, stranger 
abductions, kids who are lost. 
</P>
<P>
	There's one big exception: children taken by their own parents.  
</P>
<P>
	Parental kidnappings have been rising steadily, said Ben Ermini,  
director of the missing children's division at the Virginia-based 
center. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see the increase in the number of breakups in marriages, so  
naturally as that occurs there's going to be a custody issue 
involving children,'' Ermini said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though many cases are quickly solved -- some turn out to be  
misunderstandings about when a parent was to return a child after a 
visit -- several parental abductions have grabbed headlines in the 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	One is the case of Stephen Fagan, accused of kidnapping his  
daughters from Massachusetts in 1979. The now-adult children, 
Rachael and Lisa Martin, were taken to Florida and told their 
mother was dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan maintains he took the girls to protect them from his  
former wife, a woman he described as an alcoholic and unfit mother. 
She denies the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnstable County officials are now searching for Julie Poner, a  
mother who disappeared more than a month ago with her 4-year-old 
twins just as she was to have turned them over to their father. 
</P>
<P>
	Ermini said the center only handles cases where the courts have  
established legal custody. In Poner's instance, a probate judge 
granted her ex-husband, Jiri, temporary custody of the twins -- a 
boy, Miro, and a girl, Allie. 
</P>
<P>
	In many cases of family abductions, the parent will argue that  
the child was taken for the child's own good. 
</P>
<P>
	Poner makes similar claims. In an interview with The Boston  
Globe last week, she said she feared her husband would have taken 
the children if she had not done so herself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe I'm the only mother who had to break the law  
to protect her children,'' she said, speaking from an undisclosed 
location. ``The children are much better off and safer and more 
secure than they would be if they were with their father.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From investigators' point of view, however, Poner is now a  
criminal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our opinion on this is very simple: We're just trying to find  
her and bring her back,'' said State Trooper Bob Knott. 
</P>
<P>
	The most recent national study, published in 1990, showed that  
163,200 children are abducted by relatives each year. That's out of 
932,000 adults and children reported missing last year, but the FBI 
said that between 85 and 90 percent of those were missing 
juveniles, most of whom were runaways. 
</P>
<P>
	In the majority of parental kidnapping cases, revenge against a  
former spouse is a primary motive, said Trooper Sarah O'Leary, who 
works for the state police's Missing Child Clearinghouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the child is well taken care of, the long-term  
psychological effects can be devastating, said Geoffrey Greif, 
associate dean at the University of Maryland School of Social Work. 
</P>
<P>
	Children who are taken by their parents may be told the other  
parent died, or that the parent doesn't love them anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	The children are frequently given new names, haircuts and  
clothing. They can't see their friends. They can't return to their 
school. They might even be discouraged from excelling in academics 
or sports because a star student athlete might have his or her 
picture in the local newspaper, Greif said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a report just completed for the U.S. Department of Justice,  
Greif interviewed so-called ``searching parents,'' whose children 
had been taken but were eventually recovered. The interviews took 
place an average of 10 years after the searching parent and child 
were reunited. 
</P>
<P>
	One-third of the parents said their now-adult children were  
having ``significant problems'' a decade after the abduction. 
</P>
<P>
	``Parents act thinking that they're doing things in the best  
interest of their kids,'' Greif said. ``But they're not looking 
down the road.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 16:53:03 </DATE_TIME>
