<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> El Paso Energy To Buy Sonat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- El Paso Energy Corp. is buying Alabama-based  
Sonat Inc. for $3.5 billion in stock to create the largest natural 
gas pipeline system in North America. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal allows El Paso Energy to ship gas from supply fields in  
California and Texas to growing markets in the South. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed with 40,000 miles of pipeline -- about 25 percent more than  
rival Enron Corp. -- El Paso Energy will be transporting nearly 
one-fourth of all the natural gas moved in the United States each 
day. It also gives the Houston-based company access to the 
expanding Florida electrical market. 
</P>
<P>
	``New gas-fueled power generation development is particularly  
active in these areas,'' said El Paso Energy chief executive 
William A. Wise. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Energy's Southern operations previously were centered  
around Tennessee Gas Pipeline Co., one of its five subsidiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the stock swap, El Paso Energy will assume about  
$1.9 billion in Sonat debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The original value of the deal was $3.9 billion, but El Paso  
Energy shares tumbled $3.68 3/4, or 10 percent, to close at $32.06 1/4 on 
the New York Stock Exchange after the announcement. Sonat shares 
slipped 43 3/4 cents to $29.62 1/2 on the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonat is currently based in Birmingham, Ala., and the  
headquarters of its interstate pipeline, Southern Natural Gas 
Company, will remain there. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonat chief executive Ronald L. Kuehn Jr. will become El Paso  
Energy's nonexecutive chairman until the end of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso energy had revenue of $5.78 billion last year, compared  
to $3.71 billion for Sonat. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
