<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 18:52:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Holyfield-Lewis Judge Defends Call </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Eugenia Williams trained to be a  
boxer. But she wound up going to modeling school, took up karate, 
got a job at city hall -- and became a boxing judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, she's the one on trial. And the verdicts aren't good.  
</P>
<P>
	Williams, one of three judges for Saturday's heavyweight  
showdown between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis, said Holyfield 
won. In doing so, critics say, she cheated Lewis of a unified title 
and gave the sweet science the foul smell of a fix. 
</P>
<P>
	Announcer Jim Lampley, who called the fight on pay-per-view,  
called the decision ``fraudulent.'' Lewis trainer Emmanuel Steward 
used the word ``fix.'' Lewis said he was robbed. 
</P>
<P>
	New York State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer called for an  
investigation, his spokesman blaming either ``incompetence'' or 
``tampering'' for the decision. New York Gov. George Pataki asked 
the state Athletic Commission to investigate the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``She is either biased, incompetent or worse,'' said HBO  
matchmaker Lou DiBella. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman at the eye of the storm spent Monday far from the  
glare of Madison Square Garden's ringside klieg lights, answering 
telephones at a cramped office in City Hall, where she works as a 
$39,200-a-year accounts clerk. 
</P>
<P>
	She had no apologies. No, she wasn't told to favor Holyfield.  
No, she wasn't biased. No, she isn't incompetent. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are entitled to their own opinion. I called what I saw.  
I have no problems with that,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A lifelong boxing fan, Williams trained to be a boxer as a  
teen-ager when she was growing up here. She quit because there were 
no opportunities for women fighters, turning to karate instead. She 
raised two children as a single mother and working her day job in 
the city's landlord-tenant relations office. 
</P>
<P>
	Active with amateur boxing programs at the Police Athletic  
League, she began judging amateur fights in 1983, then moved up to 
the pro ranks in 1989. Since then, she has judged more than 90 
fights, including 27 world title bouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, who won't give her age, has attended clinics and  
seminars put on by the sport's sanctioning bodies at least once a 
year throughout her tenure as a professional judge. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've worked with her many times, and I've never had a problem  
with her,'' said veteran judge Eva Shain of Fort Lee. ``I can't 
answer for what happened the other night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Lee, president and commissioner of the IBF, which appointed  
her to the $1,600 one-night gig, called Williams a top-flight 
judge. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has impeccable credentials,'' Lee said Monday. ``She  
attends the seminars and she takes an active part in them. I don't 
question her decision. She is a good professional. When I appoint 
her, I expect her to record what she sees. If she says that's what 
she saw, then I support her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What Williams apparently didn't see was the fifth round, when  
Lewis battered Holyfield mercilessly, landing 43 punches to 
Holyfield's 11. 
</P>
<P>
	She awarded that round for Holyfield, shocking most observers.  
</P>
<P>
	Williams scored the fight 115-113 for Holyfield. WBA judge  
Stanley Christodoulou of South Africa had it 116-113 for Lewis and 
WBC judge Larry O'Connell of Britain scored it 115-115. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone's jumping on poor Jean for the way she scored, but if  
you look at the British official, he scored two rounds even and if 
he hadn't scored the last round for Lennox Lewis, Evander Holyfield 
would have won the fight,'' Lee said. 
</P>
<P>
	So why did Lee join with the heads of the WBA and WBC in  
immediately ordering a rematch? 
</P>
<P>
	``The major concern we had was that we didn't get a unified  
title holder, which is what we wanted,'' said Lee. Asked if he 
thought Lewis won the fight, he said: ``I really didn't think so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Promoter Don King, who had the most to lose in a Holyfield loss,  
denied the fix allegation. ``Absolutely not. Why would it even be 
considered that I fixed the fight?'' he said on ABC's ``Good 
Morning America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, meanwhile, took the hubbub in stride.  
</P>
<P>
	``As long as you're honest, they can say what they want to say.  
I'm not the first (person) that disagreed with someone else. I 
guess I won't be the last.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 15:14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Balloon Team May Have Broken Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The Swiss-English balloonists trying to circle the  
world nonstop broke American millionaire Steve Fossett's distance 
record Monday and sped across the Pacific toward Mexico, their 
control center said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bertrand Piccard of Switzerland and Brian Jones of England  
finally reached a jet stream southeast of Hawaii after a seemingly 
endless float above the Pacific and picked up speed toward Mexico, 
which they hope to reach Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The center's computers showed that sometime Sunday evening, the  
Breitling Orbiter 3 broke the 15,203-mile distance record claimed 
by Fossett before he ditched near Australia last August. Their 
record claim must still be verified by the International Federation 
of Aviation. 
</P>
<P>
	By Monday morning, Piccard and Jones had traveled 16,511 miles  
since leaving the Swiss Alps on March 1, according to their control 
center. It said if all goes well, they could be over Mauritania on 
the West coast of Africa by Friday, completing their world circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Psychologically, the sight of the Mexican coast will be very  
important to the pilots, after having spent the last six days with 
nothing but water around them,'' said team meteorologist Luc 
Trullemans. 
</P>
<P>
	The balloon has been traversing the vast Pacific, sometimes  
slower than 30 mph, since it left China last Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The balloon entered the mouth of the subtropical jet stream 370  
miles south of Hawaii at 8 a.m. EST. Winds as fast as 134 miles an 
hour will push it toward Mexico, where it will likely cross the 
coastline near Guadalajara, the center said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The winds will decrease momentarily over the Caribbean, but  
will become very strong again from the Bahamas onwards,'' the 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Before entering the jet stream the team climbed onto the outside  
of their shiny red capsule to check systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took only two hours -- instead of six -- to undertake the  
necessary verifications and modifications,'' the statement said. 
``This ... enabled the craft to position itself perfectly for the 
jet stream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piccard and Jones passed the halfway point Saturday in their  
round-the-world bid. If they complete the circuit by making it back 
to North Africa they will have traveled more than 26,000 miles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 11:14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA OKs Device To Remove Blood Clots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- People who need to have blood clots removed  
from blocked arteries before angioplasty have a new alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	AngioJet, a medical device that removes these clots, was  
approved Monday by the federal Food and Drug Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The device, which was approved in 1996 for use in people  
undergoing dialysis, is expected to be especially helpful to heart 
patients who cannot use the so-called clot-busting drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Angioplasty is a widely used method for treating heart arteries  
that have been narrowed. Up to a half-million of the procedures are 
done annually in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In an angioplasty, a tiny balloon is threaded into the blocked  
artery, inflated to widen the blood vessel, then deflated and 
removed. Usually the widening remains and blood flow is increased. 
Sometimes a device called a stent is placed in the artery to help 
it stay widened. 
</P>
<P>
	But sometimes blood clots form in the narrowed areas and these  
can lead to heart attack or death. Currently these clots are 
treated with clot-removing drugs. However, some people cannot take 
the drugs, particularly those who have a predisposition to 
bleeding. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA said it gave the AngioJet System expedited review and  
approved it less than six months after receipt of a marketing 
application from the manufacturer, Possis Medical of Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike drugs, which move throughout the patient's system,  
AngioJet can be targeted at a specific area and is faster, said 
Rick Kravik, principal design engineer at Possis. 
</P>
<P>
	AngioJet is a coronary catheter containing a steel and a plastic  
tube. It shoots a jet of saline solution from the metal tube back 
into the tip of the plastic one, creating a vacuum that pulls along 
any blood clots. Treatment with this device takes about one minute, 
the FDA said. Once the blood clot is removed, the patient can then 
undergo angioplasty. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA said the manufacturer studied 731 people at 41 medical  
centers in the United States and Canada who had symptoms of heart 
artery blockage. 
</P>
<P>
	In one study, 180 were treated with AngioJet and 169 were  
treated with urokinase, a clot-busting drug. The study showed that 
AngioJet was similar in effectiveness to urokinase. 
</P>
<P>
	In another study, 105 patients who could not be treated with  
clot-busting drugs were treated with AngioJet. The study showed the 
device to be equally effective in these patients, the FDA said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 08:33:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Estonia Leader Sees NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Estonia expects next month's 50th anniversary  
NATO summit meeting in Washington to give a clear signal the 
alliance will admit new members in the early 2000s, President 
Lennart Meri said today. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he did not expect Russia to put up serious  
opposition to a second or third wave of NATO expansion although 
Moscow would be unhappy about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at the National Press Club, Meri said he would like the  
NATO summit to ``produce a road map elaborating what is required 
for membership, taking into account that NATO is not only a 
well-oiled military machine but an organization based on democratic 
values shared by big and small (member) nations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the summit simply reaffirms previous commitments to admit new  
members, Meri said, ``This will create more questions than 
answers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he planned to discuss Estonia's candidacy with Secretary  
of State Madeleine Albright. She said Friday, when the Czech 
Republic, Hungary and Poland formally joined NATO, that more 
members may be on the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO enlargement is not an event but a process,'' Albright  
said. ``It is our common purpose, over time, to do for Europe's 
East what NATO has already helped to do for Europe's West ... to 
continue erasing -- without replacing -- the line drawn in Europe by 
Stalin's bloody boot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Estonia is among a group of hopefuls waiting for the next round  
of enlargement that also includes Slovenia, Romania, Lithuania and 
Latvia. 
</P>
<P>
	In assessing the new applicants for membership, the allies  
examine criteria such as democratic development and whether they 
meet minimum military requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	Meri rejected arguments by critics of NATO expansion that it  
risks alienating Russia and could impede closer ties with Moscow. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Russian view of the alliance is changing and accession no  
longer is viewed with panic and animosity,'' Meri said. ``While 
Russia will not support a second or third wave of expansion it will 
not seriously oppose it. '' 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has called NATO's eastward push ``a movement in the wrong  
direction'' and cautioned against admitting the Baltic states of 
Estonia, Lithuania and Latvia that were once part of the former 
Soviet Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
