<DOCNO> APW19990315.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 07:44:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Helps Fight Vs. Florida Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAPLES, Fla. (AP) -- Wet weather gave a respite to crews battling  
fires in swampy southern Florida forest land that forced about 600 
people to flee their homes and blocked a major highway. 
</P>
<P>
	Until the rain arrived Sunday, flames had burned across an  
estimated 1,600 acres, damaging up 10 houses and threatening nearly 
200 other structures. A 20-mile stretch of Interstate 75, known as 
Alligator Alley, was closed as fires burned on both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rain put a damper on the fire,'' Lt. Paul France of the  
Florida Highway Patrol said in Naples late Sunday. ``It knocked it 
down enough to give firefighters a break.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Residents were allowed back into their homes and I-75 was  
reopened late Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	State fire officials kept a small crew of firefighters watching  
for flare-ups in the area bordering Big Cypress National Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind up to 40 mph had fanned the flames close to homes in Golden  
Gates Estates, seven miles west of Naples. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, France said, ``the wind took the fire so fast  
(firefighters) couldn't keep up with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two firefighters suffered second-degree burns.  
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the blaze wasn't known, officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 18:52:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Holyfield-Lewis Judge Defends Call </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
