<DOCNO> APW19990315.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 16:16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  No Major Trades for Pat Riley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- For the first time since taking over operations of  
the Miami Heat four years ago, Pat Riley will go an entire season 
without making a major trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami's silence at last week's trade deadline speaks volumes to  
the Heat players. It was another sign that Riley thinks he has the 
nucleus to win a championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very encouraging. I'm ecstatic,'' said forward P.J.  
Brown, a Riley favorite whose name frequently has popped up in 
trade rumors. 
</P>
<P>
	While other teams were reshaping themselves in the free-agent  
frenzy that followed the NBA lockout, Riley merely dabbled while 
making sure his ``core guys'' were taken care of. 
</P>
<P>
	And after the Heat shook off injuries and a 1-3 start to win 14  
of their next 16 games, there seemed hardly any reason to tinker 
with success -- particularly in the NBA's short 50-games-in-90-days 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're 15-5 and leading the Atlantic Division, it's hard  
to break up a team like that,'' Brown said. ``You'd be hard-pressed 
to make a move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that Riley hasn't pulled the trigger in the past. Each of  
his first three seasons in Miami was marked by a trade-deadline 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Riley turned over half his roster in one day with three  
trades, including a four-player swap which brought Tim Hardaway 
from Golden State. That came three months after he pried Alonzo 
Mourning from Charlotte in a six-player deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Riley sent three players to Dallas for  
high-scoring forward Jamal Mashburn. Last season brought the only 
deal that failed to pay dividends, when he traded Ike Austin to the 
Los Angeles Clippers for Brent Barry. 
</P>
<P>
	Then this year -- nothing. Even when word surfaced that Stephon  
Marbury could be available from Minnesota at the right price, 
apparently including Hardaway, Riley defended his nucleus. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people are talking about Timmy, they are talking about an  
important part of what we built,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley did his tinkering around the edges early, signing guard  
Terry Porter and forward Clarence Weatherspoon as free agents to 
strengthen his bench. Both have paid off tremendously. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter, in his 14th season, has averaged 11.0 points per game,  
working both as Hardaway's backup and teaming with him as the 
shooting guard. He went 5-for-5 from the floor for 14 points in 
Sunday's 102-76 win over New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Weatherspoon, a seventh-year pro, is averaging 9.5 points and  
6.4 rebounds per game. He has 31 points and 14 rebounds in his past 
two games, hitting 13 of 15 field-goal attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got two veteran players that have produced since they  
got here,'' Riley said. ``Our bench has given us a huge lift. Our 
veterans simply know how to play basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the Heat still figure to improve down the stretch. Mashburn  
and Voshon Lenard have missed virtually the entire season with 
injuries, and their return will provide a scoring boost. 
</P>
<P>
	Mashburn, out the past five weeks with a hyperextended left  
knee, is expected to return to practice within a week and should be 
activated by the end of the month. Lenard, diagnosed with a stress 
fracture in training camp, figures to return in time for the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``With those guys returning, it'll improve our team,'' Brown  
said. ``We're just scratching the surface right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Heat's current makeup has been good enough to lead the  
Eastern Conference. Next up: catching Utah and Portland for the 
best record in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're thinking about winning a championship, then we're  
thinking about getting the best record,'' Riley said. ``Why not?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 22:42:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Learn Dangers of Manure Gas / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEOSTA, Iowa (AP) -- Iowa farmers can learn about the dangers of  
swine manure gas in a new building a state company has donated to 
Northeast Iowa Community College. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the $70,000 swine building, The Double L Group,  
which manufactures such buildings, is donating the time of engineer 
Matt Robert, who will teach classes held at the National Education 
Center for Agricultural Safety on the college's campus in Peosta, 
Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The hands-on training in the building will help prevent deaths  
and unnecessary exposure to harmful gases, said Sam Steel, managing 
director of the safety center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Farmers don't understand how gas works in the environment,''  
Steel said. ``There's new technology in buildings that farmers 
don't always keep up with. In the old days, pigs were outside and 
manure was dispersed and decomposed. Now, it's condensed and 
confined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Solids in manure held in a pit under a swine building settle to  
the bottom of the slurry. When farmers agitate the manure to lift 
and combine the solids for removal from the pit, a spike or plume 
of hydrogen sulfide can rise from the pit and overtake the farmer 
and his hogs. 
</P>
<P>
	People who have long-term exposure to manure gas may be more  
susceptible to bronchitis, pneumonia and other respiratory 
infections. 
</P>
<P>
	They may have decreased lung function and emphysema-type  
symptoms, said Charlotte Halverson, a nurse at the center. ``Once 
you've had exposure, you lessen your ability to fight off 
infection,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers won't find protection by wearing a simple dust mask.  
They need to wear fitted respiratory masks. 
</P>
<P>
	Swine will be brought in only for demonstrations and will not be  
kept overnight in the building, because the center borders a 
residential area. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert said training sessions in the swine building will show  
farmers easy steps and simple things they might overlook that could 
help ensure their safety. 
</P>
<P>
	``A little gas sensor on you will tell you about gases. Just  
being aware will help. It's easier showing them than giving them a 
pamphlet,'' Robert said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	VINTON, Iowa (AP) -- Three farmers who have already been selling  
their soybeans directly to the Japanese market have taken another 
step toward capturing more of the food processing dollar for 
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	They've opened a soy processing plant.  
</P>
<P>
	Iowa Soy Specialties is operated by soybean growers Dan Van  
Steenhuyse, 46, of Mount Auburn; Homer Showman, 46, of Shellsburg 
and Marlyn Jorgensen, 59, of Garrison. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal of the company, said Showman, is to make nutritious  
soybeans palatable for people. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't have to change their diet and eat tofu,'' he said.  
People can add the healthful benefits of soy to their diet by using 
flour in familiar foods and by using textured soy protein as meat. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not trying to hurt livestock producers but add to meat  
the benefit of soy. If you're vegetarian, it's great,'' Showman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's retail products are low-fat soy flour and dried,  
texturized soy protein. One pound of texturized soy protein, when 
reconstituted, is equal to five pounds of meat in volume. 
Texturized soy protein has a shelf life of seven years in its dried 
form. 
</P>
<P>
	The company provides several recipes for its soy products,  
including a smoothie made with yogurt, fruit and soy flour. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Steenhuyse, Showman and Jorgensen were founders of Iowa  
Producers Cooperative, a specialty crop organization. When the 
three men formed Iowa Soy Specialties in 1997, they invited others 
to share the risk and now have 28 soybean grower-investors and 
seven other investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The grower-investors sell beans to the plant and receive the  
market price plus a small premium. Van Steenhuyse says they also 
will receive dividends when the company makes a profit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 16:16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  No Major Trades for Pat Riley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
