best record in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're thinking about winning a championship, then we're  
thinking about getting the best record,'' Riley said. ``Why not?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 13:15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Herzog Criticizes Baseball Owners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- Baseball owners hunger for money as if they  
were ``junkies panting after crack,'' Whitey Herzog says in his new 
book. 
</P>
<P>
	The former manager also compares commissioner Bud Selig to  
reliever Neil Allen in ``You're Missin' a Great Game,'' an often 
off-color account of his advice for baseball's leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	He assails interleague play, the presence of the designated  
hitter in one league and not the other and the gulf between the 
haves and the have-not teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be honest with you,'' Herzog says. ``A lot of things  
about the big-league scene today make me want to throw up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Almost nothing is sacred. Herzog, famous for the jackrabbit  
style of play in the 1980s that was nicknamed ``Whiteyball,'' even 
takes a swing at the great home run chase. 
</P>
<P>
	He notes that all of that thunder didn't do the Cardinals or  
Cubs much good. The Cardinals finished 19 games out in the NL 
Central even with Mark McGwire's record 70 home runs, and the Cubs 
barely made the NL wild card and then got swept in three games by 
the Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was good for the game -- for a year,'' Herzog said.  
</P>
<P>
	Herzog says owners don't pay enough attention to the game on the  
field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I used to go to owners' meetings for Gussie Busch, and it's  
the same today,'' he writes. ``The only thing they ever talked 
about was money. How can we raise more revenue? How can we get more 
money? That's why we have an extra tier in the playoffs now, that's 
why we have interleague play -- more revenue. It's why we have the 
DH, 30 teams and everything we have in the game. More revenue, more 
revenue! It's junkies panting after crack.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He says Selig is a good person and adds he used to bounce ideas  
off him in the press box. 
</P>
<P>
	``How many guys sell enough Chevys in their lifetime to purchase  
a major league ball club?'' Herzog writes. ``You can't be a dim 
bulb and do that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see Bud a little bit like the way I saw Neil Allen when I  
got him for the Cardinals. I'd rather have had Bruce Sutter as my 
closer, but he'd gone to Atlanta; it was over, so why cry about it? 
I didn't feel perfect about Neil, but he was the best I had, so I 
handed him the ball and hoped for the best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Put Herzog in charge, and one of his first acts would be doing  
away with interleague play, which creates travel problems and 
affects competitive balance. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps because he's still smarting from losing the 1987 World  
Series in the Metrodome, he'd put the World Series at a permanent, 
warm-weather, neutral site. 
</P>
<P>
	His example is Nashville, where a seven-game series with no  
travel could be contested in eight days and teams would have to use 
more of their rotation than is the postseason norm these days. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the Metrodome, Herzog also thinks Wrigley Field, Fenway  
Park and Coors Field are unfair to visiting teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``The purists say it would take too much away from the team's  
hometowns,'' Herzog said in the book, co-written with Jonathan 
Pitts. ``It'd take away the charm of one league playing for all the 
marbles in the other league's stadium. However, some of these 
places guarantee that the field, not the players, will decide some 
championships.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Herzog's favorites are all on display. Casey Stengel, his first  
manager, is also the subject of the first chapter. 
</P>
<P>
	He states his case that former teammate Roger Maris belongs in  
the Hall of Fame, just like the best all-around player he ever 
managed, George Brett. 
</P>
<P>
	Herzog has a long memory. He devotes a lot of space to rehashing  
the 1985 I-70 World Series and the infamous call by umpire Don 
Denkinger, and to his rebuilding job that led to the Cardinals' 
strong run in the '80s. 
</P>
<P>
	Regarding the '85 Series, he wishes that he'd taken his team off  
the field in protest, and that maybe if he had there would be 
instant replay in the World Series today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd have been fined, suspended, maybe ... run out of  
baseball,'' Herzog said. ``In other words, it would've been 
everything my game needed to kick it in the rear.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
