<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 05:45:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DuPont buying rest of Pioneer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Chemical giant DuPont Co. is paying $7.7  
billion for 80 percent of Pioneer Hi-Bred International Inc., the 
world's largest seed corn company. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, which was announced today, boosts DuPont's 20 percent  
stake in the seed company to full ownership and is DuPont's first 
deal since it announced last week it wanted to increase its 
presence in the life sciences. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is expected to be completed this summer.  
</P>
<P>
	Under the terms of the agreement, Pioneer shareholders will  
receive $40 per share in cash and stock. 
</P>
<P>
	That is a 16.5 percent premium over Pioneer's stock price on  
Friday when it climbed 40 percent after the companies disclosed 
they were in talks on a possible business combination. 
</P>
<P>
	The boards of directors of both companies have approved the  
transaction. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both companies are customer focused with compatible cultures  
and values,'' said Charles O. Holliday, Jr., DuPont chairman and 
chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the combination of DuPont's agricultural businesses and  
Pioneer's seed business would create a $5 billion agricultural 
enterprise. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont's life sciences business totaled $4.3 billion in sales  
last year -- less than 20 percent of the company's total sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Pioneer will be a wholly owned subsidiary of DuPont, doing  
business under the Pioneer name and will remain headquartered in 
Des Moines. It has 5,000 employees worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``Crop genetics offers tremendous potential for meeting the  
needs of farmers, agriculture and consumers around the world,'' 
said Charles S. Johnson, who will continue to lead Pioneer as 
chairman, president and chief executive. ``Bringing the talents and 
resources of our two companies more closely together will ensure we 
deliver that potential to the market and do it quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont's business moves have been swift in the life sciences  
area the last few years. Two years ago, it spent $1.7 billion to 
buy 20 percent of Pioneer Hi-Bred, with the companies creating a 
joint venture for crop research. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, DuPont spent $2.6 billion to buy out Merck Co.'s  
share in a joint venture between the two, creating DuPont 
Pharmaceuticals. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
