<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 20:05:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers 1, Capitals 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Enrico Ciccone scored at 11:44 of the third  
period to lift the Washington Capitals into a 1-1 tie with the New 
York Rangers on Monday night in a game between two teams fighting 
for a playoff berth. 
</P>
<P>
	The tie moved the Rangers one point behind the Boston Bruins in  
the race for the eighth and final spot in the NHL's Eastern 
Conference. The Capitals closed within eight points of Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	With New York nursing a 1-0 lead, Michal Pivonka won the faceoff  
in the Rangers' end, Tom Chorsky nudged the puck back to the left 
point and Ciccone beat Mike Richter with a low shot to the far side 
of the net. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams had excellent scoring opportunities in the overtime.  
Capitals goaltender Olaf Kolzig, who stopped 22 shots, made the 
save of the game on a one-timer from the slot by Scott Fraser with 
just over a minute left. Richter made 33 saves for New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Roman Ndur scored his first NHL goal to give the Rangers a 1-0  
lead. Ndur took a pass from Fraser just behind the left circle and 
blasted a slap shot through a group of players past Kolzig at 14:33 
of the first period. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers made the goal stand up into the third period despite  
managing only four shots in the first period and one through the 
first 11 minutes of the second. New York killed off a two-man 
Washington advantage for 40 seconds, and Richter was brilliant, 
making key saves on Jaroslav Svejkovsky in the first and Pivonka in 
the second. 
</P>
<P>
	New York has a 6-2-2 record in the 10 games since Wayne Gretzky  
was sidelined with a neck injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the game, the Rangers announced that the team's leading  
scorer, Adam Graves, had signed a multi-year contract. Graves was a 
potential free agent in the coming off-season. Terms of the 
agreement were not disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
