<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:47:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC President Suspects Revolt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- IOC president Juan Antonio  
Samaranch suspects officials within his own staff are trying to 
force him out, Olympic sources told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch, who faces a crucial vote of confidence this week at a  
special International Olympic Committee general assembly, has told 
close associates in recent days ``there is someone in the house'' 
working against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has said he believes these elements are capitalizing  
on the corruption crisis engulfing the IOC to try to unseat him and 
install a new leadership, the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources, who spoke to the AP on condition of anonymity, have  
firsthand knowledge of Samaranch's concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Suspicion of a palace revolt marks a dramatic shift in  
Samaranch's position. He previously told close aides and friends he 
believed his IOC lieutenants were completely loyal. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was the first time I've heard him say this,'' one source  
said Monday. ``He has always stressed that the house was totally 
with him and there was no plot in the house.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The house refers to the Chateau de Vidy, the IOC's  
administrative headquarters on the shores of Lake Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources said Samaranch did not identify who or how many  
might be involved in the suspected campaign. He will not be 
available for comment until after the general assembly on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has come under attack from critics outside the IOC in  
the wake of the vote-buying scandal stemming from Salt Lake City's 
successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	While critics have called for Samaranch's resignation, the  
78-year-old Spaniard has insisted he intends to serve out the rest 
of his term until 2001 if IOC members continue to support him. 
</P>
<P>
	The general membership is expected to overwhelmingly endorse  
Samaranch on Wednesday at the extraordinary session called to deal 
with the Salt Lake crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	But there has been increasing speculation, including among IOC  
officials, about the possibility of Samaranch stepping down before 
2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal last week quoted ``senior IOC  
officials'' as saying Samaranch might announce that he would step 
down later this year and stay on in a leadership role -- possibly a 
transitional co-presidency -- until the 2000 Sydney Games. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC leaders have denied the story, but the report created more  
suspicion and intrigue behind the scenes. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from endorsing Samaranch, the assembly will be asked to  
ratify the expulsions of six members accused of accepting cash or 
other improper inducements from Salt Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	A two-thirds majority of the expected total of 91 members is  
required for expulsion. If any of the expulsions are rejected, it 
would mark a critical defeat for Samaranch and his executive board. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're assuming the session will agree with the  
recommendations,'' Richard Pound, the IOC vice president from 
Canada, said. ``I hope it's understood we have to do this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The assembly will also be asked to approve a new bidding and  
selection procedure for Olympic cities, the creation of an 
independent ethics commission and the appointment of a reform panel 
to study long-term structural changes to the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	In other developments Monday:  
</P>
<P>
	-- the executive board backed Anita DeFrantz, the American IOC  
vice president. Dave Johnson, the former No. 2 official in the Salt 
Lake bid, told the New York Times last week that DeFrantz ``knew 
everything'' about the city's improper inducements. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz has denied Johnson's claims. Pound said the matter was  
discussed briefly at Monday's board meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``As of right now, the account we have from Anita is she did not  
know and we are satisfied with that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Pound said his inquiry commission has no evidence yet to  
investigate reports that Australian member Phil Coles received 
thousands of dollars worth of jewelry from an official of the 1996 
Athens bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles is under pressure in Australia to resign from the board of  
directors of the 2000 Sydney Games organizing committee. That 
position is contingent on his continued IOC membership. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Pound said the IOC is ready to open its books to the public.  
</P>
<P>
	-- Pound said the executive board has reached apparent consensus  
on the formula for choosing the 2006 Winter Games site. 
</P>
<P>
	In a process that would take place on the same day at the June  
session in Seoul, South Korea, a 15-member body would be appointed 
to narrow the six-city field to two finalists. The entire IOC 
membership would then vote to select the winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
