<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Sen. John Chafee Retiring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Sen. John Chafee, an influential  
moderate Republican first elected in 1976, announced today he will 
retire next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Chafee, 76, said he will not seek a fifth term in 2000.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to try something else,'' Chafee said at a news  
conference at the Rhode Island State House. His voice broke when he 
said: ``I want to come home.'' He was flanked by his wife, children 
and grandchildren, and by Gov. Lincoln Almond, a fellow Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican Party could end up losing Chafee's Senate seat in  
next year's election. Rhode Island is predominantly Democrat, with 
just 8 percent of voters registered as Republicans, and at the 
moment the state GOP does not have a strong candidate to run for 
Chafee's job. 
</P>
<P>
	``Senator Chafee seems to have found me a very big job,'' said  
Joan Quick, state party chairwoman. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans now hold a 55-45 edge in the Senate, but must defend  
19 seats next year, compared with 14 for the Democrats. The 19 GOP 
seats include many held by first-termers who were pulled into 
office on the strength of the GOP landslide in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one other Republican has announced plans to retire so far:  
Florida Sen. Connie Mack, who is leaving after two terms. Three 
Democratic senators have announced retirement plans: Richard Bryan 
of Nevada, Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey and Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Providence and a scion of one of Rhode Island's most  
powerful families, Chafee is perhaps the most popular Republican in 
state history. 
</P>
<P>
	Considered one of the Senate's most liberal Republicans, Chafee  
is the senior member in a dwindling group of Republican moderates, 
working to forge compromises in divisive areas such as health care 
and child care. He is chairman of the Environment and Public Works 
Committee, where he is a key voice for environmental protection and 
conservation in his party. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, he praised Senate colleagues who have joined him in  
bipartisan efforts to get things done, and praised the 
predominantly Democratic voters who sent him to Washington, saying, 
``They seek, as I do, bipartisan solutions to problems, rather than 
partisan gridlock.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his Senate service, his political resume includes  
terms as state representative, governor and secretary of the Navy. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of Democrats have been mentioned as possible candidates  
for Chafee's seat. They include Rhode Island Secretary of State 
James Langevin; Myrth York, who has lost two gubernatorial races to 
Almond; and Rep. Robert Weygand. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's other congressman, Rep. Patrick Kennedy, has said he  
will remain in the House because of his increasing influence there. 
Kennedy was recently named chairman of the Democratic Congressional 
Campaign Committee. Nonetheless, some pundits wonder whether 
Kennedy, son of Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts, will be able 
to resist making a run for Chafee's seat. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Republican side, Lincoln Chafee, the senator's  
45-year-old son who is mayor of Warwick, said he is considering 
running for his father's seat. He declined to elaborate on whether 
he is forming an exploratory committee or taking other steps. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can we talk about this tomorrow?'' he said. ``Today is his  
day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chafee was elected governor in 1962. He was re-elected in 1964  
and 1966, both by the largest margins in state history at the time, 
but was defeated when he sought a fourth term in 1968. Chafee was 
appointed secretary of the Navy in 1969, a position he held until 
1972. 
</P>
<P>
	He lost a 1972 Senate race to Democrat Claiborne Pell. But he  
won an open Senate seat in 1976, and was re-elected three times 
after that. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:32:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CIA To Probe China Spy Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The CIA named a retired admiral on Monday to  
review its own damage assessment into how much nuclear weapons 
technology, if any, was lost to China through a suspected spy 
working at the Los Alamos, N.M., National Laboratory. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment of retired Adm. David Jeremiah appeared aimed at  
adding an air of independence to an inquiry buffeted by partisan 
politics. Republicans have accused the Clinton administration of 
acting too slowly when the potential espionage problem emerged. 
</P>
<P>
	CIA Director George Tenet briefed the Senate Intelligence  
Committee on the ongoing inquiry, and afterward the top Republican 
and Democrat on the committee agreed that additional security 
changes need to be made at the nation's weapons laboratories. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee Chairman Richard Shelby, R-Ala., said the  
administration should consider a moratorium on scientific exchanges 
in which foreign scientists visit the national laboratories and 
U.S. scientists from the labs go overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is perhaps just the tip of an iceberg. We need security  
at our national labs. ... It has been too loose, too long, and it's 
too important,'' Shelby said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Kerrey D-Neb., the committee's vice chairman, cautioned  
that the espionage case in question involved not an exchange of 
scientists but a potential breach by a single employee. But he 
agreed that security at the labs must be revamped. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's obvious that considerably more needs to be done,'' Kerrey  
said. ``This is something that is potentially a very serious 
situation that has damaged the security of the United States of 
America considerably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tenet said Jeremiah will provide an independent review of the  
work being done now by a multiagency intelligence team. It is the 
second such assessment Jeremiah has been asked to do. Last year, a 
study led by Jeremiah identified problems that contributed to the 
intelligence community's failure to adequately warn of nuclear 
testing by India. 
</P>
<P>
	``Admiral Jeremiah is the perfect person to lead such a  
review,'' Tenet said. ``His credentials are impeccable and his 
credibility is unquestioned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeremiah's panel of outside experts will examine work begun in  
mid-February within the intelligence community about whether a 
Taiwanese-born scientist who worked at the Energy Department's Los 
Alamos laboratory provided China with technology that could be used 
in developing a multiwarhead nuclear weapon. China has yet to field 
such a weapon, but a document obtained by U.S. intelligence in 1995 
indicated that China had knowledge of technology similar to the 
W-88, a U.S. multiwarhead nuclear weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	A Taiwanese-born computer scientist, Wen Ho Lee, was fired from  
his job at Los Alamos a week ago amid suspicions that he leaked 
secrets to the Chinese in the 1980s. Lee has not been charged with 
any crime, and Newsweek magazine said the FBI now believes it has 
virtually no chance of making a case against him. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI began its investigation in 1996, and Republicans have  
accused the administration of dragging its feet by allowing Lee to 
continue working at Los Alamos long after the initial suspicions 
arose. 
</P>
<P>
	The intelligence damage assessment was ordered based on the  
recommendation in a classified report by a House select committee 
headed by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., which looked into a 
variety of charges that sensitive U.S. weapons and missile 
technology has been leaked to China. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate is holding hearings this week on the espionage case  
involving the Los Alamos nuclear weapons lab. The allegations date 
to the mid-1980s but only recently came to light. In the House, 
members are demanding public release of the classified, 700-page 
Cox committee report on technology transfers to China. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., in an interview on  
PBS' ``NewsHour with Jim Lehrer,'' also called for declassifying 
the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said he had not been reassured by what administration  
officials have been saying about the case. ``What we need is 
answers. What happened? Why wasn't more done sooner? ... Most 
important, what are we going to do about it?'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Beijing Monday, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji rejected  
allegations China stole U.S. nuclear weapons secrets and said 
U.S.-Chinese ties were being sacrificed to partisan struggles in 
Washington. Despite the nuclear secrets scandal, Zhu said he still 
planned to travel to the United States in April. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think my visit to the United States will bring me into  
a minefield, but I do expect to encounter some hostile or some 
unfriendly atmosphere there,'' Zhu said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Monday the espionage  
allegations are certain to come up during Zhu's visit ``as part of 
the broad relationship we have with China.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``All of these issues will be on the table,'' Lockhart said.  
``This is an important issue and it's important we have addressed 
it the way we have.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 15:55:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Story Absolves Cleland in Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For 31 years, Max Cleland has blamed himself  
for the grenade explosion that cost him both legs and an arm in 
Vietnam, thinking he accidentally dropped the grenade as he jumped 
from a helicopter near Khe Sanh. 
</P>
<P>
	But now, a former Marine corporal has come forward to tell the  
Georgia senator a different story. 
</P>
<P>
	David Lloyd, who says he was one of the first to reach Cleland  
after the explosion, said in an interview Monday that he treated 
another soldier that day who was sobbing uncontrollably: ``It was 
my grenade. It was my grenade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lloyd said he doesn't know the other soldier's identity, but he  
was an Army private who had gotten off the helicopter just after 
Cleland and who suffered minor shrapnel wounds in the explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I put maybe 20 battle dressings on him and the whole time he  
was crying, but he wasn't crying from the pain,'' said Lloyd. ``He 
was crying more from knowing it was his grenade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Lloyd's story has not been independently verified, Cleland  
said he met with the Annapolis, Md., man last week, viewed pictures 
and maps he brought back from Vietnam and has no reason to doubt 
his account. A Marine Corps spokesman said it would take several 
days to confirm Lloyd's military service. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes more sense than anything I've heard,'' Cleland,  
D-Ga., said in an interview Monday. He never knew the names of any 
of the soldiers or corpsmen who aided him on the battlefield. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleland was an Army captain in the Signal Corps when he was  
wounded near Khe Sanh on April 8, 1968. His radio team had gotten 
off a helicopter to help establish a relay station on a hill when 
he spotted the grenade and reached for it just before it exploded. 
</P>
<P>
	While he was never certain where the grenade came from, Cleland  
thought it had fallen from his own belt. 
</P>
<P>
	It was ``easy after Vietnam to blame yourself as the  
victim...,'' the senator said. ``What poured salt into my wounds 
was the possible knowledge that it could have been my grenade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lloyd said he always knew Cleland was the soldier crippled that  
day. But until he saw the senator on a cable TV show two weeks ago 
telling how Navy corpsmen had saved him, he hadn't known Cleland 
was unaware the grenade that exploded had come from another 
soldier. 
</P>
<P>
	A few days after contacting Cleland's office, the two spoke by  
phone. They had lunch together last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't believe it,'' said Cleland. ``For 31 years you have  
in your mind a certain set of circumstances that you've pretty much 
come to terms with and all of a sudden a call like this out of the 
blue changes everything for you.... It sent cold chills down my 
spine, caused me to relive the whole thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleland speculated that the soldier Lloyd treated had joined his  
unit just before the fateful helicopter ride. He said he'd like to 
learn his identity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd tell him, `Don't feel guilty. We were all in situations  
where this could have happened to any of us. Live life the best you 
can, which is what I'm trying to do. There should not be any guilt 
there. It was just a tragic accident.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleland said he plans to accept Lloyd's invitation for a fishing  
trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Vietnam War requires a great deal of healing afterwards,''  
he said. ``The deepest wounds and scars we carry are the ones that 
are not visible, and I've had a deep wound and scar about this all 
my life. I think this will help me move on to a little deeper 
healing than I was experiencing.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
