<DOCNO> APW19990315.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Foreign Policy Ranked No. 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans rank President Clinton No. 1 among  
postwar U.S. presidents on foreign policy success, up from eighth 
place in the middle of his first term, according to a poll released 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, conducted every four years by the Gallup  
Organization for the Chicago Council on Foreign Relations, shows 
support for a strong defense and for efforts to fight terrorism and 
prevent the spread of weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
<P>
	Less support is expressed for deployment of U.S. forces abroad.  
And, although the poll finds that more Americans measure strength 
in terms of economic than military power, there is less 
apprehension over economic competition from Japan or Europe than in 
previous surveys. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirroring high public satisfaction with the economy, the survey  
shows widespread contentment in the conduct of U.S. foreign 
affairs, despite rising Republican challenges to Clinton on his 
dealings with the Kosovo crisis, China's human rights performance, 
North Korea's weaponry programs, faltering Middle East peace 
efforts, Iraq's intransigence and other foreign policy issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey shows no indication that ordinary Americans view any  
of these as critical issues. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked to list the two or three biggest foreign policy  
problems facing the country, the most common response among the 
public, at 21 percent, was: ``I don't know.'' That was followed by 
mainly global issues: terrorism (12 percent), the world economy (11 
percent), balance of payments (10 percent) and the Middle East 
situation (8 percent.) 
</P>
<P>
	Gallup, which has conducted the survey in a similar manner since  
the 1970s, interviewed 1,507 men and women in October and November. 
The margin of error was plus or minus 3 percentage points. 
Separately, the pollsters interviewed 379 policy leaders, including 
members of Congress, administration officials, international 
business figures and members of the news media. 
</P>
<P>
	In the leaders poll, which is less scientific but has included  
the same types of people every four years, the biggest problems 
cited were the world economy (21 percent), Iraq (18 percent), arms 
control (15 percent), Japan and the Asian economic crisis (13 
percent) and dealings with Russia (13 percent). 
</P>
<P>
	The survey was published today in the journal Foreign Policy.  
</P>
<P>
	Richard Haas, foreign policy director for the Brookings  
Institution, said the assessment of Clinton's foreign policy 
success reflects the prosperous times for Americans more than any 
real achievement abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American people feel content with the world as it is, but  
history has a different standard,'' he told reporters at the 
presentation of the report. He said Clinton has missed several 
opportunities to develop a coherent post-Cold War strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton soared past Presidents Kennedy, Nixon, Truman,  
Eisenhower, Reagan, Bush and Carter, ranked in that order in 1994, 
to top the poll of presidents with ``very successful'' foreign 
policy performance since World War II. Only Presidents Ford and 
Johnson had trailed Clinton in the 1994 poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress also got improved marks, with 43 percent of those  
surveyed saying its role in foreign policy is about right, the 
highest number since the surveys began in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite general satisfaction with the direction of U.S. foreign  
policy, the survey revealed concern for the new century: 53 percent 
said they believe there will be more bloodshed and violence 
worldwide, with 19 percent predicting less. In the leaders survey, 
however, 40 percent said they believe there will be less violence 
and only 23 percent predicted more. 
</P>
<P>
	In the public poll, 84 percent listed terrorism as the most  
critical threat to the United States, up 15 points from the last 
survey. 
</P>
<P>
	Questions in the poll also ranked countries that respondents  
believe are vital to U.S. interests and gave each a ``thermometer 
rating'' on the respondent's warm or cold feelings. 
</P>
<P>
	Topping the list of vital countries was Japan, followed by  
Russia, Saudi Arabia, China and Israel. Among leaders, the ranking 
was China, Japan, Mexico, Russia, Canada, Saudi Arabia and Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	On the thermometer, with 50 degrees being neutral, Canada topped  
the chart for the fifth survey in a row at 72 degrees and Iraq hit 
the bottom with 25 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, concern for foreign policy issues ranked below key  
domestic problems in the poll. The biggest concerns cited by the 
public were crime, Clinton's personal conduct, drug abuse and poor 
education. For leaders, top problems were education, 
dissatisfaction with government, immorality and the troubled Asian 
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
