<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sheffield Exits Dodgers for Few Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Gary Sheffield, who is considering  
retirement, has left the Los Angeles Dodgers for a few days to take 
care of some personal business. 
</P>
<P>
	But the team said Monday that Sheffield had planned the trip  
more than a month ago and that it was unrelated to his comments 
this weekend about possibly ending his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Dodgers have known about this since before spring  
training,'' said John Olguin, a team spokesman. ``He'll be back 
Tuesday evening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old outfielder told the Los Angeles Times that he  
has thought about retiring because of chronic pain in his throwing 
shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he was upset the Dodgers had reinstated a policy  
restricting facial hair and jewelry -- rules that were relaxed last 
season to accommodate Sheffield, who has worn a beard and earrings. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second year of a six-year, $61 million contract,  
Sheffield came to the Dodgers last May from the Florida Marlins in 
the Mike Piazza trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be honest with you, if I still didn't have five years left,  
and if not for the trade, I would retire right now,'' Sheffield 
told the Times. ``But you're supposed to honor things that you 
agree to, and that's what I'm trying to do, but it's hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffield, who underwent surgery on his right shoulder during  
the offseason to repair tendon damage, has been moved from right 
field to left. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
