<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 09:25:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Urges Milosevic Kosovo OK  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today challenged Yugoslav  
President Slobodan Milosevic to follow the lead of ethnic Albanians 
in pledging to sign a peace deal for Kosovo. He said NATO 
airstrikes are still possible. NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana 
said that if the Kosovars agree to sign and Milosevic does not, 
``The risk of a catastrophe would be very likely.'' Clinton said 
the Serbs should be given a chance to agree to peace, but said they 
``can't go on indefinitely.'' The agreement gives Kosovars autonomy 
for three years but not the independence they sought. 

</P>
<P>
	Gephardt Backs Gore in 2000 Run  
</P>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt  
endorsed Vice President Al Gore today for the Democratic 
presidential nomination, signaling that party leaders want to 
settle the nomination early and focus on winning next year's 
election. Gephardt was considered a viable candidate himself, but 
decided last month to concentrate on helping Democrats take control 
of the House. Gore's visits to New Hampshire and Iowa today are 
seen as attempts to distance himself from President Clinton. 

</P>
<P>
	Fares Increase for Air Travel  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- For the second time this year, the airline  
industry has increased fares. The price hikes took effect this 
weekend. Business fares rose about 1 percent and leisure fares grew 
about 3 percent. United Airlines started this round of increases 
last Thursday and the other major carriers then followed. 

</P>
<P>
	Snowstorm Sweeps Across East Coast  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A storm that dumped nearly two feet on snow on  
parts of the Midwest last week pounded the East Coast overnight, 
knocking out power to thousands, snarling traffic and closing many 
schools and businesses. Areas of Maryland and West Virginia are 
under a foot or more of snow, and outlying sections of New York 
City got as much as 10 inches. The bad weather was blamed for a 
traffic pileup involving more than 20 vehicles on a Maryland 
interstate. Eighteen people were hurt, including five seriously, 
but none of the injuries were life-threatening, police said. 

</P>
<P>
	China Denies Stealing US Secrets  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji today denied his  
country stole U.S. nuclear weapons secrets and said the allegations 
are hurting U.S.-China relations. Zhu said he still planned to 
travel to the United States next month, despite what he called an 
``anti-China wave.'' He said the visit will be tough, given the 
allegations and disputes on trade, human rights and Taiwan. A 
Taiwanese-born American scientist was fired last week from a U.S. 
weapons lab amid suspicions that he shared secrets with Beijing. 

</P>
<P>
	Parental Kidnapping on the Rise  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The number of reported kidnappings is holding  
steady, except in one category: children taken by their own 
parents. Many cases are quickly solved, including some that turn 
out to be misunderstandings about when a parent was to return a 
child after a visit. But the most recent national study, published 
in 1990, showed that 163,200 children are abducted by relatives 
each year. Law enforcement officials say the primary motive is 
revenge against a former spouse, and that long-term psychological 
effects of abduction, even by a parent, can be devastating. 

</P>
<P>
	Death Toll at 28 in New Delhi Blaze  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- The death toll rose to 28 today in a  
fire that swept through a New Delhi slum crowded by residents who 
scratched out a living selling paper and plastic to recyclers. 
Noxious smoke from burning plastic made the fire especially hard to 
control. In addition, firefighters had to bulldoze shacks along the 
slum's narrow lanes to make way for their trucks. Many of the slum 
residents were so-called rag pickers -- poor people who collect 
plastic bags, old newspapers and other trash to sell. 

</P>
