<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Sen. John Chafee Retiring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- John Chafee of Rhode Island, senior member of  
a dwindling band of Senate Republican moderates, announced plans 
Monday to retire at the end of the term in a decision that 
strengthens Democratic chances of taking a seat away from the GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to come home,'' the 76-year-old Chafee told a news  
conference, his voice breaking, as he declared he would not seek a 
fifth term. A three-term governor and four-term senator, Chafee has 
been the most successful Republican politician in generations in a 
state that is overwhelmingly Democratic. 
</P>
<P>
	As chairman of the Committee on Environment and Public Works, he  
has carved out a record that consistently wins the praise of 
national environmental groups. And he has bucked GOP orthodoxy on 
issues ranging from abortion to health care. Most recently, he was 
one of five Republicans voting to acquit President Clinton on both 
impeachment counts. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton issued a statement praising Chafee as a ``tireless  
champion of the environment'' and lauding his work to expand health 
care to more women and children and improving services for the 
disabled. ``It is truly a rich legacy for America,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as Democrats were cheered by Chafee's retirement, they were  
stung by the announcement in Nevada that former Gov. Bob Miller 
will not run for the Senate. Party elders had courted Miller to run 
for the seat being vacated by Democrat Richard Bryan. Former GOP 
Rep. John Ensign is already in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans hold a 55-45 majority in the current Senate but must  
defend 19 of the 33 seats on the ballot in 2000. Chafee is the 
second Republican to announce retirement plans; three Democrats 
have done so. 
</P>
<P>
	The affable Chafee had been favored for re-election to a fifth  
term, so much so that second-term Democratic Rep. Bob Weygand had 
said he likely wouldn't run for the seat if the veteran lawmaker 
wanted to stay on. 
</P>
<P>
	Weygand is now expected to run, along with several other  
Democrats. Others whose names surfaced in the aftermath of Chafee's 
announcement are Secretary of State James Langevin and Myrth York, 
who twice has been defeated in gubernatorial races. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's other House member, Rep. Patrick Kennedy, recently  
joined the Democratic leadership and he reaffirmed that he will run 
for re-election to his current job. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Republicans, Chafee's son, Lincoln Chafee, is said to be  
interested in running for the Senate. Mayor of Warwick, the state's 
second-largest city, he attended his father's announcement. ``Can 
we talk about this tomorrow?'' he said to reporters asking about 
his own plans. ``Today is his day,'' he said of his father. 
</P>
<P>
	Former GOP Rep. Ron Machtley is also a potential contender.  
</P>
<P>
	Chafee was elected governor in 1962 for the first of three  
terms. He was defeated for re-election 1968 and was named secretary 
of the Navy. He left the Pentagon to challenge former Sen. 
Claiborne Pell in 1972, but was defeated and his political career 
seemed to be over. Four years later, though, he was elected to the 
Senate, and he vanquished three opponents in the years since. 
</P>
<P>
	At his news conference, Chafee thanked the predominantly  
Democratic electorate who consistently sent him to Washington. 
``They seek, as I do, bipartisan solutions to problems, rather than 
partisan gridlock,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chafee frequently labored to bridge partisan gaps in the Senate.  
In 1994, he was a key member of a group of senators who struggled -- 
in vain -- to find compromise on comprehensive health care 
legislation that President Clinton had proposed and the GOP 
leadership was working to defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, he voted against legislation to ban ``partial  
birth abortions,'' even though it was a key item on the GOP agenda 
and his state is home to a heavy concentration of Catholics. 
</P>
<P>
	He also slowed the GOP drive for block grants in welfare,  
casting his vote in favor of requiring continued protection for 
pregnant women, for example. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the Senate, Chafee has paid a price for his independence.  
Elected to the GOP leadership in the 1980s, he was ousted from his 
post in 1990 as the rank and file became more conservative. 
</P>
<P>
	If Republicans hold control of the Senate in 2000, his successor  
as chairman of the environment panel would be Sen. Bob Smith of New 
Hampshire, a fellow New Englander but considerably more 
conservative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
