<HEADLINE> Rangers Extend Graves' Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Adam Graves, in the midst of one of his best  
seasons, has signed a contract extension with the New York Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	No terms were given in the announcement Monday by Rangers  
general manager Neil Smith, except that Graves had signed a 
multi-year extension. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into Monday night's game against Washington, the  
30-year-old Graves led the Rangers in goals this season with 33. 
Graves was tied for fourth in the league with 13 power-play goals 
and tied for fourth in the league with seven game-winning goals. 
</P>
<P>
	In 815 games with New York, Edmonton and Detroit prior to Monday  
night, the 6-foot, 200-pound left wing had scored 493 points on 265 
goals and 228 assists. 
</P>
<P>
	Graves holds the single-season Rangers record for most goals,  
52, in the 1993-1994 season. Graves was a member of two Stanley Cup 
champions, the 1990 Edmonton Oilers and 1994 Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tremendous organization,'' Graves said of the Rangers.  
``It's great to play with the guys here -- Jeff Beukeboom, Brian 
Leetch, Mike Richter. I look forward to playing with all these guys 
for a few more years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graves said the Rangers had treated him very well, and he felt  
obligated to return the favor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was fortunate enough in '93-94, they tore (the contract) up  
and gave me a new contract,'' Graves said. ``I wanted to give Neil 
the same opportunity he gave me five years ago. Life is a two-way 
street. 
</P>
</TEXT>
