<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force Board Issues Crash Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Pilot error, training shortfalls and burnout  
are among the factors blamed for a crash of two Air Force 
helicopters that killed 12 airmen. 
</P>
<P>
	An overview of the investigation into the Sept. 3 accident of  
two Pavehawk helicopters was released by the Air Force Monday. The 
leader of the investigative board, Col. Denver Pletcher, said one 
helicopter had a new instructor pilot on board and a marginally 
qualified copilot and an unqualified gunner. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think that if any one of the crew members in those critical  
positions we mentioned had been different or more experienced, this 
accident might not have happened,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two helicopters were taking part in a mock rescue of a  
stranded airman at night when one helicopter struck the second 
craft, tearing into the cockpit with its rotor. The two helicopters 
crashed in rugged terrain 65 miles northwest of Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Pletcher also said the victims, members of the 66th Rescue  
Squadron, were ``operating at a constant state of surge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``All four pilots in this accident weren't as sharp as they  
could have been simply because they deployed too much,'' Pletcher 
said. ``The result in this case was chronic fatigue and burnout.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
