	Women Debate Breast Implant Deal  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Tens of thousands of women who sued the main  
manufacturer of silicone used in breast implants have 60 days to 
decide whether a proposed settlement is enough to end a decade of 
bitter legal fighting. Dow Corning has announced it would spend $12 
million to inform women about the $3.2 billion settlement plan and 
answer questions about the 265-page document. Dow Corning has set 
up a call center to handle questions about the plan. The center of 
200 people will answer questions in 30 languages from 8 a.m. until 
midnight EST. 

</P>
<P>
	Y2K May Affect Chemical Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Large chemical companies are well prepared for  
the Year 2000 computer problem, but smaller companies, many located 
near residential areas, may be less able to cope with potentially 
dangerous shutdowns, says a report presented to Congress today. 
Some 85 million Americans live within a five-mile radius of 66,000 
facilities handling high-hazard chemicals, the report's author, Dr. 
Gerald Poje of the U.S. Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation 
Board, told a news conference in the Capitol's Senate side. 

</P>
<P>
	Europe May End Duty-Free Shops  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union finance ministers failed  
to back an extension of duty-free shopping within the 15-nation 
bloc. Those sales are scheduled to end June 30. The ministers split 
over German proposals to grant a temporary reprieve for duty-free 
sales of tobacco, liquor, perfume and other goods for travelers 
crossing borders within the EU. 

</P>
<P>
	FDA OKs Device To Remove Blood Clots  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- People who need to have blood clots removed  
from blocked arteries before angioplasty have a new alternative. 
AngioJet, a medical device that removes these clots, was approved 
today by the federal Food and Drug Administration. The device, 
which was approved in 1996 for use in people undergoing dialysis, 
is expected to be especially helpful to heart patients who cannot 
use the so-called clot-busting drugs. 

</P>
<P>
	Chancellor Media Ends Merger Quest  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chancellor Media is ending its quest for a  
merger partner after just two months, with no takers emerging for 
the $20 billion price tag set by the radio-station empire. Instead, 
Chancellor is shaking up top management -- with its chief executive 
stepping aside -- and scrapping the planned purchase of Lin 
Television Corp. The company said it hopes to revive its lethargic 
stock price by focusing solely on radio and outdoor advertising. 
Chancellor Media shares were up 1 3/16 to 45 9/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers Push for Steel Sanctions  
</P>
