<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Push for Steel Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation establishing quotas on steel  
imports has gained the backing of nearly half of the House despite 
signs that the domestic industry's outlook is brightening. 
</P>
<P>
	That strong support in a Republican-led Congress that usually  
opposes restrictions on free trade reflects a belief that the 
turnaround is only temporary and that much larger layoffs loom if 
the federal government doesn't do something soon. 
</P>
<P>
	A House vote is scheduled Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``Steel is still hitting the docks on the coasts ... cheaper  
than what is produced in the United States,'' said George Becker, 
president of the United Steelworkers of America. ``Not a thing has 
changed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some U.S. steel plants recently recalled workers laid off last  
year as the domestic industry faced a surge in low-priced steel 
imports. Some imports have dropped since November because of 
preliminary rulings on complaints, and several companies have 
announced price hikes for April and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, House support for strong trade sanctions remains  
strong. The bill has 205 co-sponsors, including more than 40 
Republicans with large steel constituencies. 
</P>
<P>
	``While the trade figures have marginally improved, the crisis  
continues,'' said Rep. Pete Visclosky, D-Ind., the bill's chief 
sponsor. ``We can't let the problem take care of itself. We have to 
take a global approach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill faces a veto threat even if it overcomes steep hurdles  
in the Senate, so it may never become law. But supporters say they 
are happy just to show Congress takes the issue seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say the legislation would violate international trade  
agreements and ultimately could hurt the U.S. economy if other 
countries raise trade barriers in response. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really sends a pathetic message,'' said David Phelps,  
executive director for a Washington trade group for steel importers 
and exporters. ``One hopes there is some fundamental economic 
common sense in Congress and that they will give this legislation 
the indecent burial it deserves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steel imports reached record levels last year as the Asian  
economic crisis reduced demand for steel abroad and forced foreign 
producers to turn to U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite rehiring at some plants, thousands of steelworkers  
remain out of work and 100,000 more jobs are threatened when a 
contractual no-layoff clause expires this summer. Three companies 
have filed for bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic producers and two steelworkers unions complained to  
federal government that Japan, Russia and Brazil illegally dumped a 
widely used product -- hot-rolled carbon steel -- in the United 
States at prices dramatically below production costs. Allegations 
have also been brought concerning cut-to-length plate, another 
major product line, as well as stainless steel. 
</P>
<P>
	Preliminary rulings in favor of the U.S. industry regarding  
hot-rolled carbon steel helped reduce those imports from the three 
countries by 96 percent since November. 
</P>
<P>
	But overall imports in January, the most recent figures  
available, remain 27 percent higher than December 1997 levels, 
while steel prices have barely inched back to what they were 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry fears that Japan and Brazil will now shift to other  
products and that other countries will fill the void on hot-rolled 
carbon steel. Russia has reached a broad agreement with the United 
States to curb imports. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're making some progress but the issue is a longer-term  
one,'' said Curtis H. Barnette, chairman and chief executive 
officer of Bethlehem Steel Corp. ``While there have been some 
modest price increases, the starting price is so low.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials, already reluctant to take steps that  
could start a trade war, have used the signs of improvements as 
reasons not to take stronger action on steel. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the U.S. steel industry has intensified its efforts  
in Congress. The House Ways and Means Committee last week cleared 
the way for a House vote on legislation that would restrict imports 
to pre-July 1997 levels. Although opposed by a committee majority, 
the panel sent it to the full House with a negative recommendation 
to avoid parliamentary tactics by supporters. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Co. To Cut 6,700 More Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co. said Monday it will cut 6,700 more  
jobs than expected, due to reduced overtime and other manufacturing 
efficiencies in its commercial airplane division. 
</P>
<P>
	The additional cuts will mean total job reductions by the end of  
the year will be at the high end of a range of 28,000 to 38,000 
that the company announced earlier, Boeing said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They began to make a turn in the fourth quarter last year and  
have continued to make improvements in production,'' Boeing 
spokesman Peter Conte said. ``As you get better, and more 
efficient, you need less people to do the job.'' While there will 
be layoffs, about half of the job cuts will come through attrition, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing's profits and its stock price have been severely  
depressed during most of the past two years, the result of 
production line snarls, parts shortages and late aircraft 
deliveries. 
</P>
<P>
	The troubles began as Boeing was cranking up assembly lines to  
record production rates, and asking workers to perform vast amounts 
of overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then sales have slackened due partly to recessions in Asia  
and other markets and Boeing plans to reduce its production rates 
over the next two years. 
</P>
<P>
	It announced late last year it would reduce employment from its  
mid-1998 peak of 238,400 down to between 185,000 to 195,000 by the 
end of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Puget Sound area, where the majority of Boeing jetliners are  
assembled, will bear the brunt of the layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Machinists union officials say the new job cuts are uncalled  
for. The union, which represents Boeing production workers in 
Seattle and Wichita, Kan., negotiates a new contract with Boeing 
later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are not mere numbers. These are people with families  
working and living in the Puget Sound,'' said Bill Johnson, 
president of Machinists District Lodge 751 in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are people who are good, highly skilled workers. So  
good, in fact, that they are able to drastically reduce the time it 
takes to produce an airplane. So good, in fact, that Boeing's 
fourth-quarter profits were up. ... And instead of giving these 
people the job security that they demand and deserve, Boeing 
threatens their job,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Jacobs, an analyst with Ragen MacKenzie, said white-collar  
workers, not production employees, will be the target of future 
cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they also will be cutting additional salaried workers  
such as engineers and technical workers to further reduce overhead, 
which is unrelated to what's going on in the production line,'' 
Jacobs said. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, Boeing had profits of just $1.1 billion or $1.15 a  
share on revenue of $56.2 billion. It lost $178 million, or 18 
cents a share, on revenue of $45.8 billion a year earlier. The 1997 
loss was the first for Boeing in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing's stock fell 43 3/4 cents Monday to close at $34.68 3/4 on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they are getting back on their feet but it's still too  
early to gauge how that might translate into improved 
profitability,'' Jacobs said. ``We're already expecting the profit 
levels to improve this year ... but do these additional cuts mean 
that the profit levels would be up further? We just have to wait 
and see.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
