<HEADLINE> Fund-Raiser Case Will Affect Others </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A fund-raiser who steered thousands of dollars  
from a Buddhist temple to the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign 
deliberately covered her tracks and deserves no protection from the 
First Amendment, a federal prosecutor argued Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Maria Hsia knew she was soliciting illegal campaign  
contributions and arranged to use straw donors to hide the true 
source of the money, Justice Department lawyer Elizabeth Collery 
alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	``That type of deceitful conduct is simply not entitled to  
protection,'' Ms. Collery said in trying to persuade a federal 
appeals court panel to reinstate five charges against Ms. Hsia. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hsia's lawyer, Nancy Luque, argued that a lower court judge  
was right to dismiss the charges. The judge cited the First 
Amendment's broad protections of religious expression and free 
speech in dropping the campaign finance charges last September. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hsia, a California immigration consultant, is one of several  
foreign-born fund-raisers whose role in the 1996 campaign has 
become the focus of a Justice Department prosecution task force. 
</P>
<P>
	The fate of her case will affect at least two others in which  
government prosecutors have alleged that successful Democratic 
fund-raisers made ``false statements'' to campaign regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Those cases -- against Thai businesswoman Pauline Kanchanalak and  
former Little Rock, Ark., restaurateur Yah Lin ``Charlie'' Trie -- 
are on hold while the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of 
Columbia decides what to do about Ms. Hsia. The three-judge panel's 
decision is due later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Paul Friedman had said prosecutors used  
``Alice in Wonderland '' logic to blame Ms. Hsia for false campaign 
filings, but said she still must stand trial for conspiracy 
involving $65,000 in illegal contributions by a California Buddhist 
temple. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hsi Lai Temple, the Los Angeles-area host of an April 1996  
fund-raiser attended by Vice President Al Gore, was named as an 
unindicted co-conspirator when Ms. Hsia was indicted last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The temple is a tax-exempt religious organization barred from  
participating in any political campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Friedman is also handling the Kanchanalak and Trie cases, and  
has dismissed some of the charges against each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
