<HEADLINE> Dollar, Gold Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was down against most other major  
currencies in European trading Monday. Gold fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0951, up from $1.0924 Friday. Other  
dollar rates compared with late Friday included 117.88 Japanese 
yen, down from 119.52; 1.4611 Swiss francs, down from 1.4635; and 
1.5280 Canadian dollars, up from 1.5215. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the dollar rose against the British pound, which was  
quoted at $1.6250, down from $1.6299. 
</P>
<P>
	In midday New York trading, the dollar was worth 117.70 yen and  
1.4648 Swiss francs. The euro was worth $1.0925 and the pound was 
worth $1.6220. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar in London was worth 1.7860 German marks, down 
from 1.7904; 5.9899 French francs, down from 6.0047; and 1,768.12 
Italian lire, down from 1,772.49 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $289.70 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$291.50 on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $289.50, down from $292.60.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell $1.00 in Hong Kong to $291.45.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.16 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.27. 
</P>
