<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jimenez, Sjoland Added to Masters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Even with a new set of qualifications for the most exclusive  
major championship in golf, Augusta National found room Monday for 
Miguel Angel Jimenez and Patrik Sjoland, giving the Masters its 
largest field in 23 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The special invitations offered to Jimenez, coming off a victory  
in his native Spain, and Sjoland, a 27-year-old Swede, should 
complete the field for the first major championship of the year 
unless someone not already in the Masters should win the next three 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both men are very talented players,'' Augusta chairman Hootie  
Johnson said. ``Both golfers finished among the top five last year 
on the European tour's Order of Merit and have competed 
successfully against the best players in the world. We are very 
happy to have them in our field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of Jimenez and Sjoland brings the total number of  
invitations to 104, which includes past champions such as Byron 
Nelson and Gene Sarazen. The 95 players expected to compete is the 
largest field since 103 played in 1966. 
</P>
<P>
	Jimenez won twice last year and finished fourth on Europe's  
money list. He received his invitation Friday during the Turespana 
Masters, then responded with a 62 in the third round that sent him 
on his way to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``My message to them is get ready!'' Jimenez said. ``It proves  
that my game is in great shape for not only the Masters but also 
for the rest of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the second Masters for Jimenez, who missed the cut in  
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Sjoland will be making his debut at Augusta National. He earned  
his first European victory last year in the Italian Open and 
finished fifth on the money list. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I answered the phone and heard it was from Augusta  
National, I went all wobbly,'' Sjoland said. ``I had to turn down 
the volume on my stereo. It was the best news I've ever received.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Augusta National traditionally extends special invitations  
to international players at its discretion, that number dropped 
sharply this year when the Masters for the first time decided to 
invite the top 50 players from the world rankings. 
</P>
<P>
	Those in the top 50 at the end of last year, and any others who  
made the top 50 last week after the Doral Open, received 
invitations. 
</P>
<P>
	Jimenez and Sjoland came close to getting into the Masters  
through the rankings over the past month. 
</P>
<P>
	Sjoland was No. 55 going into the Match Play Championship and  
was 3-up with four holes to play in the third round when John 
Huston rallied to win the match and keep the Swede from locking up 
a spot in the Masters. Sjoland slipped to No. 58 Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jimenez needed a victory in the Portuguese Open two weeks ago  
and was three off the lead going into the final round but closed 
with a 76 and finished well back. With a special invitation in 
hand, he played the weekend like he had Augusta on his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a great week with a lot of good things happening,''  
said Jimenez, who moved up to No. 47 in the rankings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
