<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Higher; Dow Up 76 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average resumed its  
advance toward 10,000 today as a new round of corporate mergers 
sent stock prices higher. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow was up 76.32 at 9,952.67, less  
than 48 points from 10,000. The index of blue-chip stocks has 
flirted with the milestone in recent sessions, coming as close as 
42 points on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market appears to be tiptoeing toward Dow 10,000,'' said  
Alan Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. ``But we 
could reach that mark at any time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher today.  
</P>
<P>
	As the Dow stayed in a narrow range with relatively low volume,  
analysts said the market appeared to be awaiting a catalyst 
powerful enough to spark a strong run past 10,000. Monday's 
momentum came from announcements of several big mergers. 
</P>
<P>
	The $16 billion acquisition of BankBoston by Fleet Financial  
Group added some punch to the financial services sector. And DuPont 
said it will pay $7.7 billion to acquire 80 percent of Pioneer 
Hi-Bred International Inc., the world's largest seed corn company. 
</P>
<P>
	``These big deals are making investors feel very confident,''  
said Rao Chalasani, chief investment strategist at Everen 
Securities in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline stocks benefited from fare increases that will push up  
the price of a business fare about 1 percent and a leisure fare 
about 3 percent. UAL Corp., which also indicated its first-quarter 
earnings will top analysts' expectations, was up 6 5/16 at 73 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks were among the decliners after rallying Friday as  
world oil producers agreed to cut their output. Chevron was off 
9/16 at 84 1/8, and Exxon was off 7/16 at 73 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	By midafternoon, technology stocks, which have driven the market  
higher in recent months, looked stronger than the broader market as 
Internet stocks traded mostly higher. The Nasdaq composite index, 
driven by technology issues, was up 37.65 at 2,419.18. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues and decliners were nearly even on the New York  
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 576.1 million shares, well off 
Friday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 9.76 at 1,304.35, the  
NYSE composite index was up 2.83 at 614.47, and the American Stock 
Exchange composite index was down 1.68 at 719.53. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks rallied sharply overnight in Japan, as the Nikkei reached  
its highest level since last summer, rising 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	European markets, however, were mixed. Germany's DAX index  
closed 0.2 percent higher, Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 1.2 percent and 
France's CAC-40 rose 0.2 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
