<DOCNO> APW19990315.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:51:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Allots Preparedness Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Addressing the threat of terrorist strikes at  
home, President Clinton announced Monday that he was reallocating 
$11 million in federal funds to bolster urban medical teams trained 
to respond to chemical and biological attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The president made the announcement at the annual legislative  
conference of the International Association of Fire Fighters, whose 
members enthusiastically welcomed the news. 
</P>
<P>
	``In most instances of domestic terror, the first professionals  
on the scene will be the fire fighters,'' Clinton said. ``They're 
becoming the front-line defenders of our citizens -- not just from 
accidents and arsonists, but from those who would seek to sow 
terror, and so undermine our way of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Clinton highlighted $21 million in grants already  
included in this year's federal budget to help train fire fighters 
to handle terrorist attacks and $73.5 million to help communities 
buy protective and communications gear. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said that technological advances and more porous borders  
would make the next century ``a century in which limitless 
opportunities will be linked to dangerous new threats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not trying to put any American into a panic over this,  
but I am determined to see that we have a serious, deliberate, 
disciplined, long-term response to a legitimate potential threat to 
the lives and safety of the American people,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the initiatives Clinton discussed Monday were included  
in the fiscal 1999 budget, but the $11 million he announced to 
bolster the rapid-response medical teams came from across-the-board 
cuts in the Health and Human Services budget. Two programs were 
exempt from the cuts, one that helps low-income families pay 
heating bills and one that bolsters child care. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's fiscal 2000 budget proposals call for spending $2.8  
billion to safeguard the nation against chemical and biological 
attacks, as well as assaults on sensitive computer networks. That 
plan includes $683 million to train and equip urban emergency 
personnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:51:52 </DATE_TIME>
