<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 16:14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EU Executive Commission Resigns  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The entire EU Executive Commission  
resigned Tuesday after a panel of experts issued a scathing report 
on cronyism and financial irregularities at the top of the 
executive branch. EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler said 
the report cited several of the 20 European Commissioners for 
cronyism and financial irregularities in aid and other programs had 
created a climate in which the EU executive could not remain in 
office. 

</P>
<P>
	Panel Wants Tougher Seat Belt Laws  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- To prevent child deaths in car crashes, an  
expert panel recommended today that seat belt laws be strengthened 
and older children stay in booster seats longer before graduating 
to seat belts. The government had asked the panel to come up with 
recommendations for children aged 4 through 15 because so many die 
in auto crashes while riding unrestrained. In 1997, car crashes 
killed 1,627 children in that age group. Of those, 1,015 were 
unrestrained. Properly used booster seats and safety belts would 
have prevented about 500 of the deaths, an expert said. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Albanians Ready To Sign  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians have agreed to an international  
peace plan for Kosovo, leaving Yugoslavia's president with the 
choice of making peace or face NATO's wrath. The Kosovo Albanian 
delegation told international mediators today they were ready to 
sign the peace accord that gives them wide political autonomy but 
not the vote on independence they wanted. French and British 
foreign ministers said the decision will heighten pressure on 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept the deal, which 
calls for NATO troops to enforce it. 

</P>
<P>
	Gay Military Harassment Said Higher  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Harassment of homosexuals in the military more  
than doubled last year, a gay rights groups said today in 
criticizing Pentagon enforcement of the ``don't ask, don't tell'' 
policy. The military isn't supposed to investigate sexual 
orientation unless ``credible information'' surfaces about a 
person's homosexuality. Proof that someone is gay or professes to 
be gay is grounds for automatic discharge. The Servicemembers Legal 
Defense Network counted 400 cases of anti-gay harassment in the 
military last year, including death threats, compared with 182 
violations in 1997, a 120 percent increase. 

</P>
<P>
	Airlines Stocks Soar on Price Hike  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Higher fares and hopes for even higher profits  
sent shares in the nation's airlines rising sharply today. Airlines 
last weekend imposed their second price increase of the year and 
today the parent company of United Airlines said its profit growth 
would be faster than expected. UAL Corp. gained $6.68 3/4 to $73.75 on 
the New York Stock Exchange and the rest of the industry followed. 
AMR, parent of American Airlines, and Southwest Air both saw its 
stock soar. As for passengers, airlines have now boosted leisure 
fares 7 percent this year and business fares are up 3 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's Allen Buys Go2Net Share  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Billionaire Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen  
agreed to buy a $300 million majority share in Go2Net Inc., in a 
deal that could make Go2Net's Web sites a main Internet destination 
for many cable-TV users. The company runs a network of Web sites 
focusing on personal finance, Internet search, commerce and games. 
Allen's investment firm, Vulcan Ventures, owns stakes in cable-TV 
companies that provide high-speed Internet access. 

</P>
<P>
	Balloonists Break Distance Record  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The Swiss-English balloonists trying to circle the  
world nonstop broke American millionaire Steve Fossett's distance 
record today and sped across the Pacific toward Mexico, their 
control center said. The Breitling Orbiter 3 last night broke the 
15,203-mile distance record claimed by Fossett before he ditched 
near Australia last August. The record claim of the balloon piloted 
by Bertrand Piccard of Switzerland and Brian Jones of England must 
still be verified by the International Federation of Aviation. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Hits Another Record at 9,958.77  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average resumed its  
advance toward 10,000 today as a new round of corporate mergers 
sent stock prices higher. The Dow industrials rose 82.42 for a 
record high closing at 9,958.77. The technology-heavy Nasdaq 
finished at 2,431.44, up 49.91. 

</P>
<P>
	Nets Fire Coach John Calipari  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John Calipari was fired today as coach of the  
New Jersey Nets, a once-promising team that quickly became one of 
the NBA's worst this season. Nets swingman Kendall Gill confirmed 
the dismissal, which had been expected ever since Calipari met with 
owners yesterday after a loss in Miami and didn't accompany the 
team to Toronto. Only the Los Angeles Clippers have a worse record 
then the Nets' 3-17 mark. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
