<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Major Trades for Pat Riley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- For the first time since taking over operations of  
the Miami Heat four years ago, Pat Riley will go an entire season 
without making a major trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami's silence at last week's trade deadline speaks volumes to  
the Heat players. It was another sign that Riley thinks he has the 
nucleus to win a championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very encouraging. I'm ecstatic,'' said forward P.J.  
Brown, a Riley favorite whose name frequently has popped up in 
trade rumors. 
</P>
<P>
	While other teams were reshaping themselves in the free-agent  
frenzy that followed the NBA lockout, Riley merely dabbled while 
making sure his ``core guys'' were taken care of. 
</P>
<P>
	And after the Heat shook off injuries and a 1-3 start to win 14  
of their next 16 games, there seemed hardly any reason to tinker 
with success -- particularly in the NBA's short 50-games-in-90-days 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're 15-5 and leading the Atlantic Division, it's hard  
to break up a team like that,'' Brown said. ``You'd be hard-pressed 
to make a move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that Riley hasn't pulled the trigger in the past. Each of  
his first three seasons in Miami was marked by a trade-deadline 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Riley turned over half his roster in one day with three  
trades, including a four-player swap which brought Tim Hardaway 
from Golden State. That came three months after he pried Alonzo 
Mourning from Charlotte in a six-player deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Riley sent three players to Dallas for  
high-scoring forward Jamal Mashburn. Last season brought the only 
deal that failed to pay dividends, when he traded Ike Austin to the 
Los Angeles Clippers for Brent Barry. 
</P>
<P>
	Then this year -- nothing. Even when word surfaced that Stephon  
Marbury could be available from Minnesota at the right price, 
apparently including Hardaway, Riley defended his nucleus. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people are talking about Timmy, they are talking about an  
important part of what we built,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley did his tinkering around the edges early, signing guard  
Terry Porter and forward Clarence Weatherspoon as free agents to 
strengthen his bench. Both have paid off tremendously. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter, in his 14th season, has averaged 11.0 points per game,  
working both as Hardaway's backup and teaming with him as the 
shooting guard. He went 5-for-5 from the floor for 14 points in 
Sunday's 102-76 win over New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Weatherspoon, a seventh-year pro, is averaging 9.5 points and  
6.4 rebounds per game. He has 31 points and 14 rebounds in his past 
two games, hitting 13 of 15 field-goal attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got two veteran players that have produced since they  
got here,'' Riley said. ``Our bench has given us a huge lift. Our 
veterans simply know how to play basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the Heat still figure to improve down the stretch. Mashburn  
and Voshon Lenard have missed virtually the entire season with 
injuries, and their return will provide a scoring boost. 
</P>
<P>
	Mashburn, out the past five weeks with a hyperextended left  
knee, is expected to return to practice within a week and should be 
activated by the end of the month. Lenard, diagnosed with a stress 
fracture in training camp, figures to return in time for the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``With those guys returning, it'll improve our team,'' Brown  
said. ``We're just scratching the surface right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Heat's current makeup has been good enough to lead the  
Eastern Conference. Next up: catching Utah and Portland for the 
best record in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're thinking about winning a championship, then we're  
thinking about getting the best record,'' Riley said. ``Why not?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Foreign Policy Ranked High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans favor a strong national defense and  
aggressive action against terrorists, but most oppose any use of 
U.S. ground troops to protect allies, a new survey suggests. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll conducted by the Gallup Organization for the Chicago  
Council on Foreign Relations supports ``the guarded engagement of a 
largely satisfied superpower,'' said council president John Rielly. 
He gave high marks on foreign affairs to both President Clinton and 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	In the survey, 84 percent listed terrorism as the most critical  
threat to the United States, up 15 points from the last survey. To 
fight terrorists, 74 percent favored U.S. air strikes, and 57 
percent favored the use of U.S. ground troops. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, 68 percent oppose sending troops if China should  
invade Taiwan, 66 percent in case of a North Korean invasion of 
South Korea or a Russian invasion of Poland, and 56 percent oppose 
if Arabs invade Israel. Opposition drops to 48 percent if it's Iraq 
invading Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since 1978, however, those favoring increased  
defense spending exceeded the number who want cutbacks. Similar 
polls have been conducted every four years since 1974 
</P>
<P>
	Support for foreign aid continued a slow slide. Only 13 percent  
now favor increased spending for economic aid to other countries, 
and 48 percent want more cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	The new survey underscores general satisfaction with the U.S.  
role abroad by ranking Clinton No. 1 among postwar U.S. presidents 
for foreign policy success, up from eighth place in the middle of 
his first term. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress also got improved marks, with 43 percent saying its  
role in foreign policy is about right. That's the highest number 
for Congress since the surveys began. 
</P>
<P>
	Rielly said approval of Clinton parallels an absence of major  
foreign policy problems cited by those surveyed. When asked to list 
the two or three biggest foreign policy problems facing the 
country, the most common response among the public, at 21 percent, 
was: ``I don't know.'' That was followed by terrorism, 12 percent; 
the world economy, 11 percent; balance of payments, 10 percent; and 
the Middle East situation, 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Haas, foreign policy director for the Brookings  
Institution, who participated on a panel to mark the survey's 
release, challenged the assessment of Clinton. He said it reflects 
Americans' prosperity more than real achievement abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American people feel content with the world as it is, but  
history has a different standard,'' he said. Clinton, he said, has 
missed opportunities to provide leadership in the post-Cold War 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton soared past Presidents Kennedy, Nixon, Truman,  
Eisenhower, Reagan, Bush and Carter, ranked in that order in 1994, 
to top the poll of presidents with ``very successful'' foreign 
policy performance since World War II. Only Presidents Ford and 
Johnson trailed Clinton in the 1994 poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallup interviewed 1,507 men and women in October and November.  
The margin of error was plus or minus 3 percentage points. 
Separately, the pollsters interviewed 379 policy leaders, including 
members of Congress, administration officials, international 
business figures and members of the news media. 
</P>
<P>
	A report on the survey was published Monday in the journal  
Foreign Policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 06:53:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WWII Camp Commander Pleads Innocent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- Declaring his conscience clear, the last  
known living Nazi concentration camp commander pleaded innocent 
today to charges he was responsible for torture, killings and mass 
persecution of thousands of people. 
</P>
<P>
	Dinko Sakic faces charges of crimes against humanity in the  
death of 2,000 people during the eight months in 1944 when he 
commanded Jasenovac, the camp in Croatia known as the ``Death 
Factory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I absolutely do not feel guilty, not for a single charge,''  
the 77-year-old Sakic told the court after prosecutors read the 
35-page indictment. ``My conscience is clear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sakic's trial resumed today after court-appointed doctors  
testified he was fit to take part in the proceedings, which were 
postponed after he fainted on the eve of his March 4 trial. Sakic 
was hospitalized with severe circulatory problems and high blood 
pressure and the proceedings were postponed for 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Jewish groups feared the postponement might signal that  
Croatia's government is unwilling to prosecute Sakic for fear of a 
right-wing backlash. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakic, who had lived since 1947 in Argentina until extradited to  
Croatia, could face up to 20 years in prison if convicted over his 
role as commander of the worst of about 20 concentration camps run 
by the then-Nazi puppet state of Croatia. 
</P>
<P>
	Tens of thousands of Serbs, Jews, Gypsies and antifascist Croats  
were killed in 1941-45 in Jasenovac. The Simon Wiesenthal Center 
and B'nai B'rith International believe Sakic is the last surviving 
commander of a Nazi-era concentration camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges against Sakic focus on ``torture, maltreatment and  
killings,'' allegedly committed by him and by his subordinates with 
his knowledge. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment charges that Sakic exposed inmates to ``excessive  
labor, starvation, physical and psychological torture,'' which led 
to diseases and death for a number of them. 
</P>
<P>
	The sick and those unable to work were ``liquidated,'' the  
indictment said. Others were tortured, some to death, for the 
alleged misbehavior, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakic is also accused of allowing his subordinates to ``maltreat  
and kill ... out of capriciousness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the summer of 1944, as a reprisal for the escape of a  
musician prisoner, Sakic ordered a ``performance'' of all the 
detainees, the indictment said. As they stood before him, Sakic 
allegedly selected other musicians at random and had them killed -- 
two by his own hand. 
</P>
<P>
	On another occasion, the indictment says more than 20 inmates  
were to be hanged. One of them, Milo Boskovic, told Sakic that 
hanging was a humiliating way to die, so Sakic allegedly drew his 
pistol and shot him. 
</P>
<P>
	Last April, talking to an Argentine TV reporter in an interview  
that prompted his arrest, Sakic claimed the Jasenovac victims died 
of ``natural causes or diseases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sakic claimed he was ``only doing my job.'' Asked whether he was  
ashamed before his children, Sakic said: ``No, I'm proud. I would 
do it again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Franjo Tudjman, who often was criticized for  
cultivating the kind of nationalism that harks back to the World 
War II state, has promised that the trial will be impartial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:54:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gephardt Endorses Gore in 2000 Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, in a show of  
political force to kick off his 2000 presidential campaign, secured 
the endorsements Monday of House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt and 
party stalwarts from the early battleground states of New Hampshire 
and Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	With onstage hugs from Gephardt, Gore implored a New Hampshire  
crowd to ``stand with me,'' then headed for Iowa and a later stop 
in his onetime rival's hometown of St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would all be proud to have him as president of the United  
States,'' said the Missouri lawmaker, who opted out of the 
presidential race Feb. 3 to focus his energies on becoming speaker 
of the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt's announcement reflects the desire of top Democrats to  
settle the presidential nomination early and set their sights on 
winning both the House and White House in November 2000. President 
Clinton long ago pledged to help Gore get elected, guaranteeing his 
understudy an advantage not always bestowed upon vice presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley is the only announced  
challenger for the party's presidential nomination, though civil 
rights activist Jesse Jackson may enter the fray. 
</P>
<P>
	Lagging in polls, Bradley hopes to build a resurgent campaign  
that catches fire at the grass roots. He is buoyed by evidence of 
potential Gore weakness in the general election. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to have a nominee who can win,'' Bradley said.  
</P>
<P>
	Gore plans to capitalize on the popularity of Clinton  
initiatives while at the same time distinguishing himself from his 
boss. 
</P>
<P>
	The difficulty of this balancing act was evident at a New  
Hampshire news conference. Gore said he will ``face entirely new 
challenges, and we need new answers.'' Yet his answers sounded 
familiar: Reduce class sizes, make preschool available to all 
students and improve health care. Clinton has pressed those ideas, 
but Gore promises to push them further. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't want to join us in bringing radical change to  
public education, stand out of the way,'' he told a crowd of 400 
New Hampshire activists at a boisterous indoor rally. 
</P>
<P>
	With hardly a mention of his boss, Gore shouted again and again:  
``Stand with me!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt and Gore hugged after their speeches, raising their  
hands high. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair headed next to Iowa, hitting in one day the two states  
that cast the earliest votes in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In rolling out the endorsements on his first official political  
trip of the campaign, Gore hoped to develop a sense of 
inevitability about his nomination even before he formally 
announces his candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a reflection of reality,'' David Rohde, a professor of  
political science at the University of Michigan, said of Gephardt's 
endorsement. ``He and everyone else thinks Gore will be the 
nominee. What Gephardt wants is to be speaker -- and it's better to 
be part of a team than to hold back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with The Associated Press, Gore said he is  
taking nothing for granted. ``I welcome a spirited contest,'' he 
said. ``I always expect it.'' He promised to return to both states 
to campaign in living rooms and coffee shops. 
</P>
<P>
	During the three-state swing, Gore also locked down the  
endorsements of Bill Shaheen, husband of New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne 
Shaheen, and prominent Democrats in Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Hampshire governor and Iowa Gov. Tom Vilsack are still  
neutral, though Shaheen is said to be leaning heavily toward Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	The same polls that show Gore with a wide lead over Bradley  
offer hints at weakness. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest Wall Street Journal-NBC poll shows Gore 18 percentage  
points behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the early favorite for the 
Republican nomination. Gore did not mention Bush but criticized his 
father's ``failed prescriptions of the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Pew Research Center survey found nearly half of independent  
voters and 16 percent of likely Democratic voters said they had 
ruled out voting for Gore. The same poll showed that 76 percent of 
independents and 53 percent of Democrats said they would consider 
voting for Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I were the Gore campaign I would be concerned,'' said  
Democratic consultant David Axelrod of Chicago. ``But I wouldn't 
panic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Gore worked from the White House to lay claim to a  
series of bite-size initiatives popular among suburban voters, such 
as promising to ease traffic jams. Fine ideas, Democrats say, but 
he needs to leave Clinton's side to promote his own agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure about that ribbon-cutting strategy. That one  
makes me nervous,'' Axelrod said. ``I think it just underscores the 
second-banana thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans say Gore won't escape Clinton's policies or  
controversies. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is the Velcro to Clinton's Teflon,'' said GOP media  
strategist Alex Castellanos. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore proved last week that he can make mistakes. He claimed that  
he created the Internet, giving Republicans reason to howl. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after announcing he would not be a presidential  
candidate, Gephardt told Gore over lunch that he would endorse him. 
Gore's campaign saved the announcement until they could get the 
greatest attention for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore will formally declare his candidacy later this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
