<DOCNO> APW19990315.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Profits Up 4.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Profits at U.S. commercial banks in 1998 set a  
record for the seventh straight year, rising 4.7 percent to $61.9 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong income from bank fees overcame the costs of a merger wave  
and weakness in overseas operations, the Federal Deposit Insurance 
Corp. said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	But profits declined slightly in the fourth quarter of 1998, the  
FDIC reported. 
</P>
<P>
	In announcing the results for the nation's 8,774 commercial  
banks, the agency said last year's record profits came despite 
restructuring expenses related to mergers of some institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	There was a net decline of 368 banks nationwide in 1998, as 557  
banks were absorbed in mergers, three failed, 190 new ones were 
chartered, and two uninsured institutions became federally insured, 
the FDIC said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank profits declined 2.5 percent in the fourth quarter of 1998  
to $14.9 billion, weakened by continued lower earnings from foreign 
operations and the restructuring costs from mergers. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic and financial turmoil last year in Asia and Latin  
America were major factors in the weaker earnings overseas, 
according to the FDIC. 
</P>
<P>
	A basic yardstick of bank profitability -- return on assets -- was  
an average 1.11 percent in the October-December quarter, down from 
1.24 percent a year earlier. A majority of banks, 54.6 percent, 
reported lower returns on assets than in the fourth quarter of 
1997, the FDIC said. 
</P>
<P>
	Income from bank fees was strong, however.  
</P>
<P>
	Consumer advocates have criticized as excessive the fees that  
banks charge consumers for accounts, ATM machines and credit cards, 
and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan recently expressed 
concern over rising bank fees in congressional testimony. Studies 
by the Fed have found that bigger banks -- including those created 
by mergers -- tend to charge higher fees than smaller ones. 
</P>
<P>
	``Banks are making record profits by raising their fees, and  
some consumers are being priced right out of the bank,'' Edmund 
Mierzwinski, consumer program director for U.S. Public Interest 
Research Group, said Monday. ``Banks are not passing along the 
benefits of size to their customers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The banking industry maintains that the fees are reasonable in a  
competitive industry and are needed, for example, to keep people 
from writing insufficient checks. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDIC does not separately report bank fees -- which include  
credit card fees -- but includes them in the category of 
non-interest income. That income jumped 18.4 percent in 1998 to 
$19.2 billion, the new figures show. 
</P>
<P>
	The three banks that failed last year were Bestbank, Boulder,  
Colo.; Omnibank, River Rouge, Mich.; and Q Bank, Fort Benton, Mont. 
The two uninsured institutions that started taking deposits and 
became federally insured were Harris Trust Co., West Palm Beach, 
Fla.; and Mercantile Trust Co., St. Louis., Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the nation's 1,687 savings institutions insured by  
the FDIC reported record earnings of $10.2 billion last year, up 
15.6 percent from 1997. The FDIC said the gain was largely the 
result of lower expenses for credit losses and growth in 
interest-earning assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 07:55:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fares Increase for Air Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The airline industry increased fares over the  
weekend, the second price increase so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Business fares were hiked by about 1 percent and leisure fares  
grew about 3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	United Airlines, a unit of UAL Corp., started this round of  
increases last Thursday when it first posted the higher fares. The 
other major carriers then followed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think one of the primary motivators that caused the  
airlines to fall into line was the fact that fuel prices appear to 
have bottomed and are creeping back up,'' said Susan Donofrio, an 
analyst with BT Alex Brown Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Before this increase, the industry's last round of fare changes  
were at the end of January when business fares went up 2 percent 
and unrestricted leisure fares grew 4 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
