<DOCNO> APW19990315.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 11:05:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Minorities Becoming Cops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Someone reported a fight at an apartment building,  
but the crowd of Haitians in the stairwell told police they knew 
nothing about it. Then they began talking animatedly in Creole. 
</P>
<P>
	About what? A gang fight they were scared to report? A domestic  
dispute? 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign languages can frustrate investigators, but in this case  
there was no barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just regular conversation,'' Officer Georges Exilien, a  
rookie Haitian-American officer, whispered to his black partner. 
</P>
<P>
	Exilien left the building, a little more confident the situation  
was under control. And that's just what the Boston Police 
Department was hoping for when it began recruiting members of 
immigrant communities. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is how you can best serve neighborhoods that require  
specific language and cultural backgrounds,'' said Sgt. Detective 
Margot Hill, a spokeswoman for the Boston police. ``It's not rocket 
science; it's just responsive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Around the country, many police departments are finding that  
hiring a few newcomers can make their jobs easier. 
</P>
<P>
	--St. Paul, Minn., has hired 12 officers from Southeast Asia to  
help patrol the Hmong community. The ethnic group from Laos now 
accounts for more than 10 percent of the city's 300,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	--Palisades Park, N.J., a New York suburb whose Korean community  
quickly grew to about a quarter of the population, hired its first 
Korean officer in January after years of animosity between 
immigrants and authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	--Willows, Calif., a mostly white, rural town of 6,500, added a  
Hmong to its nine-member force when nearly 1,000 Hmong and Laotian 
immigrants moved into an apartment complex nine years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In a city where four of every 10 residents are immigrants,  
Boston has helped create detente in what was a cold war between 
minorities and police, said Pierre Imbert, executive director of 
the Catholic Charities Haitian Multiservice Center in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``It raises the level of comfort. If you were stopped or go to  
the department and there is someone there who speaks your language, 
you cannot buy that'' sense of relief, Imbert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many police departments have worked in recent decades to hire  
more blacks and Hispanics. But crime prevention experts have begun 
recommending that forces search for recruits from new immigrant 
communities, too, and departments in cities big and small seem to 
be listening. 
</P>
<P>
	``My feeling at the police department was that they're a new  
group and we need to start learning about their customs and 
learning how to deal with them,'' said former Police Chief Bob 
Shadley of Willows, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Shadley hired Thomas Lee, a Hmong, as a civilian liaison. Lee  
eventually became a full police officer in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	National statistics break down police forces by race, not by  
ethnic groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The vast majority of police officers are American-born white men  
who got their jobs with high scores on civil service exams. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't always that way. In the early years of the century,  
immigrant-dominated political machines doled out police jobs to 
their supporters, who often spoke with an Irish brogue. 
</P>
<P>
	With civil service reforms in the 1930s, departments began  
hiring new officers based on exams that were often difficult for 
many immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1990s, however, police abandoned the strategy of just  
responding to crimes and instead pursued community policing, which 
involves trying to forge new bonds with people in the neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	One problem is that many refugees fled official corruption and  
violence at home and do not trust the police in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Like most departments, the Boston police still hire new officers  
based on civil service exams, but some candidates who fill a 
special need, such as those who speak Creole, are pushed to the 
front of the list. That's how Exilien, whose exam scores were good 
but not sterling, became an officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Exilien, 23, was born in the United States to immigrant parents.  
Before graduating from the police academy in January, he delivered 
supplies for the school district, worked in a residential home and 
restocked restaurants with soda syrup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never even thought about being a cop. I thought I would be a  
laborer, but I knew I didn't want to be a laborer all my life,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	One recent night, Exilien drove with his partner through  
Boston's Haitian-dominated Mattapan neighborhood, where Exilien 
grew up. 
</P>
<P>
	Exilien's understanding of the community is invaluable,  
especially now that killings and other violent crime have decreased 
and much of his shift is spent mediating domestic disputes, said 
his partner, Philip Morgan. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are highly emotional situations,'' Morgan said. If the  
participants can identify with the officer, ``that's a lot more 
helpful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	These ethnic officers are already proving their worth in many  
towns. 
</P>
<P>
	A Vietnamese officer in Chamblee, Ga., prevented a potentially  
wrenching child abuse investigation when he recognized that a 
little girl's bruises were not the result of a beating, but of hot 
oil rubbed on her back with a coin -- a folk cure for a fever. 
</P>
<P>
	In St. Paul, the Hmong tradition of kidnapping teen-age girls as  
brides caused a lot of anger and confusion. Now Hmong officers sit 
down with the ``kidnapper'' and the girl's family, explain American 
law to them and ask the two sides to work out the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DeBartolo May Pay NFL $1M Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Eddie DeBartolo, exiled owner of the San  
Francisco 49ers, will pay the NFL a $1 million fine for his part in 
a Louisiana gambling scandal, the San Francisco Chronicle reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue's decision to impose the fine  
may be announced this week at the annual owners meeting in 
Scottsdale, Ariz., the newspaper said, citing unidentified sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The fine brings to $3 million the total amount DeBartolo faces  
for his involvement with indicted former Louisiana governor Edwin 
Edwards. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, DeBartolo pleaded guilty to one felony charge of  
failing to report an alleged extortion attempt by Edwards in 
connection with DeBartolo's bid for a riverboat gambling license. 
The judge imposed $2 million in fines. 
</P>
<P>
	DeBartolo and his sister, Denise DeBartolo York have been at  
odds for more than a year over control of the team, in part because 
of Eddie's debts to the family-held corporation. DeBartolo's 
attorney, Aubrey Harwell, while declining to discuss Tagliabue's 
pending sanctions, said he was hopeful Eddie DeBartolo and his 
sister could work things out. 
</P>
<P>
	Tagliabue said in January that DeBartolo would be suspended for  
the 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, John York told the San Jose Mercury News that  
DeBartolo York had no plans to sell the team if Eddie DeBartolo did 
not regain control. 
</P>
<P>
	``What she wants is a separation from her brother,'' said York,  
recently appointed vice president of the team. ``His interests and 
hers do not go down the same path.'' 
</P>
<P>
	York told the newspaper Sunday his wife was committed to keeping  
the team while her brother was out. 
</P>
<P>
	DeBartolo relinquished control of the team in December 1997 when  
the NFL investigated the gambling scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	While his wife might be interested in selling her share to her  
brother, she has no plans to sell to a third party if he can't 
return as active owner. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's first and foremost is a separation of her interests  
with Eddie's,'' York said. ``That does not mean she is out to hurt 
Eddie, but they need to be separated because their business 
interests are not the same. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 49ers are not for sale now. I can't tell you that that  
wouldn't change, but we don't have any intentions to sell the team. 
We are committed to running it because it is the most valuable 
single asset in the DeBartolo Corporation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 13:44:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Home Run Hitters in Spotlight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Properly aware of the excitement Mark McGwire  
and Sammy Sosa generated with last summer's home run race, the 
editors of the sixth edition of Total Baseball dedicated the 
official encyclopedia of major league baseball to the game's 
sluggers, past and present. 
</P>
<P>
	So they pay homage to homer hitters, listing 10 who have  
specialized in the long ball and led all major league players, 
either for a single season or an entire career. 
</P>
<P>
	Included are the usual suspects -- McGwire and his 70 homers,  
Hank Aaron and his 755, Roger Maris and his 61, Babe Ruth and his 
714. Even Sosa's 66 earned him an honorable mention. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there are the others, a collection of mystery men -- Dan  
Brouthers, Roger Connor, George Hall, Charley Jones, Harry Stovey 
and Ned Williamson. 
</P>
<P>
	Look them up and their power numbers seem like nothing special,  
except for one thing. They all played baseball before 1900, an era 
of the dead ball and the live arm. 
</P>
<P>
	That was before those rascally rabbits made their way into the  
cork-and-twine middle of baseballs, turning them into missiles. 
Home run leaders, forced to supply their own distance, rarely made 
it to double digits then, although occasionally some anomalies 
showed up. 
</P>
<P>
	In those pre-Comiskey days, the Chicago White Stockings played  
their games in Lakefront Park, where the right field fence was a 
cozy 190 feet from home plate. Before 1884, a ball that cleared 
that inviting wall was a ground-rule double. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the proprietors of the team and the league decided to make  
those balls home runs. Records, obviously, were treated more 
casually in those days. 
</P>
<P>
	Instantly, the White Stockings' long ball production zoomed from  
21 in 1883 to 142 in 1884. Williamson led the league with a record 
27 that year and, not surprisingly, 25 of them were hit at home. 
</P>
<P>
	This seemed exceedingly unfair, since no other team hit more  
than 39 homers that season. So the rule was changed again in 1885 
and Chicago's home run total dipped back to a more conventional 37. 
But Williamson's output stood as the single season record until 
Ruth hit 29 in 1919. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the times, Connor's 138 homers in 18 years gain in  
stature. And so does Stovey's production. He led his league in 
homers five times, including his rookie year of 1880, when he 
muscled six for Worcester. 
</P>
<P>
	That was one more than Hall hit for Philadelphia when he became  
the National League's very first home run champion in 1876. The 
next season, Hall was playing for Louisville and became involved in 
an unpleasant affair that involved the outcome of games. 
</P>
<P>
	After Louisville blew the pennant to Boston, league president  
William Hulbert, elected a year ago to Hall of Fame, started an 
investigation. When it was over, so were the careers of Hall, Bill 
Craver, Al Nichols and Jim Devlin, all thrown out of baseball in 
one of the many scandals that punctuated that period. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall was the most prominent of the four and he was devastated by  
the ban. Down on his luck, he went to see Hulbert and pleaded for 
another chance. The NL president was unimpressed. He gave the 
ex-home run king $50, saying, ``That's what I think of you as a 
man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All four never played organized baseball again.  
</P>
<P>
	How were the Louisville schemers caught?  
</P>
<P>
	Probably the fact that they negotiated with gamblers by telegram  
-- no beepers in those days -- had something to do with it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 04:14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rocker Marilyn Manson Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- A Marilyn Manson concert was cut short  
when the shock-rocker fell onstage at the Great Western Forum and 
injured his ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did injure himself, a minor injury to his ankle. The  
concert was stopped early,'' police Lt. Alex Perez said early 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate word on Manson's condition. Two local  
hospitals said the singer, whose real name is Brian Warner, had not 
been admitted after Sunday's concert. 
</P>
<P>
	Concertgoers logging onto a bulletin board on the singer's  
official Web site said Manson jumped or fell from an amplifier or 
speaker during a rendition of ``Rock is Dead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The concert halted after the band finished the song.  
</P>
<P>
	Concertgoers at first were told there were technical  
difficulties and the show would continue, but a second announcement 
indicated Manson had been injured and the event was over. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were not sent to the scene. A Fire Department dispatcher  
referred calls to the Forum but calls there rang unanswered early 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Manson was playing a much-anticipated concert along with  
Courtney Love and her rock band Hole. The show started at 7 p.m., 
with Monster Magnet as the opening act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:47:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  No Major Trades for Pat Riley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- For the first time since taking over operations of  
the Miami Heat four years ago, Pat Riley will go an entire season 
without making a major trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami's silence at last week's trade deadline speaks volumes to  
the Heat players. It was another sign that Riley thinks he has the 
nucleus to win a championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very encouraging. I'm ecstatic,'' said forward P.J.  
Brown, a Riley favorite whose name frequently has popped up in 
trade rumors. 
</P>
<P>
	While other teams were reshaping themselves in the free-agent  
frenzy that followed the NBA lockout, Riley merely dabbled while 
making sure his ``core guys'' were taken care of. 
</P>
<P>
	And after the Heat shook off injuries and a 1-3 start to win 14  
of their next 16 games, there seemed hardly any reason to tinker 
with success -- particularly in the NBA's short 50-games-in-90-days 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're 15-5 and leading the Atlantic Division, it's hard  
to break up a team like that,'' Brown said. ``You'd be hard-pressed 
to make a move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that Riley hasn't pulled the trigger in the past. Each of  
his first three seasons in Miami was marked by a trade-deadline 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Riley turned over half his roster in one day with three  
trades, including a four-player swap which brought Tim Hardaway 
from Golden State. That came three months after he pried Alonzo 
Mourning from Charlotte in a six-player deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Riley sent three players to Dallas for  
high-scoring forward Jamal Mashburn. Last season brought the only 
deal that failed to pay dividends, when he traded Ike Austin to the 
Los Angeles Clippers for Brent Barry. 
</P>
<P>
	Then this year -- nothing. Even when word surfaced that Stephon  
Marbury could be available from Minnesota at the right price, 
apparently including Hardaway, Riley defended his nucleus. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people are talking about Timmy, they are talking about an  
important part of what we built,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley did his tinkering around the edges early, signing guard  
Terry Porter and forward Clarence Weatherspoon as free agents to 
strengthen his bench. Both have paid off tremendously. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter, in his 14th season, has averaged 11.0 points per game,  
working both as Hardaway's backup and teaming with him as the 
shooting guard. He went 5-for-5 from the floor for 14 points in 
Sunday's 102-76 win over New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Weatherspoon, a seventh-year pro, is averaging 9.5 points and  
6.4 rebounds per game. He has 31 points and 14 rebounds in his past 
two games, hitting 13 of 15 field-goal attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got two veteran players that have produced since they  
got here,'' Riley said. ``Our bench has given us a huge lift. Our 
veterans simply know how to play basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the Heat still figure to improve down the stretch. Mashburn  
and Voshon Lenard have missed virtually the entire season with 
injuries, and their return will provide a scoring boost. 
</P>
<P>
	Mashburn, out the past five weeks with a hyperextended left  
knee, is expected to return to practice within a week and should be 
activated by the end of the month. Lenard, diagnosed with a stress 
fracture in training camp, figures to return in time for the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``With those guys returning, it'll improve our team,'' Brown  
said. ``We're just scratching the surface right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Heat's current makeup has been good enough to lead the  
Eastern Conference. Next up: catching Utah and Portland for the 
best record in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're thinking about winning a championship, then we're  
thinking about getting the best record,'' Riley said. ``Why not?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:47:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
