<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Blaming Shutdown on Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After years of paying a political price for  
shutting down the government over a budget stalemate, Republicans 
are trying to harvest a financial windfall from the episode. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican National Committee, seeking $5 million for an ad  
campaign supporting this year's GOP budget proposal, sent 
fund-raising letters blaming the 1995 and 1996 shutdowns on 
President Clinton and suggesting another might be inevitable this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each year since 1994, President Clinton has engineered an  
artificial budget crisis with constant veto threats and three 
partial government shutdowns in four years,'' the GOP fund-raising 
letter states. 
</P>
<P>
	Predicting Clinton would ``shut down the government for a fourth  
time in five years'' the letter from RNC chairman Jim Nicholson 
asked recipients to donate $5 and up to help the RNC ``win the 
communications battle'' over this year's budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter's assignment of blame on Clinton comes despite polls  
and election results showing that Americans have blamed Republican 
congressional leaders for the two previous shutdowns that spanned 
27 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Some federal agencies and national parks closed after Clinton  
vetoed the spending bills to keep them open because he objected to 
provisions in the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Then-House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., said at the time that  
one reason for the impasse was that Clinton snubbed him during a 
flight on Air Force One. The New York Daily News put a cartoon of 
Gingrich in diapers on the front page, under the headline, ``Cry 
Baby.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton shot up in the polls after standing up to the GOP and  
easily won re-election in November 1996. Meanwhile, House Democrats 
gained seats in both 1996 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	RNC spokesman Tim Fitzpatrick said the GOP has been unfairly  
blamed for the government shutdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our party certainly takes issue with the fact that the  
president seems to be disavowing any responsibility for that 
shutdown when it was his veto power that led to the government 
shutdown in the first place,'' Fitzpatrick said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to point that out, and we want to make sure the  
president doesn't get away with any of his budgetary smoke and 
mirrors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Andrew, the new Democratic National Committee national  
chairman, called the Republican fund-raising letter ``revisionist 
history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Blaming President Clinton for the government shutdown is like  
blaming President Roosevelt for Pearl Harbor,'' Andrew said. 
</P>
<P>
	With both sides poised to revisit the thorny budget disputes  
this year, there may be an advantage in Republicans getting their 
side of the story out early, GOP consultant Eddie Mahe said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's best we set out and make sure we don't get beat up on it  
again,'' Mahe said. ``It's what we call inoculation. We have to get 
the process under way that Republicans know it's not Republican 
members of Congress making it happen, it's Bill Clinton.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
