<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ailing Kjus Wins World Cup Skiing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIERRA NEVADA, Spain (AP) -- In and out of his sick bed all  
season with lung and chest problems, Lasse Kjus still proved to be 
the most durable skier of all. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his battle with chronic bronchitis, the 28-year-old  
Norwegian still managed to win the prestigious World Cup overall 
crystal globe, the season's World Cup downhill and combined titles, 
and a record five medals at the world championships in Vail, 
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult to compare it with my overall title in 1996,''  
said Kjus. ``But at the moment this is my favorite because I'm 
feeling the emotion right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old Kjus hacked and coughed through the first half  
of the season, took an early leave before Christmas to recuperate, 
then missed six races in the second half, losing valuable chances 
to collect points. 
</P>
<P>
	His accomplishments this season overshadowed every other skier  
expect one -- Austria's Alexandra Meissnitzer, who matched Kjus 
title for title, winning gold in the super-G and giant slalom at 
the World Championships, as well as the World Cup overall, super-G 
and giant slalom crowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Poor health wasn't the only thing Kjus had to battle. He also  
had to fend off last year's overall champion, Hermann Maier, and 
teammate Kjetil Andre Aamodt. 
</P>
<P>
	It proved to be the tightest fight for the men's overall since  
1991, and ended in dramatic fashion on Sunday -- the last day of the 
season -- when Kjus edged Aamodt by just 23 points, even though 
Aamodt finished ahead in the final race, a giant slalom. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy I was in the fight for the overall,'' said Aamodt,  
who didn't win a World Cup race all season. ``This second place 
makes me happy and motivates me for next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Maier, who shot to stardom claiming double Olympic gold, 10  
World Cup wins and the overall title in his first full season on 
the circuit last year, settled for the World Cup super-G title. 
</P>
<P>
	He surrendered his World Cup overall crown to Kjus, and allowed  
Michael Von Gruenigen to reclaim the giant slalom title the Swiss 
skier had won in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am still very happy and proud of my season,'' Maier said.  
``I won eight World Cup races and won two gold medals at the world 
championships. The overall doesn't matter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeping all five World Cup crystal globes last season, this  
year Austria's men claimed only two -- Maier in super-G and Thomas 
Stangassinger in slalom. 
</P>
<P>
	But the nation's pride survived thanks to a dominant performance  
by its women, who swept five titles with German Hilde Gerg taking 
the season combined. 
</P>
<P>
	Meissnitzer won overall, super-G and giant slalom, Renate  
Goetschl captured the season downhill, and Sabine Egger won the 
slalom crystal globe. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a disappointing season for Gerg, who was hoping to  
benefit from the absence of '98 overall champion and teammate Katja 
Seizinger, out with a leg injury. 
</P>
<P>
	But a disappointing performances just days before the start of  
the World Cup Finals last week allowed rivals to pull away from her 
in overall and the downhill. 
</P>
<P>
	The Finals, disrupted by quick-changing weather in Sierra  
Nevada, were also hit with a strike threat when women skiers 
declined to ski the second leg of slalom because of a rutted piste. 
FIS moved quickly and canceled the race to avoid embarrassment. 
</P>
<P>
	The cancellation cost Swede Pernilla Wiberg -- a mere 10 points  
behind Egger in slalom -- a chance to win the season crown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
