<HEADLINE> Billionaire Probes Man's Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The parents of a man who committed suicide in  
a bathroom near the office of conservative billionaire Richard 
Mellon Scaife are trying to trace their son's final days. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still don't know if Steve was running or if he was after  
somebody,'' said Jan Lankeet, the mother of Steven R. Kangas. 
</P>
<P>
	Kangas, 37, was found dead from a gunshot wound to the head last  
month on the 39th floor of One Oxford Center, where Scaife has his 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're as baffled as anybody else. We have no earthly idea why  
he would be up there,'' said Robert Esh, the victim's father. 
``Steve was totally nonviolent. He didn't even believe in guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kangas, who championed liberal causes with a Web site titled  
``Liberalism Resurgent,'' posted a message on the Internet six days 
before his death. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Tribune-Review of Greensburg, where Scaife is  
publisher, the message blamed Scaife for President Clinton's 
political troubles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clinton is, in my mind, a moderate Republican, and it is only  
the insanity of Richard Mellon Scaife that is causing them to go 
after this man,'' the newspaper on Sunday quoted Kangas writing. 
</P>
<P>
	Scaife himself has hired a private investigator to investigate  
Kangas' motives. The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette reported Sunday that 
Scaife is interested in knowing whether Kangas was after him 
because Scaife funded conservative causes, including giving a 
magazine, the American Spectator, $1.8 million to investigate 
President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	In discovering Kangas' body, police said they found a pistol he  
had bought two weeks earlier in Las Vegas, where he had been a 
partner in a gambling venture before recently selling his stake in 
the business. 
</P>
<P>
	He was found with $14.63 in his pockets, 47 rounds of ammunition  
in his backpack, a nearly empty bottle of Jack Daniels whiskey and 
a copy of Hitler's ``Mein Kampf,'' authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Post-Gazette reported that in an autobiography he posted on  
his Web site, Kangas called his move to Las Vegas in 1997 ``a big 
mistake'' and said he was planning to move back to Santa Cruz, 
Calif., where he had attended the University of California. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, according to family and friends, he placed ads in a  
newspaper to sell his car and his camera, then bought a gun. 
Authorities did not know precisely when he left Las Vegas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
