<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group: Gay Military Harassment Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Harassment of homosexuals in the military more  
than doubled last year, a gay rights groups said Monday in 
criticizing Pentagon enforcement of the ``don't ask, don't tell'' 
policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the 5-year-old policy, the military isn't supposed to  
investigate sexual orientation unless ``credible information'' 
surfaces about a person's homosexuality. Proof that someone is gay 
or professes to be gay is grounds for automatic discharge. 
</P>
<P>
	The Servicemembers Legal Defense Network counted 400 cases of  
anti-gay harassment in the military last year, including death 
threats, compared with 182 violations in 1997, a 120 percent 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The group said they found 511 incidents -- including a number of  
the 400 harassed -- in which service members said they were asked 
about their sexual orientation and their cases were pursued by 
military investigators or commanders until they quit or were 
dismissed. In 1997, the legal defense network's counted 359 such 
instances. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was in constant fear of being found out, investigated and  
discharged despite my impeccable record,'' said former Navy Lt. 
Comdr. Jill Szymanski, who resigned in August after 12 years. ``It 
has become an acceptable part of military culture to pick on and 
demean suspected gay service members and no one is held accountable 
for these actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon declined immediate comment on the report.  
</P>
<P>
	There were 1,145 gay discharges from all service branches last  
year, the Pentagon reported in January. In 1997, the total was 997, 
the highest number since 1987. The number hit a low of 617 in 1994, 
the year the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy took effect. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon officials, in releasing the discharge figures, said  
many were recruits intent on leaving the military anyway. But a 
Pentagon report last April concluded, ``The reasons for this 
increase are not known and would be difficult to ascertain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	C. Dixon Osburn, co-executive director of the legal defense  
network, said the cases his group documented tell the story behind 
the discharges. 
</P>
<P>
	``The service members are forced between hiding under this  
blanket of fear and anxiety from harassment every day or coming out 
and being fired for who they are,'' Osburn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Osburn said he isn't arguing for a ``zero discharge'' policy,  
realizing members of Congress, the administration and the Supreme 
Court aren't going to reverse the law any time soon. Instead, his 
group is advocating commanders enforce the rules designed to 
protect the privacy of service members and limit investigations 
into their lives. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon, facing criticism for alleged overzealous pursuit  
of gay men and women in the military, issued guidelines in March 
1997 for carrying out the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy more 
evenly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investigators should not solicit allegations concerning the  
sexual orientation or homosexual conduct of the threatened 
person,'' said the guidelines, written by Undersecretary of Defense 
Edwin Dorn. He also wrote that service members who are harassed 
should be able to report that without fear of reprisals. 
</P>
<P>
	David Raleigh, a former lance corporal with the Marine Corps who  
quit after two years, said he experienced harassment from basic 
training when his drill instructor asked, ``You're a fag, aren't 
you?'' He said he was afraid that reporting the insults and threats 
would end his career, but he finally decided it was unsafe to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the end, I knew I couldn't trust these Marines in combat  
for fear that I would be the first casualty,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
