<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magazine Bill Advances in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- The House of Commons passed a contentious bill  
Monday that would limit U.S. magazine operations in Canada, but the 
government indicated it was still open to compromises to avert a 
trade war. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, which now goes to the Senate, would impose fines on  
foreign publishers who carried Canadian advertising in special 
Canadian editions of their magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian publishers say they lose advertising to these so-called  
split-run magazines, which have lower production costs and charge 
less for ads. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, which cleared the House of Commons on a 193-46 vote,  
has been assailed by the U.S. government. Washington has threatened 
retaliatory trade sanctions on Canadian lumber, textiles steel and 
plastics if the measure goes into effect. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations on a compromise are scheduled to continue this  
week, and U.S officials have said they are willing to be patient in 
hopes agreement can be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's heritage minister, Sheila Copps, said Monday that her  
government might be willing to compromise by amending the bill to 
set allow split-runs with a specified amount of Canadian editorial 
content. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are willing to discuss with the Americans changes that  
would accommodate their concerns and at the same time respect 
Canadian content,'' Copps said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
