<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Round of Kosovo Talks Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The second round of Kosovo peace talks opened  
today, but negotiators expressed little hope of a deal between 
rival Serbs and ethnic Albanians as violence flared anew. 
</P>
<P>
	Three weeks after the first round of talks ended without any  
agreement, Yugoslav forces bombarded two rebel-held villages in 
northern Kosovo with tank and rocket fire and an army officer was 
shot in the arm. 
</P>
<P>
	The Serbs accused the Kosovo Liberation Army of attacking an  
army post early today after firing on two police stations the 
previous night. 
</P>
<P>
	A Yugoslav army officer was shot and wounded today as he rode in  
a jeep along the main road just north of Kosovo's capital, 
Pristina, near a rebel-held village, a spokesman for the 
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe said. 
</P>
<P>
	International monitors said they saw the bodies of 10 war  
victims Sunday -- four in the western Klina area and six in the 
southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Both warring sides have been vying for position while mediators  
opened a second round of talks today to end the year-old war that 
has killed more than 2,000 people and displaced 300,000 in the 
separatist province of Serbia, the dominant republic in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The two delegations at a Paris conference center this morning  
met in separate sessions with mediators. 
</P>
<P>
	A source close to mediators said the Serbs were still refusing  
to discuss a NATO-led implementation force in Kosovo -- a key 
element for any peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The international community has insisted both the military and  
political components of any settlement must be agreed upon. 
</P>
<P>
	Failure of the talks could lead to NATO bombardment of Serb  
strategic targets, especially if the Serbs are seen as the party 
blocking a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Mediators were talking tough. Phil Reeker, the chief spokesman  
for the conference, said that this time the meeting will last ``a 
few days at most.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, co-host of the talks  
with French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine, said this was a time 
for tough bargaining. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a conference for high rhetoric,'' Cook said.  
``This is a conference for serious, businesslike discussion, hard 
bargaining, aiming at a rapid conclusion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But prospects did not look good for a deal, with the Serbs  
refusing the deployment of some 28,000 NATO-led troops, including 
up to 4,000 Americans, to police the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kosovo Albanians, who represent 90 percent of Kosovo's 2  
million people, have been reluctant to sign because they are not 
getting the independence they seek and their guerrillas would have 
to be disarmed. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Kosovo Albanians, and the West, have said there cannot  
be a deal without the NATO-led police force. 
</P>
<P>
	Vedrine said Sunday night that ``there is no optimism'' among  
the Contact Group -- comprised of the United States, Russia, France, 
Britain, Italy and Germany -- which is trying to persuade the two 
sides to agree. 
</P>
<P>
	The leader of the Serb delegation, Ratko Markovic, on Sunday  
flatly rejected any NATO-led troops in Kosovo and said there will 
be no independence for the province. 
</P>
<P>
	``Serbia will never give up Kosovo voluntarily. It's only by  
force that it can be taken,'' Markovic told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources close to the Serbian delegation have indicated they  
might try to stall the talks by proposing a three-month cease-fire 
in Kosovo, or the deployment of unarmed, non-NATO peacekeeping 
troops -- something the West is sure to reject. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethnic Albanians may, for tactical reasons, sign the plan.  
The United States has hoped all along that an ethnic Albanian 
signing would step up the pressure against Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, Serbia has massed troops in and around Kosovo  
and fighting in the province itself has resulted in numerous 
casualties. Thousands of ethnic Albanians have fled their homes and 
are living in the forests and mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	There was still no public claim of responsibility for two  
weekend bomb blasts in Kosovska Mitrovica and Podujevo that killed 
seven people and injured dozens. Both sides blamed each other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
