<HEADLINE> Norway Plans Oil Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSLO, Norway (AP) -- Norway is set to cut its oil production by  
an additional 100,000 barrels a day as of April 1, joining other 
oil exporters in a drive to reduce a global glut and boost prices, 
the oil ministry said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuts will be made if the Organization of Petroleum Exporting  
Countries formally adopts a 2-million-barrel daily cut negotiated 
by five major oil exporters last week, said ministry spokeswoman 
Sissel Edvardsen. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC ministers are scheduled to meet on March 23 in Vienna.  
</P>
<P>
	Norway is the world's second-largest oil exporter, producing  
just under 3 million barrels per day. 
</P>
<P>
	It is not a member of OPEC but has often contributed to the  
organization's efforts to manage prices. Last year, Norway cut 
production by 100,000 barrels to support those efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the OPEC countries don't contribute, then Norway will have  
to reevaluate its decision. That is also the case if the agreed 
cuts are not carried out,'' Oil Minister Marit Arnstad was quoted 
as telling the Norwegian news agency NTB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
