<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Higher Rallying / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Tuesday morning as  
global investors shifted funds into the rallying Tokyo stock 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 118.24 yen in late morning, down 0.18 yen from  
late Monday in Tokyo but above its rate of 117.64 yen in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average rose 62.67 points, or 0.40 percent, to  
15,842.27 at the end of the morning session. On Monday, the average 
closed up 290.74 points, or 1.88 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese stocks have risen on news of corporate restructurings  
such as that announced by Sony Corp., helping to make the Nikkei 
the best-performing major market this year. 
</P>
<P>
	That's made a number of foreign fund managers reconsider  
decisions to avoid investing in the lackluster Japanese economy. As 
they've started putting money into Japan, their buying has given 
the yen a boost. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar moved as low as 117.28 yen at one point early in the  
Tokyo session following comments from Japan's Finance Minister 
Kiichi Miyazawa that seemed initially to indicate a turn toward a 
stronger yen. 
</P>
<P>
	At a regular news conference, Miyazawa said the dollar's fall  
below 118 yen in New York earlier somewhat reflected fundamental 
economic factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Miyazawa's remarks came after comments Monday by Vice Finance  
Minister for International Affairs Eisuke Sakakibara, who clearly 
said that yen strength was ``undesirable'' at this time. 
</P>
<P>
	Market players who sold the U.S. currency soon after Miyazawa's  
remarks scrambled later to cover their short, or oversold, 
positions, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 128.32 yen, down  
sharply from 129.44 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro fell after news that the 20-member European Union  
Executive Commission resigned en masse Tuesday following reports of 
financial irregularities. The resignation was announced by EU 
Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section gained 11.76 points, or 0.97 percent, to 1,222.94. 
The TOPIX gained 15.57 points, or 1.30 percent, on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.765  
percent from Monday's close of 1.785 percent, driving its price up 
to 110.27 yen from 110.11 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
