<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Forbes Announces Candidacy  
</P>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Steve Forbes will declare his  
presidential candidacy Tuesday on the Internet, promising to wage 
an ``information-age campaign about great ideas and enduring 
values.'' In an address produced for transmission on his Internet 
site, Forbes says, ``You and I are entering the information age and 
Washington politicians are stuck in the Stone Age.'' He outlines 
his Republican agenda to abolish the tax code, protect Social 
Security and curb abortions. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Allots Preparedness Funds  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Addressing the threat of terrorist strikes at  
home, President Clinton announced Monday that he was reallocating 
$11 million in federal funds to bolster urban medical teams trained 
to respond to chemical and biological attacks. In addition, Clinton 
highlighted $21 million in grants already included in this year's 
federal budget to help train fire fighters to handle terrorist 
attacks and $73.5 million to help communities buy protective and 
communications gear. 

</P>
<P>
	EU Executive Commission Quits  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The chief executive of the European  
Union and 19 other senior officials abruptly resigned early 
Tuesday, after an investigative panel alleged cronyism and 
financial irregularities in their ranks. It marked the first time 
in the group's 42-year history that the European Commission, which 
runs the day-to-day affairs of the powerful trading block, had 
stepped down under fire. The action would be roughly equivalent to 
the entire U.S. Cabinet resigning. 

</P>
<P>
	HMO Group Requiring Outside Reviews  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- HMOs must let patients appeal denials of care  
to outside experts if they want a seal of approval from the 
nation's largest accrediting group. It's the latest in a string of 
private initiatives boosting the idea of external reviews, which 
both supporters and critics of managed care have come to support as 
a way to assure consumers they won't be unfairly denied treatment 
for financial reasons. The National Committee on Quality Assurance, 
which accredits about half of the nation's health maintenance 
organizations, plans to require these independent reviews beginning 
next year. 

</P>
<P>
	More Salmon Species Now Endangered  
</P>
<P>
	GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) -- Nine salmon species in the Pacific  
Northwest are being added to the endangered list in a move that 
could change the way people fertilize their lawns, dig construction 
sites or wash their cars. The National Marine Fisheries Service 
said that Endangered Species Act protections will be extended to 
certain wild salmon stocks in the region. The waterways, once full 
of salmon, are now surrounded by urban sprawl where industries 
pollute rivers, road culverts block spawning areas and even lawn 
fertilizers and soap used to wash cars seep into streams through 
storm drains. 

</P>
<P>
	Communities Sue Over Crack Epidemic  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- City residents who claim the federal  
government did nothing to stop crack cocaine sales in their 
neighborhoods in the 1980s sued the CIA and Justice Department on 
Monday. The complaints were filed on behalf of mostly black 
residents whose babies were born addicted to crack, whose relatives 
died in drug-related drive-by shootings and whose communities were 
affected by crowded emergency rooms and gutted business districts, 
the lawsuit said. 

</P>
<P>
	Asian Cities Are Most Costly  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Tokyo and four other cities in Japan and China  
have the world's highest cost-of-living for foreigners despite 
Asian financial turmoil, according to a survey released Tuesday. 
Besides Moscow in sixth place and London in 8th, all the top 10 
cities were in Asia. The least expensive cities were Madras, India, 
in 148th place; Volgograd, Russia, 149, Blantyre, Malawi, 150; and 
Harare, Zimbabwe, 151. 

</P>
<P>
	Rock Hall of Famers Honored  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Three singers who dominated in the 1970s -- Bruce  
Springsteen, Paul McCartney and Billy Joel -- joined the Rock and 
Roll Hall of Fame today along with 1960s star Dusty Springfield, 
who died two weeks ago. Other inductees included ``Superfly'' 
singer Curtis Mayfield, Del Shannon and The Staples Singers. The 
ceremony was held at New York's Waldorf Astoria Hotel. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Post Rally  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Global investors shifted funds into the rallying  
Tokyo stock market, boosting the Nikkei 62.67 points, or 0.40 
percent, to 15,842.27 at the end of Tuesday's morning session. In 
New York, the Dow rose 82.42 for a record high closing at 9,958.77. 

</P>
<P>
	NCAA Women's Roundup  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Top-ranked Purdue reached the round of 16  
despite a second poor showing in NCAA women's tournament play, 
beating Kansas 55-41 tonight in a Midwest Regional game at West 
Lafayette, Ind. In other second-round action, Duke defeated St. 
Joseph's 66-60, Georgia downed SMU 68-55, LSU bested Notre Dame 
74-64, Virginia Tech defeated Auburn 76-61, Tennessee routed Boston 
College 81-53 and Texas Tech got past North Carolina State 85-78. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
</P>
