<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball May Leave Umpires Behind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- If umpires don't want to go to Cuba, they can  
stay behind, major league baseball said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires filed grievances last week to prevent the American  
League from sending them to Cuba for Baltimore's historic 
exhibition game on March 28 and to block the new interpretation of 
the strike zone. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Bud Selig was livid, according to several baseball  
officials. The grievance over the Cuban game was interpreted by the 
commissioner's office as an attempt to get more money for both the 
first leg of the series and the return game in Baltimore on May 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not required to have major league umpires for the game  
in Havana or the game in Baltimore,'' Sandy Alderson, the executive 
vice president of baseball operations in the commissioner's office, 
said Monday, ``If the umpires are not inclined to go, they won't be 
invited to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires union head Richie Phillips said that was fine with him.  
</P>
<P>
	``The umpires always seem to be an afterthought. That kind of  
disrespect the umpires really can't tolerate,'' Phillips said. 
``They'd rather go with four Cuban umpires than negotiate with the 
umpires' association. If that's their inclination, that just proves 
where their coming from.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Selig, according to several officials, is tired of Phillips  
attempting to force his will on owners. Selig planned to shift 
authority over umpires from the league presidents to Alderson this 
year, but was blocked by Phillips. Selig intends to make the change 
after this season, when the umpires' labor agreement expires. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not clear what the next step will be in the strike zone  
grievance. Owners want umpires to call more high strikes. In a Feb. 
19 memo, Alderson told them to raise the top of the strike zone to 
two inches above the top of the uniform pants -- still below the 
definition called for in the official playing rules: the midpoint 
between the top of the shoulders and the top of the uniform pants. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was disappointed but not surprised given the lack of  
communication we've had and the general posture the union has 
taken,'' Alderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires deny the strike zone is a problem, with some saying they  
do enforce the rule as written and others saying players don't want 
them to call high strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, they're going against the rule book,'' NL umpire  
Bob Davidson said. ``I don't think any player has any problem with 
it. I think baseball is succumbing to media pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While some umpires in Florida have called higher strikes,  
Chicago Cubs infielder Gary Gaetti says he hasn't noticed any 
change in calls this spring in Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't seen an effort to call that particular pitch, and I  
haven't noticed anybody complaining,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires think they're caught in the middle of a power struggle  
that pits AL president Gene Budig and NL president Len Coleman, who 
are their legal bosses, against Selig and Alderson. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of flattering,'' Davidson said. ``Everyone wants to  
be in control over us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's still resentment stemming from 1996, when umpires  
attempted to strike the postseason after Roberto Alomar was given 
just a five-game suspension for spitting at umpire John Hirschbeck. 
Representatives of owners, players and umpires met that offseason 
in an attempt to develop a code of conduct, but no code has emerged 
and that committee hasn't met in a over a year, Phillips said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The code of conduct was a sham,'' Phillips said. ``That whole  
concept seems to have gone by the wayside. That was just talk from 
Bud and nothing more than talk from Bud.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
