<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux Upbeat about Penguins Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Mario Lemieux said Monday he has an excellent  
chance of becoming president and co-owner of the Pittsburgh 
Penguins in the next few months. 
</P>
<P>
	``This week is crucial,'' Lemieux said at his official induction  
into the Quebec Major Junior Hockey League's Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``The group I lead has put together the $50 million needed to  
save the Penguins. We have been working on a solid re-establishment 
project for nearly six months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, who later left for meetings in Pennsylvania on Tuesday  
and Wednesday, said his group will present its business plan 
Thursday to a bankruptcy court hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decision whether to accept the plan won't be made for a  
few months,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, who submitted his plan last Thursday to NHL  
commissioner Gary Bettman, declined to identify the other members 
of his group. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're mostly good friends,'' Lemieux said. Later, he  
admitted former Penguins owner Howard Baldwin could be among the 
group members. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux is eager to have his project accepted because he risks  
losing about $32 million owed to him by the current owners in 
delayed salary payments. The Penguins have declared bankruptcy and 
are using a bank loan to support them this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux said he wouldn't be involved in the venture if the  
Penguins didn't owe him money. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't blame me for wanting to protect my assets,'' he  
said. ``But I'm equally concerned about the survival of the 
Pittsburgh Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't spend 12 seasons playing for the Penguins just to  
watch them leave a few years after my retirement. I believe in the 
future of the Pittsburgh franchise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, 33, said he never thought he'd find himself in such a  
situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't part of my retirement plans,'' he said. ``You know  
me -- I don't like to be in the spotlight. But after a couple of 
years of playing golf, I was ready for the challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd even say that after a few months, I'm starting to like it.  
But it looks like it's tougher to be an administrator than a 
player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux said he'll be highly visible as president of the  
Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll attend all the home games and travel with the team. I'll  
be quite a bit more involved than people think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the future of Canadian NHL teams, Lemieux said  
governments should give them more financial support. 
</P>
<P>
	``If governments don't do anything, Canadian teams will have no  
choice but to leave within a few years,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux also said he's pleased to note there's less hooking and  
grabbing nowadays in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's better but there's still room for improvement.''  
</P>
<P>
	The Hall of Fame induction prompted Lemieux to recall some fond  
memories of his last regular-season game in the QMJHL. 
</P>
<P>
	It was March 14, 1984, when Lemieux, playing for Voisins de  
Laval, scored six goals and added five assists. That gave him a 
record 133 goals in a season, surpassing the previous mark of 130 
set by Guy Lafleur. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's league record still stands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
