<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BASF Expects Hard Times </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LUDWIGSHAFEN, Germany (AP) -- The German chemicals company BASF  
posted record earnings in 1998 for the second consecutive year, but 
forecast tougher times ahead and announced plans to cut costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The company earned 3.32 billion marks, or $1.9 billion, in 1998,  
up from a record 3.24 billion marks in 1997. Sales slipped to 54.1 
billion marks, or $30.4 billion, from 55.8 billion marks in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	But Chairman Juergen Strube said Monday that for the first two  
months of 1999, BASF sales were down about 10 percent from a year 
earlier. ``That clearly describes what challenges face us,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strube said results slipped due to the worldwide decrease in  
energy prices and noted a fourth-quarter decline in the chemical 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	The economic crisis in Asia and South America also affected  
BASF, because a surplus of chemicals on the market pushed prices 
down worldwide, Strube said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company hopes to realize $506.2 million in savings from  
measures such as reducing inventory and other operational changes, 
a spokesman said, adding there were no plans to reduce the work 
force of some 105,000 people worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Echoing calls by other companies, notably DaimlerChrysler and  
Allianz Insurance, Strube said BASF demanded the government ease 
the tax burden on German businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	According to BASF, a business slowdown began in the last quarter  
of 1998 with a decrease in sales of about 11.4 percent. Operating 
profit was down 28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Strube said BASF expects to 1999 sales to match those last year,  
although he warned there would be less profit. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
