<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stradivari Violin Goes to Winner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When Judith Ingolfsson was 10, the great  
violinist Josef Gingold autographed one of his record albums for 
her, predicting a fine career for the budding artist. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, the late master's 17th century Stradivari violin  
was handed to the now 25-year-old winner of the Indianapolis 
competition associated with Gingold. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Ingolfsson will make her Carnegie Hall debut in 2000 with  
the brilliant, sweet sound of the Gingold Stradivari. She can play 
the 1683 instrument until it is passed on to the next winner in 
three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has an unbelievable sound, very warm, expansive -- a breadth  
that just hugs the room,'' the beaming musician said as she tuned 
the strings at the shop of violin craftsman Rene Morel. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Ingolfsson won the quadrennial International Violin  
Competition of Indianapolis in September, but it took months of 
negotiations for organizers to acquire the violin with a grant from 
the Lilly Endowment, said Tom Beczkiewicz, founding director of the 
17-year-old competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingold, the contest's artistic director and a former professor  
at the Indiana University School of Music, played the violin for 
five decades as a soloist and as concertmaster of the Detroit and 
Cleveland orchestras. Gingold, a favorite of maestro Arturo 
Toscanini and beloved ``guru'' to such violinists as Itzhak 
Perlman, Pinchas Zukerman and Joshua Bell, died in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	His violin, worth up to $2 million and one of only several dozen  
Stradivaris that have survived in concert-playing shape, ``has a 
very rich, sweet sound -- like Gingold's personality,'' said Morel, 
who kept it in his shop's vault after Gingold's family put it up 
for sale in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Morel has been adjusting it to make the sound big  
enough to fill today's huge concert halls and to satisfy modern 
audiences with a taste for a powerful sonority. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Ingolfsson won the Indianapolis competition playing a less  
valuable Italian instrument for the prize that included the 
Carnegie Hall debut and $30,000. She is the first winner to be 
allowed to use the Stradivari, too. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Iceland who lives in Cleveland, she attended the  
Curtis Institute of Music in Philadelphia and the Cleveland 
Institute of Music. 
</P>
<P>
	She first played for Gingold as a child prodigy while living  
with her parents in Alabama. At the 1984 encounter in Bloomington, 
Ind., the Russian-born master wrote on the LP he gave her: ``May 
your life be filled with beautiful music.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 15:55:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Health Called Top Priority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Forest Service should place forest health  
above all else as it decides how to use 191 million acres of 
national forests and grasslands, scientists recommended Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Committee of Scientists said in a 193-page report that the  
agency should use science in regulating lands, make forest plans 
flexible, ensure that critical species remain viable and consider 
entire regions when developing plans rather than individual 
forests. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Lyons, the Agriculture Department undersecretary who  
oversees the Forest Service, said the agency already is doing much 
of what the scientists recommended. ``What I get is a message ... 
that we're on the right track,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Agriculture Department appointed the 13-member group in late  
1997 to help update forest rules that have been unrevised since 
1982. Most panel members are college professors from schools 
including the University of Michigan, Pennsylvania State University 
and the University of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules guide local forest officials in crafting plans for 155  
national forests that dictate most aspects of forest management, 
from where loggers can work to where a ski chalet can be built. The 
rules also help determine which lands must be left pristine to 
preserve nature. 
</P>
<P>
	More than two-thirds of the plans are to be revised in the next  
three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists were pleased with the panel's emphasis on  
conservation, but industry groups worried the document could lead 
to broad new restrictions on logging, recreation and other forest 
uses. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're moving in a direction that I don't think is supported  
by the laws of this land,'' said Laura Cleland, vice president of 
the Independent Forest Products Association, based in Portland, 
Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists opposed attempted rules updates in 1991 and  
1994 as lacking sufficient public involvement and lacked 
protections for plants and animals. They said the scientists 
redressed those problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully the Forest Service will accept most of the guidance  
it got,'' said Michael Francis, director of national forests for 
the Wilderness Society. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forest Service will now decide which if any recommendations  
to accept and put out draft rules in late spring or early summer. 
Final rules could be complete at the end of the year or in early 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Committee of Scientists didn't work entirely without  
controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	Norman Johnson, an Oregon State University professor who led the  
panel, quit last year when he said he could no longer defend its 
conclusions. His colleagues quickly persuaded him to rejoin the 
effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:36:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> El Paso Energy Buys Sonat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Natural gas supplier El Paso Energy  
Corp. is buying Sonat Inc. for $3.9 billion in stock, extending its 
reach deeper into the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal announced today gives Houston-based El Paso Energy the  
ability to ship gas through pipelines from supply fields in 
California and Texas to growing Southern markets, especially 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``New gas-fueled power generation development is particularly  
active in these areas,'' said El Paso Energy chief executive 
William A. Wise. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will have some 40,000 miles of pipeline  
transporting nearly one-fourth of all the natural gas moved in the 
United States each day. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to swapping stock, El Paso Energy will assume some  
$1.9 billion in Sonat debt. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Energy chief financial officer H. Brent Austin said the  
merger includes 1.6 trillion cubic feet of gas or equivalent 
reserves held by Sonat. The company's Southern operations 
previously were centered around Tennessee Gas Pipeline Co., one of 
five subsidiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors reacted favorably to the deal, with share prices in El  
Paso Energy rising $1.16 to $35.75 a share in early trading on the 
New York Stock Exchange. Sonat was unchanged from Friday's closing 
price of $30.16 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Energy has about 3,600 employees compared to about 1,900  
for Sonat. The merged company will retain the El Paso Energy name 
and be headquartered in Houston, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonat is currently based in Birmingham, and the headquarters of  
Sonat's interstate pipeline, Southern Natural Gas Company, will 
remain there. 
</P>
<P>
	Wise will continue as CEO. Sonat chief executive Ronald L. Kuehn  
Jr. will become chairman of the board until Dec. 31, 2000 for the 
merged company, which will have directors from both companies. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Energy has more than $10 billion in assets. Sonat's  
assets are valued at $4.4 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
