<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 15:34:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Condemns EU Executive Branch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union's executive branch  
came under scathing attack Monday by a panel of experts who say 
they found cronyism and financial irregularities in the upper 
ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Parliament's two largest parties called for the  
resignation of the entire European Commission after the report 
cited several of the 20 commissioners for lax control over aid and 
other programs, for putting friends and relatives on the EU payroll 
and for pleading ignorance when asked why they did not act sooner 
to stop waste and fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, set up by the Parliament, said ``undoubted cases of  
fraud and corruption ... have thus passed `unnoticed''' at the top 
of the institution that runs the EU's day-to-day affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	It dismissed the defense of senior executives who contended they  
did not know matters were so bad. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is becoming difficult to find anyone who has even the  
slightest sense of responsibility,'' the 140-page report concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel found no evidence that any commissioner ``was directly  
and personally involved in fraudulent activities'' or had 
personally enriched themselves. Yet, it said, all bear 
``responsibility for instances of fraud, irregularities or 
mismanagement in their services or areas of special 
responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate reaction from the Commission, which went  
into emergency session Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The report did not call for the dismissal of any of the 20  
commissioners, but members of the European Parliament were quick to 
demand the resignations of some, if not all, of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward McMillan-Scott of Britain, leader of Conservatives in the  
assembly, said the entire commission should step down. 
</P>
<P>
	``The report concerns a culture of cover-up and cronyism ... a  
conspiracy if silence on the part of the commission,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 626-member assembly set up the inquiry by the independent  
experts, including two former EU auditors, in January. 
</P>
<P>
	The report reserved its harshest criticism for Edith Cresson, a  
former French prime minister who is in charge of EU research 
programs. It alleged that she ``failed to act in response to known, 
serious and continuing irregularities over several years'' in 
educational and other programs for which she was responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	It alleged that when told of fraud and waste in an outside  
contractor that squandered $160 million meant for a youth training 
program, she failed to stop the abuses. She also was criticized for 
getting a short-term EU research job for a friend in 1997 for which 
the man was later judged to be unqualified. He was paid for 10 
months but was allegedly sick for nine. 
</P>
<P>
	Magda Aelvoet of Belgium, leader of the Green faction, which was  
instrumental in getting the assembly to launch an independent 
inquiry, told reporters: ``On the basis of these elements, it is 
obvious that Mrs. Cresson has to step down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report condemned others for cronyism, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Regional Development Commissioner Monika Wulf-Mathies of  
Germany, and Portugal's Joao de Deus Pinheiro, the commissioner for 
relations with developing nations, put friends and relatives on the 
EU payroll, it alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	It cited Development Commissioner Manuel Marin, a Spaniard, for  
lax control over the running of an aid scheme for Mediterranean 
nations, for irregularities in hiring and for doing too little to 
stop fraud in the EU's humanitarian aid budget handled through a 
Luxembourg contractor in the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	The commissioners, in appearances before the panel in recent  
weeks, denied any wrongdoing and testified they were unaware of 
sloppiness and fraud by their staffs or outside contractors. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said that only made it worse because a ``sense of  
responsibility is essential (and) must be demonstrated ... by the 
commissioners individually and the Commission as a body.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commissioners are political appointees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
