<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Decision on NFL Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- If the NFL likes what it has seen and heard from  
Houston so much, why doesn't it just give the Texas city an 
expansion team? Simply because the league would like to see and 
hear the same kind of things from Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Team owners on Sunday delayed any decision on where they will  
place a 32nd franchise -- or, indeed, if they will expand anytime 
soon -- even though Houston's bid seems to have all the ingredients. 
What Houston doesn't have is the No. 2 market in the United States, 
something the NFL desperately wants. 
</P>
<P>
	So Los Angeles, despite the presence of competing groups, each  
without a stadium proposal in the same, uh, ballpark with Houston, 
is getting extra time to come up with one. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Los Angeles situation was as far along as Houston's  
situation, we'd come away with a much clearer idea of what will 
happen this week,'' Cleveland Browns president Carmen Policy said. 
``We need a clear relationship with the Los Angeles community and 
the state of California powers that be. I get a sense that the 
stadium plan is not solid in terms of being readily 
implementable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns are the league's 31st team, beginning play this  
season. With an odd number of teams, the schedule gets messy, with 
at least one team off every week -- including the opening weekend 
and the final weekend. Although the 32nd team probably wouldn't 
begin play until 2002, most team owners believe it is imperative 
that the enrollment be expanded. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody who doesn't want a 32nd team isn't looking at it,''  
Steelers president Dan Rooney said. ``We need 32 for the schedule 
and to get eight divisions of four teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Jerry Jones, owner of the Dallas Cowboys, isn't so sure  
expansion is a good idea. He wouldn't be surprised if no decision 
is made at these winter meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's understandable to want a team in Los Angeles and  
a team in Houston. It's more a question of the timing and the 
owners and the stadium,'' Jones said. ``We will do the NFL in Los 
Angeles and in Houston. It's just a matter of how we get to that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think LA is such a great market and we ultimately want a  
team there. But there are so many criteria to base it on, so it 
takes time to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robert McNair, who heads Houston's bid for a new team, isn't so  
patient. He even sent a letter to nine teams he claims ``do not 
have advantageous stadium situations'' to express his group's 
interest in buying a current team and moving it to Houston if the 
city doesn't get an expansion franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	He also realizes that further delays in making a decision helps  
Los Angeles, which lost the Rams and Raiders four years ago. 
Houston lost the Oilers to Tennessee after the 1996 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, you've got some owners who do not want to do  
anything, some owners who want to go to Houston ... Some who want 
to wait and see if something can be put together in Los Angeles,'' 
McNair said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to have to get a coalition of at least two of  
those groups in order to come up with the 24 votes. So there has to 
be some type of compromise to resolve the issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chargers owner Alex Spanos sounded ready to vote for Houston,  
also calling on government officials to get involved in the bidding 
by helping finance a new stadium in the Los Angeles area. 
</P>
<P>
	``The city of Los Angeles hasn't shown it's ready. I'd like the  
city to get involved,'' Spanos said. ``Look at what Houston's 
done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But is it enough? Nobody will know until Tuesday or Wednesday.  
Maybe. 
</P>
<P>
	McNair, an opera buff, was asked which opera this bidding  
process resembles. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know how most operas end,'' he said. ``It depends if you  
are the stabber or the stabbee.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:54:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Landmark D.C. Cafeteria May Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It's not quite the Lincoln Memorial, yet  
Sholl's Colonial Cafeteria, as homey as the rich brown gravy it 
serves, is undisputedly a Washington monument -- a place enjoyed by 
thousands of busloads of people who have come on school visits to 
the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Sholl's, where VIPs dine next to the homeless,  
observed its 71st, and perhaps last, anniversary. 
</P>
<P>
	The cafeteria's rent is going up faster than its profits. And  
despite a ``Save Our Sholl's Committee,'' praise from first lady 
Hillary Rodham Clinton, who calls it an ``warm and welcoming 
organization,'' a T-shirt campaign and well wishes from longtime 
customers, the cafeteria could soon serve its last slice of rhubarb 
pie. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can't negotiate a lower rent, then come this summer  
we'll be out of business,'' says George Fleishell, the proprietor 
who is 71 years old just like the business. He could move, but that 
would cost up to $1 million. ``I don't have the money and I don't 
have the will to go into that much debt,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleishell, who wears a knife-and-fork tie clip, is the nephew of  
founder Evan Sholl. Since 1928, there have been cafeterias at about 
a dozen locations in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The plainspoken Harry S. Truman ate at Sholl's when he was vice  
president. George Wallace dined there when he ran for president in 
1972. Former President Carter stopped in on a visit to Washington. 
Art Buchwald has eaten at the cafeteria. Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., 
is a loyal patron. 
</P>
<P>
	Today there's only one Sholl's. It's in the basement of a modern  
office high-rise about five blocks from the White House. The 
building, owned by Asian businessmen, is represented by Cushman &AMP; 
Wakefield, which did not return phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleishell says the landlord wants to raise the monthly rent from  
$20,000 to $24,000. That's 2,286 more plates of Sholl's $1.75 
meatloaf. 
</P>
<P>
	``My favorite Pennsylvania lunch: Meatloaf with smothered  
onions. I love it,'' exclaimed former Pennsylvania Congressman Fred 
Rooney, who stopped in for lunch on Monday. He got out of there for 
under $4. 
</P>
<P>
	A trendy, high-priced eatery it's not. Roast beef is $2.65. Beef  
stew is just a dime more. Liver and onions is $2.25. There's soup, 
salad, vegetables, fruit and nine kinds of pie. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like plain ordinary cooking and that's what they've got,''  
says Helen Gant, who started eating at Sholl's in the late 1940s. 
</P>
<P>
	No one leaves hungry. Not even the hungry.  
</P>
<P>
	A few years ago, Michael Kirwan, founder of the Llewellyn Scott  
Catholic Worker House of Hospitality, gave $5,000 to the cafeteria, 
printed $12 tan-colored meal tickets and began passing them out to 
poor people on the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somehow that $5,000 check never seemed to run out,'' Kirwan  
said. ``The stories I've heard from people on the streets, their 
quiet moments of dignity, respect, warmth and a full and nourishing 
meal at the hands of this wonderful cafeteria could fill a book of 
essays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the bill was under $12, the cafeteria credited Kirwan's  
account. But when they ate more than $12, the cafeteria, despite 
its financial troubles, absorbed the loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``They do a little,'' Fleishell says modestly as he stuffs the  
tickets back in a safe. ``And we do a little.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 07:33:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gephardt Backs Gore in 2000 Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore secured the  
endorsement today of House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt in a sign 
that top Democrats would like to settle the presidential nomination 
early and focus on winning in November 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt, who decided on Feb. 3 that he would not seek the  
presidency himself, announced his endorsement in Manchester, N.H. -- 
the first stop on Gore's first official political trip of his 
presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm here today because I want to make my fight putting Al Gore  
in the presidency of the United States,'' Gephardt told a 
boisterous rally of 400 activists. ``We would all be proud to have 
him as president of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With a row of American flags as a backdrop, Gore replied in  
kind: ``We are going to make Dick Gephardt the next speaker of the 
House of Representatives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore was headed next to Iowa and St. Louis, Gephardt's hometown,  
before returning to Washington late tonight. ``I'm going to be back 
early and often,'' Gore promised the New Hampshire rally in a 
cramped auditorium. A huge banner read: ``New Hampshire welcomes 
the next president of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt would have been a formidable rival for the nomination  
but decided he stood a better chance of helping Democrats seize the 
House of Representatives in 2000 and become speaker. At a 
Democratic unity rally two weeks ago, Gephardt and Gore hugged on 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's huge,'' Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said of the  
endorsement. ``Obviously, having Congressman Gephardt's support is 
very welcome. The unity that this is going to bring to our effort 
will be extremely helpful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, hoping to begin stepping outside President Clinton's  
shadow, was visiting New Hampshire and Iowa on a one-day swing 
today to address supporters in states that are critical to winning 
the Democratic nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's only announced opponent for the nomination is former New  
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, although civil-rights activist Jesse 
Jackson is considering the race. Opting out in recent weeks in 
addition to Gephardt were three senators who could have offered 
stiff challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, a Hall of Fame basketball player, says he can beat Gore  
one-on-one and win the general election. 
</P>
<P>
	He hopes to capitalize on Democrats' concern about Gore's poll  
numbers. Although the vice president is maintaining a healthy lead 
over Bradley among Democratic voters, he is not fairing as well 
against Republican favorite George W. Bush in public opinion polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore says he's not worried about polls conducted ``four  
lifetimes'' before the election. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I were the Gore campaign I would be concerned,'' said  
Democratic consultant David Axelrod of Chicago. ``But I wouldn't 
panic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic operatives say Gore's two biggest challenges are  
showing that he can be a leader after years as Clinton's understudy 
and convincing Americans that he cares about their problems. 
</P>
<P>
	With those goals in mind, Gore planned to roll out a new stump  
speech to promote initiatives not necessarily part of the 
administration agenda. Promising to make ``revolutionary changes in 
our schools,'' he was calling for reduced class sizes in all 
grades. Clinton had focused on elementary schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president also wants to make preschool available  
everywhere in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore is staking out territory in poll-tested health care issues,  
promising more preventive care options. ``Instead of more breast 
cancer tomorrow, let's have more mammograms today. Instead of more 
low-birth-weight babies tomorrow, let's have more prenatal care 
today. Instead of more sick children tomorrow, let's have more 
immunizations today,'' his stump speech says. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Gore worked from the White House to lay claim to a  
series of bite-size initiatives popular among suburban voters, such 
as promising to ease traffic jams. Fine ideas, Democrats say, but 
he needs to leave Washington to promote his own agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure about that ribbon-cutting strategy. That one  
makes me nervous,'' Axelrod said. ``I think it just underscores the 
second-banana thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the disease that all vice presidents have: You cannot  
be seen as a strong, decisive leader when you're the second man on 
the totem pole,'' said Democratic pollster Mark Mellman. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's biggest advantage, the support of a popular president,  
was being put on display today as he continued to collect 
endorsements from party stalwarts. Bill Shaheen, husband of New 
Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, will formally join the Gore team. In 
Iowa, 70 prominent Democrats are set to side with the vice 
president. Gov. Shaheen and Iowa Gov. Tom Vilsack are still 
neutral. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans say Gore won't escape Clinton's policies or  
controversies. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is the Velcro to Clinton's Teflon,'' said GOP media  
strategist Alex Castellanos. ``A lot of problems that slide off of 
Clinton stick to Gore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore proved last week that is prone to gaffes of his own. He  
claimed that he created the Internet, giving Republicans reason to 
howl. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has done political chores on previous trips, but this is  
the first one in which his campaign organization will pick up part 
of the tab. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
