<HEADLINE> Bucks Fined for Comments by Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The NBA fined the Milwaukee Bucks $25,000 today  
for comments head coach George Karl made about the Seattle 
SuperSonics, the team he formerly coached. 
</P>
<P>
	Karl's comments about Sonics general manager Wally Walker  
appeared in the March 10 edition of the Seattle Post-Intelligencer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wally totally discontinued the communication,'' Karl said.  
``He said it's because I talk too much. I say it's because he's 
incompetent. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were very few negative things negative about Seattle  
outside of Wally. I believe in doing the right things and I don't 
think he does. He's a politician. He's a trickster. And that's 
opposite of how I handle my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The SuperSonics fired Karl last summer despite a sixth straight  
50-win season after another playoff run fell short of the title. 
</P>
<P>
	Karl signed a four-year, $20 million deal with the Milwaukee  
Bucks in August. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know what they try to do,'' Karl said before Monday night's  
game between the Bucks and the New York Knicks in Milwaukee. ``I 
think they try to protect the league, and if they felt I was 
hurting the league, I'm sorry that they felt that way. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that makes me sad is that I think I said 90 percent  
awful positive things about my time in Seattle and about the team 
there because I have a lot of love for the team,'' Karl said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's one human being there that I have problems with,'' he  
said, and ``I guess they don't want me talking about that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
