<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women Debate Breast Implant Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Women who sued Dow Corning Corp. over the  
silicone it manufactured for breast implants face a vote on the 
proposed $3.2 billion settlement plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The claimants, who number in the tens of thousands, have 60 days  
to decide. A packet explaining the deal along with a ballot is 
being mailed to claimants. The ballot must returned by May 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Corning said Monday it would spend $12 million to inform  
women about the settlement. It has set up a call center to handle 
questions about the plan. The center of 200 people will answer 
questions in 30 languages from 8 a.m. until midnight EST. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement is the cornerstone of a $4.5 billion bankruptcy  
reorganization plan, which details how Dow Corning will pay off 
about 570,000 creditors, about 170,000 of whom are women who sued. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Corning filed for bankruptcy under the weight of the breast  
implant suits. Among the other creditors are banks who hold Dow 
Corning's debt, insurance companies, doctors and hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Arthur Spector will hold hearings in June  
on whether the plan should be approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the proposed settlement, women who blame illnesses on Dow  
Corning silicone breast implants could get between $12,000 and 
$300,000 each. Women could also receive up to $25,000 for ruptured 
or leaking implants, and up to $5,000 for implant removal. 
</P>
<P>
	Women who have no problems with Dow Corning implants but still  
filed claims against the company could also settle for $2,000 with 
no questions asked. The plan allows women who joined the case to 
file claims for 15 years after it goes into effect, and also offers 
payments to people who had other types of silicone implants. 
</P>
<P>
	Women outside the United States would be paid 40 percent to 65  
percent less for their claims, depending on where they live. Dow 
Corning said that was due to lower medical costs and different 
economic conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	And for those who reject the money and still want to sue, Dow  
Corning would set aside up to $400 million to cover any costs of 
defending such lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Dow Corning and breast implant plaintiffs said the  
settlement was the best they could do. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan ``is the result of intensive, often acrimonious  
negotiations stretching over a long period of time,'' said 
plaintiffs lawyer Ralph Knowles. 
</P>
<P>
	``There had to be compromise in order to come to some conclusion  
to this litigation in a reasonable period of time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The creditors are divided into several classes. For the  
bankruptcy plan to be approved, a majority of the creditors in each 
class must approve it, and they would have to represent two-thirds 
of the claims in that group. 
</P>
<P>
	While Dow Corning still contends breast implants are safe, ``in  
the end, both sides believed it was far wiser to agree to disagree 
and find common ground,'' said company spokeswoman Barbara 
Carmichael. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys fees would be capped to between 10 and 30 percent of a  
woman's award, with the percentage increasing with the size of the 
award. 
</P>
<P>
	 *---	 
</P>
<P>
	The information number for the United States and Canada is  
1-888-577-7526. Those outside the United States may call collect at 
718-361-4500. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
