<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CIA To Probe China Spy Allegations  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The CIA said today it will investigate whether  
China obtained nuclear weapons secrets through a suspected spy at 
Los Alamos National Laboratory. CIA Director George Tenet said 
retired Adm. David Jeremiah will independently review the findings 
of a multi-agency intelligence team. Last year, Jeremiah oversaw a 
review that found weaknesses in procedures that contributed to the 
CIA's failure to provide adequate warning that India was about to 
test a nuclear weapon. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Albanians OK Peace Deal  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The Kosovo Albanian delegation told peace mediators  
today it is ready to sign an accord that gives wide political 
autonomy but not independence. It leaves Yugoslavia with a choice: 
agree or face NATO's military wrath. The French and British foreign 
ministers praised the decision by the Kosovo Albanians and said it 
will heighten pressure on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to 
accept the deal, which calls for NATO troops to enforce it. 

</P>
<P>
	Gephardt Endorses Gore in 2000 Run  
</P>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, here to kick off  
his 2000 presidential campaign, secured the endorsements today of 
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt and party stalwarts from the 
early battleground states of New Hampshire and Iowa. Gephardt's 
announcement reflects the desire of top Democrats to settle the 
presidential nomination early and set their sights on winning both 
the House and White House in November 2000. Former New Jersey Sen. 
Bill Bradley is the only announced challenger for the party's 
presidential nomination. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Sen. John Chafee Retiring  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican Sen. John Chafee of Rhode Island  
announced today he will retire at the end of the term in a decision 
that strengthens Democratic chances of taking a seat away from the 
GOP. Chafee, 76, said he wants ``to come home'' and would not seek 
a fifth term. During his tenure, he earned a record that 
consistently won the praise of national environmental groups. He's 
bucked GOP orthodoxy on issues ranging from abortion to health 
care. 

</P>
<P>
	Jet Navigator Faces Fewer Charges  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- The Marine Corps said today it's  
dropping involuntary manslaughter and negligent-homicide charges 
against the navigator of the jet that sliced an Italian ski gondola 
cable last year and killed 20 people. Capt. Joseph Schweitzer will 
be tried only on charges of obstructing justice and conspiracy to 
obstruct justice when his court-martial begins Thursday. The 
decision come after a Marine jury on March 4 cleared Capt. Richard 
Ashby, the pilot of the EA-6B Prowler, of similar charges. Ashby 
still faces a trial on obstruction charges. 

</P>
<P>
	Cancer Tumor Enzyme Is Found  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a dramatic advance, researchers have found  
an enzyme that helps build blood vessels that feed growth of cancer 
tumors. Researchers report finding -- on the surface of cells inside 
blood vessels -- ATP synthase. The enzyme apparently provides the 
energy for the growth of blood vessels, said Dr. Salvatore V. Pizzo 
of the Duke University team, the co-author of a study appearing 
tomorrow in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences. 
Without such energy, he said, tumors can never grow beyond the size 
of a pin head. 

</P>
<P>
	Y2K Fix May Only Last a Generation  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Analysts say the most common method used to  
fix computers vulnerable to Year 2000 glitches is only a short-term 
remedy and advocates of the technique say it will need other costly 
repairs or replacements within a generation. One expert describes 
computers already fixed with the technique called ``windowing'' as 
``little ticking time bombs waiting to go off.'' It's being used 
because it saves money and experts hope it will prove adequate 
until these computers are replaced -- or until programmers can 
devote enough time and money to make permanent repairs. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends at Record High: 9,958.77  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average resumed its  
advance toward 10,000 today as a new round of corporate mergers 
sent stock prices higher. The Dow industrials rose 82.42 for a 
record high closing at 9,958.77. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 
1,529-1,443. The Nasdaq composite index was at 2,431.44, up 49.91. 

</P>
<P>
	Nets Fire Coach John Calipari  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- John Calipari, his once-promising team saddled  
with a 3-17 record, was fired today as coach of the New Jersey 
Nets. The dismissal was confirmed by Nets player Kendall Gill. ESPN 
is reporting that the Nets made assistant Don Casey interim coach. 
The network added that Calipari was also dismissed as team vice 
president. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
</P>
</TEXT>
