<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jet Navigator To Face Fewer Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- The Marine Corps said Monday it is  
dropping involuntary manslaughter and negligent-homicide charges 
against the navigator of the jet that sliced an Italian ski gondola 
cable last year and killed 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision came after a jury of eight Marine Corps officers  
decided March 4 to acquit the pilot of the EA-6B Prowler of 
involuntary manslaughter and other charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be unreasonable to continue with these charges  
against the navigator in light of the pilot's acquittal,'' said a 
statement from Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, commander of Marine Forces 
Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y., will be tried  
only on charges of obstructing justice and conspiracy to obstruct 
justice when his court-martial begins Thursday. Each charge carries 
a maximum of five years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Pace decided that the other charges, including 20 counts each of  
involuntary manslaughter and negligent homicide, should be dropped, 
along with such offenses as dereliction of duty and destroying 
government and private property. 
</P>
<P>
	Those charges carried more than 200 years in prison.  
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer's civilian attorney and spokesman, Dave Beck,  
couldn't be reachedfor comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision comes after the acquittal of Capt. Richard Ashby,  
the pilot on similar charges. Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif., 
still faces a Marine trial on obstruction charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The obstruction charges accuse Ashby and Schweitzer of hiding  
and later destroying a videotape that Schweitzer shot during the 
flight. Ashby testified at his trial that Schweitzer took the tape. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 07:23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> El Paso Energy Buys Sonat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Natural gas supplier El Paso Energy  
Corp. is buying Sonat Inc. for $3.9 billion in stock, extending its 
reach deeper into the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal announced today gives Houston-based El Paso Energy the  
ability to ship gas through pipelines from supply fields in 
California and Texas to growing Southern markets, especially 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``New gas-fueled power generation development is particularly  
active in these areas,'' said El Paso Energy chief executive 
William A. Wise. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will have some 40,000 miles of pipeline  
transporting nearly one-fourth of all the natural gas moved in the 
United States each day. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to swapping stock, El Paso Energy will assume some  
$1.9 billion in Sonat debt. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Energy chief financial officer H. Brent Austin said the  
merger includes 1.6 trillion cubic feet of gas or equivalent 
reserves held by Sonat. The company's Southern operations 
previously were centered around Tennessee Gas Pipeline Co., one of 
five subsidiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors reacted favorably to the deal, with share prices in El  
Paso Energy rising $1.16 to $35.75 a share in early trading on the 
New York Stock Exchange. Sonat was unchanged from Friday's closing 
price of $30.16 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Energy has about 3,600 employees compared to about 1,900  
for Sonat. The merged company will retain the El Paso Energy name 
and be headquartered in Houston, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonat is currently based in Birmingham, and the headquarters of  
Sonat's interstate pipeline, Southern Natural Gas Company, will 
remain there. 
</P>
<P>
	Wise will continue as CEO. Sonat chief executive Ronald L. Kuehn  
Jr. will become chairman of the board until Dec. 31, 2000 for the 
merged company, which will have directors from both companies. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Energy has more than $10 billion in assets. Sonat's  
assets are valued at $4.4 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
