<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dem. Convention Brings $140M to L.A. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- When the gavel bangs down to open the  
Democratic National Convention next year, Southern California's 
hospitality industry will be listening for a different sound: the 
ringing of cash registers. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats' decision to bring their national convention to Los  
Angeles will mean an infusion of more than $140 million to the area 
economy and the opportunity to showcase the city's attractions to 
thousands of journalists from around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	The convention in the new Staples Sports Arena is expected to  
attract more than 20,000 people, including 5,000 delegates and 
about 15,000 reporters, photographers, editors and news 
technicians. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a big pop for the hospitality industry,''  
said Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Los Angeles Economic 
Development Corp. ``But the dollar impact is much larger than $140 
million. The idea is you're getting national and international 
exposure. It's one of a few plum events you would like to bring to 
your city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the convention, visitors will rent about 20,000 hotel  
rooms and consume hundreds of thousands of meals and beverages at 
Los Angeles-area restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	The $140 million, a figure provided by the Democratic National  
Committee, only includes money paid by delegates and the news media 
for hotels, food and incidental expenses. More will be spent on 
support services, such as electricians, technicians, carpenters, 
florists and caterers who will be hired to handle evening parties 
that follow the daily convention activities. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you work strictly on a delegate basis, you miss a lot of  
things,'' said Michael Collins, executive vice president of the Los 
Angeles Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``There's probably a 
significantly larger number. It's extremely hard to pin down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates will be housed in hotels throughout the Los Angeles  
area, but they will spend most of their time in the Staples Center, 
the $350 million, 20,000-seat arena under construction on the 
southern edge of downtown. The arena is scheduled to be completed 
in October, nearly a year before the convention opens in August 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In the big picture, revenue generated by the convention will be  
small. Los Angeles County's annual gross domestic product is 
estimated at $282 billion. But if the right impressions are made on 
the visitors, the convention could lead to many millions of dollars 
more in future convention and tourist business. 
</P>
<P>
	Some downtown business already are preparing to attract their  
share of the business. At the Kachina Grill, a popular lunch and 
dinner spot about six blocks from the arena, general manager 
Alfredo Cepeda is hoping for a boost in business. 
</P>
<P>
	Cepeda plans to expand evening hours to lure delegates in for  
drinks and dinner after late convention sessions. He also is making 
arrangements to participate in a shuttle service that will bring 
convention goers near his restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	``It definitely should help us out. I'm already advertising with  
them and in several magazines,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
