<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak Derails Outside Chicago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOURBONNAIS, Ill. (AP) -- An Amtrak train slammed into a truck  
loaded with steel bars at a crossing Monday night, causing several 
cars and engines to derail and starting a fire. At least 30 people 
were injured, some critically. 
</P>
<P>
	The train's engines and passenger cars were scattered over the  
tracks, with smoke pouring from the wreckage two hours after the 
crash. 
</P>
<P>
	An Amtrak manager of operations in Wilmington, Del., who would  
not give her name said two engines overturned and four passenger 
cars derailed and were still upright. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 emergency workers were on the scene, climbing on top  
of the overturned cars and working through twisted metal to rescue 
trapped passengers. One of the cars was burning and Amtrak said one 
engine was on fire. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear how many people were on board.  
</P>
<P>
	Becky Wilder, a spokeswoman for St. Mary's Hospital in nearby  
Kankakee, said 23 people had been brought to the hospital and more 
were coming in. Six were in critical condition, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A nursing supervisor at Riverside Medical Center in Kankakee  
said seven victims had been brought to that hospital so far, 
including one person with an amputated foot and another with head 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed St. Louis, captain of Bourbonnais Fire Protection District,  
said the tractor-trailer that collided with the train came out of 
the nearby Birmingham Steel Company and was loaded with steel bars 
used for reinforcing concrete. 
</P>
<P>
	The City of New Orleans train was bound for New Orleans from  
Chicago. A dispatcher with the Bourbonnais Police Department said 
the collision happened around 9:40 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Amtrak spokeswoman Debbie Hare said the train consisted of two  
engines and 14 passengers cars. She did not know the exact number 
of passengers on board. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
