<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 20:22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson, Best Accept Bench Roles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Mark Jackson and Travis Best are  
competitors, so neither enjoys sitting on the bench watching the 
other play for the Indiana Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Pacers leading the Central Division, though, the duo is  
reluctantly accepting a rotation that has Jackson starting at point 
guard and Best finishing. 
</P>
<P>
	That's been the rotation for the past six games and it is likely  
to continue since it has contributed to five victories with Indiana 
opening a 2 1/2-game lead in the division. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, I'm not happy being on the bench,'' said Jackson, who has  
the league's second highest assist-to-turnover ratio of 3.86 and is 
fifth in assists despite playing about 28 minutes per game. ``What 
I want to do is win, and if we can do it by my being on the bench, 
I'll accept that because it is for the good of the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his 12th season and nearing his 34th birthday, Jackson  
realizes he has to spend some time watching from the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never had great speed, so I'm not really slowing down,'' he  
said. ``Yes, I need a little more rest. What I want is a 
championship and however I can contribute to it, so be it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Best, meanwhile, signed a four-year, $13 million contract when  
the NBA lockout ended. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could have gone elsewhere and gotten more money, but that  
wasn't what I wanted,'' Best said. ``I'm very enthused over being 
here. We nearly got to the finals last season, and the ingredients 
are here to go all the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Best has led the Pacers in assists four times this season and  
has committed just two turnovers with 15 assists as Indiana has won 
its last four games. In those four games, he has contributed six of 
his 13 steals this season and scored 29 points while averaging just 
about 21 minutes per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Best's assists have come in the fourth quarter with  
Indiana battling for a victory. That's when he had all six of his 
assists, along with a 3-pointer that tied the score at 94-94, when 
the Pacers defeated Boston on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love to be out there when the game is on the line and it's  
time to make plays when the crowd is into it,'' Best said. ``I'm 
just happy that the coaches have confidence to leave me out there, 
and let me play at the end of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no competition between Mark and I. He's a great  
teammate and friend. He helped me through some rough times earlier 
in my career, and I respect what he means to this team,'' Best 
said. ``There's going to come a time when I become a starter, but 
there's no point in being selfish as this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers are off to their best start in franchise history and  
Bird insists he has no plan to continue the pattern with his point 
guards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always say that when you play well, you stay in the game,''  
Bird said. ``It has worked out because Travis is playing well. It's 
no reflection on either player how I use them. Travis gives us some 
things that Mark can't give us and Jackson certainly has proven 
himself in his career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Says Jackson: ``I'd be lying if I said I don't want to be out  
there on the court when the game is on the line. But, I hope to be 
a coach someday and I understand the situation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
