<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 11:05:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe May End Duty-Free Shops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union finance ministers failed  
Monday to back an extension of duty-free shopping within the 
15-nation bloc. Those sales are scheduled to end June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministers split over German proposals to grant a temporary  
reprieve for duty-free sales of tobacco, liquor, perfume and other 
goods for travelers crossing borders within the EU. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a long way from unanimity,'' said German Economics  
Minister Werner Mueller. ``I don't have much hope. A majority is 
clearly against an extension.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fate of duty-free shopping will be decided by EU leaders at  
a summit next week in Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	The governments agreed in 1991 to end duty-free sales within the  
union, arguing such benefits were incompatible with a borderless 
Europe. The goods bought in duty-free stores on a traveler's way 
out of a country are not subject to that nation's taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The ban would not apply to duty-free sales for Americans and  
other tourists traveling to or from the EU from countries outside 
the bloc. 
</P>
<P>
	At the French port of Calais, striking workers paralyzed ferry  
service and blocked Eurotunnel trains for six hours to protest the 
expected end of duty-shopping. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferry traffic between Calais and the British port of Dover was  
halted beginning at 9 a.m., and thousands of striking port workers 
blocked the entrance to the Channel tunnel. The protests ended at 
mid-afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	About 100 demonstrators gathered outside EU headquarters in  
Brussels. 
</P>
<P>
	The duty-free industry estimates the ban would destroy over  
100,000 jobs and wipe out an industry with annual sales of some $7 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Mario Monti, the EU's top tax official, insisted the impact  
would be much more limited. He argued the industry costs national 
treasuries some $2 billion a year, with taxpayers picking up the 
tab. 
</P>
<P>
	German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder last month proposed  
extending duty-free shopping for another 2 1/2 years while duties and 
taxes are introduced step-by-step. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
