<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe To Boot Duty-Free Stores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Time is running out for duty-free  
shopping in the European Union as EU finance ministers failed 
Monday to agree on an extension beyond June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The finance ministers split over German proposals to grant a  
late reprieve for duty-free sales of tobacco, liquor, perfume and 
other goodies which are scheduled to be abolished for travelers 
crossing borders within the 15-nation bloc. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a long way from unanimity,'' said German Economics  
Minister Werner Mueller, who chaired the meeting on finance 
ministers. ``I don't have much hope. A majority is clearly against 
an extension.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duty free's fate will now be decided by EU leaders next week in  
Berlin, with the popular travelers' perk looking doomed unless the 
summit produces an unanimous decision to reverse abolition. 
</P>
<P>
	Underlining the high passions the issue raises in Europe,  
thousands of French port workers Monday blockaded the Channel 
tunnel and the ferry port of Calais in protest at the planned 
abolition. About a hundred demonstrators gathered outside EU 
headquarters here. 
</P>
<P>
	The duty-free industry estimates the ban will destroy over  
100,000 jobs and wipe out an industry with annual sales of some $7 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Mario Monti, the EU's top tax official, insisted the impact will  
be much more limited. He argued the industry costs national 
treasuries some $2.2 billion a year, with taxpayers picking up the 
tab. 
</P>
<P>
	``It must end and it will end,'' Monti told reporters. ``We must  
end a situation where ordinary European citizens are paying for 
other people's duty-free and the quite considerable profits of the 
duty-free firms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Having once voted to kill it, Germany, Britain and France are  
now battling to save the industry. But officials warn that without 
agreement at the Berlin summit, it may be impossible to push 
through the necessary legislation before the deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder threw the latest lifeline  
last month by proposing to keep duty-shopping alive for another 2 1/2 
years while duties and taxes are introduced gradually. 
</P>
<P>
	But he appeared not to have swayed the doubters who are led by  
Denmark. ``The feeling is that we will stick to the original 
decision,'' said Finnish Finance Minister Sauli Niinisto. 
</P>
<P>
	All EU governments agreed in 1991 to end duty-free sales within  
the Union, arguing they were incompatible with a borderless Europe. 
Travelers in and out of the EU will still be able to shop 
duty-free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
