<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 15:14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stopping the TV Rerun Madness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Check the television listings and there it  
is, branding program after program:(R). 
</P>
<P>
	That means Rerun. Repeat. Really annoying.  
</P>
<P>
	And it's standard in the post-February ``sweeps'' slump, when  
network shows are recovering from the ordeal of airing a month of 
new episodes to inflate ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	We feasted, so now comes the famine. But here is a modest  
proposal: Maybe it doesn't have to be this way. Maybe there are 
other, more viewer-friendly options than subjecting us to a barren 
TV spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic restraint is the answer, suggests industry veteran Fred  
Silverman, former network executive and now producer (``Diagnosis 
Murder''). And, we might add, a touch of imagination. 
</P>
<P>
	First, the numbers. The 39-episode series, extending throughout  
the official September-to-May TV season and allowing for a 
tolerable 13 weeks of summer reruns, is a thing of the past. 
</P>
<P>
	Network greed prompted the initial decisions to cut episode  
orders back a bit, said Silverman. But the paring continued as 
network costs for an hourlong show rose to the current level of 
about $1.2 million per episode. 
</P>
<P>
	Series now average about 22 episodes, with more than half of  
those concentrated in the three key sweeps months. That's akin to 
an Ally McBeal-sized miniskirt that offers barely enough fabric to 
provide decent coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	In the increasingly competitive TV environment this does not  
represent the kind of customer service that encourages viewers to 
choose broadcast over cable. 
</P>
<P>
	But is it feasible to produce more episodes per season?  
Silverman thinks so. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately, what everybody has got to do is find a way to do  
shows less expensively and to do more of them. That is the solution 
to the problem,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cutting back costs on half-hour comedies is one sensible place  
to start: Big, highly paid writing staffs eat up much of their 
budget, but ``Does all that money really translate on the screen?'' 
Silverman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another drain, he says, is shooting sitcoms in front of an  
audience and keeping a five-day schedule with room for script 
revisions -- too much room, he contends. 
</P>
<P>
	What makes business sense, he said, is giving viewers something  
they can rely on for 35 to 40 weeks of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	It might be tough, however, to squeeze more episodes out of  
stars who already complain of 12-hour-plus workdays (leaving barely 
enough time for a feature film). And producers say keeping quality 
high means fewer episodes. 
</P>
<P>
	So what to do? How about something creative?  
</P>
<P>
	Maybe something like the three-in-one series wheel that worked  
28 years ago. The ``NBC Mystery Movie'' rotated episodes of 
``Columbo,'' ``McMillan and Wife'' and ``McCloud'' and was popular 
enough to last from 1971-78. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea was a hit as well with Weaver, who played McCloud, a  
New Mexico lawman transplanted to New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the most gratifying series that I ever did, the most  
fun and the least stressful,'' Weaver said. ``There were fewer 
episodes, but we took more time with those that we did. The writers 
had more time to flesh out a good story, and I think the general 
production reflected that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Viewers, he added, seemed to enjoy the variety in the Sunday  
night slot. 
</P>
<P>
	Weaver doesn't recall anyone resisting the idea. ``The feeling  
was it was a sensible way to go and had every reason to be 
successful,'' he said. ``It all depends on the quality of the 
writing and the storytelling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Or maybe another approach would work, something like ABC's new  
Tuesday night venture, ``Strange World.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The science-fiction drama is occupying the ``NYPD Blue'' niche  
through March. That means the police drama will return with eight 
new episodes leading up to its May 25 season finale (and spare us 
having to watch Jimmy Smits' character rise from his fresh grave in 
reruns). 
</P>
<P>
	``Strange World,'' which stars Tim Guinee as an ailing scientist  
pressed into government service, is labeled in ABC promotions as an 
``exclusive limited series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to make sure people understood this series ... was  
something a little special; something you could get into but you'd 
be satisfied with when the viewing experience is over,'' said 
Michael Benson, ABC's senior vice president of advertising and 
promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, if ``Strange World'' catches on, ABC would be  
delighted to bring it back as a full-fledged series. But if that 
doesn't happen, Benson said, both viewers and the networks remain 
winners. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think limited series enhance the viewing experience, help  
build the network brand and help the audience understand the 
variety of programming we have,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Short-run programs or an umbrella template like the ``NBC  
Mystery Movie'' are not flawless solutions. An abbreviated series, 
for example, means that a production company loses the chance to 
accumulate the block of episodes needed for a syndication sale. 
</P>
<P>
	And HBO executive Chris Albrecht, whose cable channel excels in  
special programming and limited series, notes that such fare 
requires intense and costly promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	TV is a ``cluttered environment,'' he notes. ``No matter how  
much money you throw at it in the beginning to promote it, by week 
three or four if you are not continually promoting it off-channel 
there are other things that are going to grab media attention or 
the front page of TV guides.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rotating series present different problems. They have to fit  
together logically with no weak leaks. And fewer episodes per year 
means a longer wait to reach the magic 100 shows for syndication. 
</P>
<P>
	Those are certainly considerations. But consider this unsettling  
alternative for viewers: Broadcast schedules packed, if not with 
reruns, then with cheap-to-produce news magazines and banal reality 
shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Envision ``The Big Moment,'' from the producers of ``America's  
Funniest Home Videos,'' taking over the tube. The ABC series, 
coming in April, awards prize money for such feats as pulling a 
cloth off a fully set dining table. 
</P>
<P>
	If TV networks have any compassion -- or intelligence -- they'll  
figure out a way to provide more of the dramas and comedies 
audiences have consistently favored. And not just for the sake of 
viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The alternative is really ugly,'' said Silverman. ``The  
alternative is that everybody will go broke.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	TO THE RESCUE: The adventures of a team of Los Angeles  
paramedics provide the drama in ``Rescue 77,'' a WB midseason 
series debuting 9 p.m. EST Monday. Richard Roundtree (``Shaft'') 
stars as the tough-but-compassionate captain. Marjorie Monaghan is 
the vulnerable heroine, Christian Kane the overzealous hero and 
Victor Browne the smooth operator. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
