<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toronto Still Eying 2008 Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Despite the recent controversies surrounding  
Toronto's bid for the 2008 Summer Games, bid chairman David Crombie 
says the quest for the Olympics is still on track. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're staying the course with this bid,'' Crombie told the  
Toronto Star from his home Sunday. ``As we go down the road and the 
IOC reforms come down we'll be in a better position to win these 
games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto 2008 Olympic Bid Corp., the private company attempting  
to win the Games, was stunned last week with the disclosure that 
International Olympic Committee vice-president Dick Pound had 
resigned from the executive board of the bid in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound said one reason for his departure was a potential conflict  
with his job as head of the IOC's investigation into the Salt Lake 
City corruption scandal. Toronto bid supporters are hoping Pound 
will return to the executive board after the IOC addresses the Salt 
Lake City matter this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Toronto Sun reported today that anger toward Toronto Mayor  
Mel Lastman and the Toronto media also influenced Pound's decision 
to resign. 
</P>
<P>
	In October, Pound said that with Beijing, a favorite to win,  
entering the race, Toronto ``would go from being a clear 
front-runner to somebody who will have to pull up the proverbial 
socks'' in order to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Lastman was angered by the comments and suggested that Pound  
could be positioning himself to succeed IOC president Juan Antonio 
Samanranch. 
</P>
<P>
	Crombie said that Pound had mentioned last year he was  
considering resigning. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did mention back in December that he was thinking of  
leaving our bid committee while he worked for the IOC, but he also 
said that he might return again when he was through and we said 
`Fine. That's your decision, Dick, and your choice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Canadian Olympic Association chief executive  
officer Carol Anne Letheren called Toronto's bid ``ambivalent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no direction,'' she said. ``One day you hear we're  
going to go for it and the next day you hear we're not. Sometime 
soon we're going to have to commit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Crombie admits the bid has had its problems. Just $2 million of  
the estimated $29 million needed to be competitive in the bidding 
process has been raised so far. However, Crombie insists the bid is 
organized. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been serious about this for the last two years,'' he  
said. ``And we've got 500 volunteers working hundreds of hours on 
this thing to prove that we're serious. This is the best time for 
Toronto to go for the Olympics.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
