<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chancellor Media Ends Merger Quest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chancellor Media Corp. is ending its quest for a  
merger partner after just two months, with no takers emerging for 
the $20 billion price tag set by the radio-station empire. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Chancellor is shaking up top management -- with its  
chief executive stepping aside -- and scrapping the planned purchase 
of Lin Television Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said Monday it hopes to revive its lethargic stock  
price by focusing solely on radio and outdoor advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	But investors gave the plan a fuzzy reception Monday, initially  
pushing Chancellor's shares down 11 percent. The stock recovered in 
the afternoon, however, closing $1.18 3/4 higher at $45.56 1/4 on the 
Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe this will all work out, but the point is the story just  
keeps changing and changing and changing,'' said analyst Bishop 
Cheen of First Union Capital Markets. ``Investors like a little bit 
of stability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chancellor -- controlled by the buyout firm Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP;  
Furst -- spent billions to acquire radio and billboard companies 
last year. The pending purchase of Capstar Broadcasting Corp., 
which is also controlled by Hicks Muse, will make Chancellor the 
nation's largest radio group with 467 stations nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	After the aggressive buildup, however, Chancellor surprised Wall  
Street in January by putting itself up for sale because its stock 
price lagged rival radio groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Chancellor had hoped to fetch at least $20 billion, but found no  
suitors willing to meet that price and face the inevitable 
regulatory hurdles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The right thing to do for this company is to stay independent  
as the best group of radio assets in the industry,'' said Thomas 
Hicks, chairman of both Hicks Muse and Chancellor, who will succeed 
Jeffrey Marcus as Chancellor CEO. 
</P>
<P>
	Marcus is stepping down nearly a year after joining Chancellor  
from Marcus Cable Co., where he had been chairman. Hicks said he 
and Marcus jointly decided that Marcus would give up day-to-day 
oversight of Chancellor, but remain a board member. 
</P>
<P>
	Chancellor shares enjoyed a brief boost after the company  
announced it was up for sale on Jan. 20, but soon fizzled amid the 
nagging uncertainties over the company's future. 
</P>
<P>
	Hicks said Chancellor had talked with several potential suitors  
-- which he refused to name -- but never received an offer. Clear 
Channel, the nation's third-largest radio company, had been widely 
seen as the most likely buyer for Chancellor. A Clear Channel 
spokesman did not return a call seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its new strategy, Chancellor is calling off its $900  
million acquisition of Lin Television, which owns or manages 12 TV 
stations and is also controlled by Hicks Muse. 
</P>
<P>
	Hicks said investors told Chancellor they would prefer it to  
focus on radio and outdoor advertising, so Hicks Muse will try to 
build its TV holdings separately through Lin. 
</P>
<P>
	Since television is perceived as having slower growth prospects  
than radio, many investors will prefer Chancellor's decision to 
abandon the Lin deal in favor of paring its debt and cutting costs, 
said Prudential Securities analyst James Marsh. 
</P>
<P>
	Chancellor also said Monday it plans to develop an Internet  
division to seek opportunities for online commerce -- an 
increasingly common strategy among media companies thanks to Wall 
Street's insatiable appetite for anything Internet-related. 
</P>
<P>
	Other moves announced Monday include James de Castro, head of  
Chancellor's radio group, assuming control of the company's outdoor 
advertising businesses, and Steven Hicks, Capstar's president and 
CEO, leading Chancellor's new media efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	Hicks Muse also announced that it will buy an additional $500  
million worth of Chancellor stock over the next two weeks, bringing 
to company's ownership stake to 29 percent once the Capstar deal 
closes. 
</P>
<P>
	Hicks Muse created Chancellor in 1993 to acquire radio companies  
in large markets. Its flagship stations now include WHTZ-FM, a top 
40 station in New York, and KHKS-FM, a top 40 station in Dallas. 
The company also provides syndicated programming, including Casey 
Kasem's long-running ``American Top 40.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
