<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft's Allen Buys Go2Net Share </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Billionaire Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen  
agreed to buy a $300 million majority share in Go2Net Inc., in a 
deal that could make Go2Net's Web sites a main Internet destination 
for many cable-TV users. 
</P>
<P>
	Go2Net's stock soared by nearly a third on the news, rising  
$26.37 1/2 to $113.37 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Redmond, Wash-based company runs a network of Web sites  
focusing on personal finance, Internet search, commerce and games. 
Allen's investment firm, Vulcan Ventures, owns stakes in cable-TV 
companies that provide high-speed Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	Providing an Internet portal -- a jumping-off point for Web  
exploration -- to cable customers ``will be a critical component in 
the future of cable,'' Allen said in a statement Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	An Allen spokeswoman said it was too early to say exactly how  
Go2Net's Web sites would be presented to cable-TV subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen's Vulcan Ventures recently bought interests in Marcus  
Cable of Dallas and Charter Communications of St. Louis, making him 
the world's seventh-biggest cable operator with 2.4 million cable 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen's investment gives him a 54 percent interest in Go2Net.  
Vulcan Ventures bought about $165 million in Go2Net stock on Monday 
and plans to buy the rest after shareholder approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Go2Net executives estimate the deal could close within 60 days.  



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
