<HEADLINE> Caves Checked in Sightseers Search </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MODESTO, Calif. (AP) -- About 1,000 people marched in a ``vigil  
of hope'' to lend comfort to two families searching for their 
relatives who disappeared one month ago while visiting Yosemite 
National Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those who attended Sunday's march were the families of  
Carole Sund, her 15-year-old daughter Julie and 16-year-old 
Argentine exchange student Silvina Pelosso. 
</P>
<P>
	Silvina's mother, Raquel Pelosso, said it ``makes you feel  
better to know you have so much support from the community. Perhaps 
something can come out of this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three women were last seen at a lodge near Yosemite. Their  
rental car is still missing and Mrs. Sund's wallet was found in 
Modesto. No suspects have been named. 
</P>
<P>
	A relative said Mrs. Sund's husband, Jens, did not attend  
because he was emotionally exhausted and had returned to the 
family's home in Eureka. Sund issued a statement saying, ``We are 
reminded of the fact Julie is missing because of the silence of the 
piano and the phone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other family members who spoke at the vigil included Mrs. Sund's  
father and mother. They were comforted by the families of other 
missing children. 
</P>
<P>
	A poem written by daughter Regina Sund was read: ``At a time  
when I need my mother's touch most, all I see of her are pictures 
nailed to a post. When it is time for bed, I rock myself to 
sleep.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the people attending the vigil was Minnie Norrell of  
Pittsburg, whose 15-year-old daughter, Lisa, disappeared in 
November after a party and was found slain days later near a garden 
center in Antioch. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I sat down the whole eight days my daughter was  
gone,'' she said. ``I just kept looking out the window.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
