<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CIA To Probe China Spy Allegations  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The CIA announced today it is launching a  
probe into whether China gained top-secret know-how on building 
multiple-warhead nuclear weapons from a Taiwanese-born scientist 
who worked at Los Alamos National Laboratory. CIA Director George 
Tenet said retired Adm. David Jeremiah will conduct an independent 
review of the work now being done by a multiagency intelligence 
team. It is the second such assessment Jeremiah has been asked to 
oversee since last year, when he led a team that found weaknesses 
in intelligence community procedures that contributed to the CIA's 
failure to provide adequate warning that India was about to test a 
nuclear weapon. 

</P>
<P>
	Cuba Sentences 4 Dissidents to Jail  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Risking international criticism, the government  
today sentenced one of Cuba's best-known dissidents to five years 
in prison and set lesser terms for his three co-defendants. The 
sentences could hold international repercussions for Cuba, which 
has worked to improve its ties with other nations, particularly in 
the Caribbean and Latin America. Several European nations pressured 
Cuba to free the four dissidents, who were arrested in 1997 for 
criticizing a Communist Party document that they said did not 
present solutions to Cuba's severe economic problems. Cuba insists 
there are no political prisoners and reject the characterization of 
the four dissidents as prisoners of conscience. 

</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians 'Ready To Sign'  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Kosovo Albanians told mediators they would agree to  
a pact that gives them autonomy but keeps the province within Serb 
borders. Prospects haven't looked good for a Serb-ethnic Albanian 
deal, with the Serbs refusing the deployment of NATO troops. The 
Kosovo Albanians, who represent 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million 
people, had also been reluctant to sign because they are not 
getting the independence they seek, and their guerrillas would have 
to be disarmed. More than 2,000 people have died and 300,000 have 
lost their homes in a year of fighting in Kosovo between the 
secessionist Kosovo rebels and Serbian security forces. 

</P>
<P>
	Reno Looks To Curb Internet Crime  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno says a new  
public-private alliance to curb Internet crime will help teach 
children ``that hacking is the same as breaking and entering.'' She 
announced the formation of a new education campaign that's designed 
to promote cyberspace ethics and help law enforcement officials 
track down online criminals. It also features a ``personnel 
exchange program'' between private business and federal agencies in 
which both will learn how the other responds to threats and crimes 
over the Internet. 

</P>
<P>
	Trial of WWII Commander Resumes  
</P>
<P>
	ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- The commander of the Balkans' most  
notorious World War II concentration camp returned today to court 
to face charges involving torture, killings and mass persecution. 
The trial of 77-year-old Dinko Sakic was delayed Friday after he 
fainted and was hospitalized with severe circulatory problems and 
high blood pressure. Sakic is charged with having a role in the 
deaths of some 2,000 inmates during the eight months he commanded 
the Jasenovac camp in 1944. He could face up to 20 years in prison 
if convicted. 

</P>
<P>
	Y2K Fix May Only Last a Generation  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Analysts say the most common method used to  
fix computers vulnerable to Year 2000 glitches is only a short-term 
remedy and advocates of the technique say it will need other costly 
repairs or replacements within a generation. One expert describes 
computers already fixed with the technique, called ``windowing'' as 
``little ticking time bombs waiting to go off.'' It's being used 
because it saves money and experts hope it will prove adequate 
until these computers are replaced -- or until programmers can 
devote enough time and money to make permanent repairs. 

</P>
<P>
	Rock Hall To Induct New Members  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After dominating radio in the 1970s, singers  
Bruce Springsteen, Paul McCartney and Billy Joel will be inducted 
tonight into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame during a ceremony at 
the Waldorf Astoria Hotel. They join Dusty Springfield, who died 
two weeks ago, ``Superfly'' singer Curtis Mayfield, already in the 
hall as a member of the Impressions; Del Shannon, who made 
``Runaway'' a hit in 1961; and the gospel group The Staple Singers. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 74 to 9,951  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before the close, the Dow industrials were  
up 74.93 to 9,951.28. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,508-1,418. The Nasdaq was up 41.05 to 
2,422.58. 

</P>
<P>
	Jimenez, Sjoland Added to Masters  
</P>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- The Masters golf tournament today increased  
its largest field in 23 years by offering special invitations to 
two players who finished among the top five on the European golf 
tour. The additions of Miguel Angel Jimenez of Spain and Sweden's 
Patrik Sjoland swelled the ranks at the prestigious golf event to 
104, including past champions Byron Nelson and Gene Sazaren. The 95 
players expected to compete is the largest field since 103 played 
in 1966. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
</P>
