<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Loser in Nigeria Vote Files Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- The loser of Nigeria's presidential  
election filed a protest of last month's results Monday, despite 
fears a dispute could derail the West African nation's return to 
civilian rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Finance Minister Olu Falae, who was defeated by retired  
Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, led a team of lawyers into the Court of 
Appeals in Abuja to file the protest. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Nigerians, including those who didn't support Obasanjo,  
oppose challenging the vote. There is widespread fear that a 
protest would simply encourage Nigeria's military -- with its long 
history of coups -- to seize power again, or to postpone the May 29 
handover to civilian rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Falae said many people had discouraged him from filing a  
protest. 
</P>
<P>
	``Very few have said `go to court,''' he said. ``But my  
conscience has told me to go to court and to court I am going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The protest accuses Obasanjo's agents of offering money, rice,  
curry and salt to buy votes before, and on the day of, the Feb. 27 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	It also says Obasanjo was not a valid candidate because of his  
alleged membership in a secret society and because he had been 
convicted of treason. 
</P>
<P>
	Obasanjo is reportedly a member of the Ogboni, one of a number  
of Nigerian secret societies that include some of the nation's most 
powerful businessmen and politicians. Nigeria's elections rules 
preclude members of secret societies from running for president. 
</P>
<P>
	The treason allegation stems from Obasanjo's conviction for  
participating in an alleged 1995 coup plot against Nigeria's former 
dictator, Gen. Sani Abacha. The plot is widely believed to have 
been invented by Abacha to imprison his political enemies. Obasanjo 
was pardoned and released from prison after Abacha's death in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Obasanjo won the elections with 63 percent of the vote. Nigerian  
and international monitors have also criticized the election, 
saying supporters of both candidates engaged in ballot-box stuffing 
and inflated vote returns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:05:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Times Delayed China Espionage Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- At the request of the FBI, The New York Times  
held up for one day a front-page story about China's theft of U.S. 
nuclear secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper refused a second request from the FBI to hold the  
story for another day. 
</P>
<P>
	The article said that China had miniaturized its nuclear bombs  
using information stolen from Los Alamos National Laboratory in New 
Mexico. The story was supposed to run on March 5. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI asked the Times to delay the article because the main  
suspect in the theft, a Taiwanese-American scientist, was due to be 
interviewed by the bureau that day. 
</P>
<P>
	The story contained at least two facts the scientist didn't  
know, including his failing a lie detector test, Times executive 
editor Joseph Lelyveld told The Washington Post. 
</P>
<P>
	Lelyveld told the Post that when the FBI asked the Times to hold  
off for a second day, he said he would only do so if FBI Director 
Louis Freeh called him directly. When Freeh failed to call by 7 
p.m., Lelyveld went ahead with the story. It appeared March 6. 
</P>
<P>
	The story did not name the suspect, Wen Ho Lee. Two days later,  
he was fired. He has not been charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Times spokeswoman Lisa Carparelli confirmed that the Times  
delayed publication for a day at the FBI's request. She was unable 
to provide further details. 
</P>
<P>
	Lelyveld did not immediately return a call for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Bill Carver, an FBI spokesman in Washington, refused to comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Journalism Review editor Marshall Loeb said the  
practice of editors delaying stories at the request of government 
officials is appropriately rare. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is legitimate for an editor to hold a story for a brief  
period if he or she has persuasive reason to believe that reporting 
it might endanger national security or hurt a significant criminal 
investigation,'' Loeb said. ``But such withholding should be done 
only rarely and only when a really important issue is at stake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Loeb said the most famous example of a newspaper honoring such a  
request was when President Kennedy asked the Times to withhold 
disclosing the Bay of Pigs invasion before it began. 
</P>
<P>
	``They withheld it much to the regret of one and all,'' Loeb  
said. ``Had the information been revealed, there might have been 
sufficient public outcry to get the whole operation called off. In 
the end, the operation was a total fiasco.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 15:31:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Flyers Still Stuck in Losing Streak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Finally, there was some fight in the  
Philadelphia Flyers. Of course, it came from captain Eric Lindros. 
</P>
<P>
	Since arriving in Philadelphia seven years ago, Lindros has come  
to personify a proud organization that even in down years has been 
about toughness and aggression. 
</P>
<P>
	Though they showed signs of life in a 1-1 tie with NHL-leading  
Dallas Sunday night, the Flyers are still mired in their longest 
winless streak in 28 years. Where do the Flyers go from here? 
</P>
<P>
	``The worst thing to do when things are not going well is sit  
back and give your problems to somebody else,'' said Lindros, who 
took the Flyers' slump into his own hands by starting a fight with 
Stars captain Derian Hatcher 40 seconds into the game. ``... We 
need a win. I guess we'll have to wait until Tuesday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers, who have plummeted from first to fifth in the  
Eastern Conference in only a month, are 0-7-4 during an 11-game 
winless streak that ties the franchise record set in the 1968-69 
season and equalled in 1970-71. A loss or tie in St. Louis Tuesday 
night would set a club record for futility. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers are 2-11-5 since going unbeaten in 23 of 24 games  
from Dec. 12 to Feb. 6, a confounding turnaround that no one in the 
organization seems able to explain. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Bob Clarke and Roger Neilson canceled a team  
retreat planned for New Orleans this week. After playing in St. 
Louis Tuesday night, the Flyers return to Philadelphia to practice 
instead of heading for Bourbon Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``First off, we don't deserve to be going,'' Lindros said. ``If  
we played the way we did tonight the previous three weeks, we'd be 
going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two days after Flyers chairman Ed Snider questioned the team's  
mental toughness, Clarke gave the players a stern talk several 
hours before Sunday night's game. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came in and gave a talk about the Flyers organization and  
what was expected,'' Neilson said. ``It was a good strong talk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though he said he didn't mind, it must have been an eerie  
situation for Neilson, presumably the ruler of the locker room. 
While Neilson is the coach, he's been a member of the organization 
for less than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarke, the captain of Philadelphia's last Stanley Cup  
championship team in 1974, viewed himself as a much better choice 
for a speech about what it means to be a Flyer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes a different voice telling them the same thing  
helps,'' Clarke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several players revealed that Clarke's speech was mostly about  
playing physical hockey, a trait that has always personified the 
Broad Street Bullies but has been absent during the month-long 
slide. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just talked about playing hockey, taking the body,''  
forward Jody Hull said. ``We talked about having trust that if 
something broke down you'd have your teammate right there behind 
you to help out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros wouldn't comment on Clarke's meeting, but no one seemed  
the least but surprised by it. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's to be expected when things are going that bad,''  
defenseman Eric Desjardins said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Neilson, Clarke mentioned nothing about fighting.  
But the Flyers' inexplicable failure to protect each other -- and 
retaliate for physical play -- has been one of the disturbing 
developments during their slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as he did when Clarke challenged him to become the best  
player in hockey during the offseason, Lindros took Clarke's 
challenge personally. Immediately after the opening faceoff, he ran 
at Hatcher with the obvious intention of starting a fight -- with 
the toughest player on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Though they still didn't eliminate defensive giveaways that have  
hounded them, at least the Flyers looked interested, hit hard and 
stuck up for each other. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros' next job is to show his teammates how to win again.  
</P>
<P>
	``He showed to everybody on the other side that he was here for  
a war, for a battle,'' Desjardins said. ``I think we followed him 
well after that. That's what we've got to do. That's what we need 
from him. We can't just watch what he's going to do, we've got to 
do it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
