<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 15:31:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Flyers Still Stuck in Losing Streak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Finally, there was some fight in the  
Philadelphia Flyers. Of course, it came from captain Eric Lindros. 
</P>
<P>
	Since arriving in Philadelphia seven years ago, Lindros has come  
to personify a proud organization that even in down years has been 
about toughness and aggression. 
</P>
<P>
	Though they showed signs of life in a 1-1 tie with NHL-leading  
Dallas Sunday night, the Flyers are still mired in their longest 
winless streak in 28 years. Where do the Flyers go from here? 
</P>
<P>
	``The worst thing to do when things are not going well is sit  
back and give your problems to somebody else,'' said Lindros, who 
took the Flyers' slump into his own hands by starting a fight with 
Stars captain Derian Hatcher 40 seconds into the game. ``... We 
need a win. I guess we'll have to wait until Tuesday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers, who have plummeted from first to fifth in the  
Eastern Conference in only a month, are 0-7-4 during an 11-game 
winless streak that ties the franchise record set in the 1968-69 
season and equalled in 1970-71. A loss or tie in St. Louis Tuesday 
night would set a club record for futility. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers are 2-11-5 since going unbeaten in 23 of 24 games  
from Dec. 12 to Feb. 6, a confounding turnaround that no one in the 
organization seems able to explain. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Bob Clarke and Roger Neilson canceled a team  
retreat planned for New Orleans this week. After playing in St. 
Louis Tuesday night, the Flyers return to Philadelphia to practice 
instead of heading for Bourbon Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``First off, we don't deserve to be going,'' Lindros said. ``If  
we played the way we did tonight the previous three weeks, we'd be 
going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two days after Flyers chairman Ed Snider questioned the team's  
mental toughness, Clarke gave the players a stern talk several 
hours before Sunday night's game. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came in and gave a talk about the Flyers organization and  
what was expected,'' Neilson said. ``It was a good strong talk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though he said he didn't mind, it must have been an eerie  
situation for Neilson, presumably the ruler of the locker room. 
While Neilson is the coach, he's been a member of the organization 
for less than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarke, the captain of Philadelphia's last Stanley Cup  
championship team in 1974, viewed himself as a much better choice 
for a speech about what it means to be a Flyer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes a different voice telling them the same thing  
helps,'' Clarke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several players revealed that Clarke's speech was mostly about  
playing physical hockey, a trait that has always personified the 
Broad Street Bullies but has been absent during the month-long 
slide. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just talked about playing hockey, taking the body,''  
forward Jody Hull said. ``We talked about having trust that if 
something broke down you'd have your teammate right there behind 
you to help out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros wouldn't comment on Clarke's meeting, but no one seemed  
the least but surprised by it. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's to be expected when things are going that bad,''  
defenseman Eric Desjardins said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Neilson, Clarke mentioned nothing about fighting.  
But the Flyers' inexplicable failure to protect each other -- and 
retaliate for physical play -- has been one of the disturbing 
developments during their slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as he did when Clarke challenged him to become the best  
player in hockey during the offseason, Lindros took Clarke's 
challenge personally. Immediately after the opening faceoff, he ran 
at Hatcher with the obvious intention of starting a fight -- with 
the toughest player on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Though they still didn't eliminate defensive giveaways that have  
hounded them, at least the Flyers looked interested, hit hard and 
stuck up for each other. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros' next job is to show his teammates how to win again.  
</P>
<P>
	``He showed to everybody on the other side that he was here for  
a war, for a battle,'' Desjardins said. ``I think we followed him 
well after that. That's what we've got to do. That's what we need 
from him. We can't just watch what he's going to do, we've got to 
do it.'' 
</P>
