<DOCNO> APW19990315.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 01:41:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GPS Technology Used To Nab Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- The television cop shows have it all  
wrong. Fact is, it's virtually impossible to track a crook in an 
unmarked car. 
</P>
<P>
	A better way? Let satellite technology do the legwork.  
</P>
<P>
	Police figured that out here last summer when they followed the  
movements of a Centre County man suspected of setting dozens of 
fires. 
</P>
<P>
	With a warrant from the court, they slipped a Global Positioning  
System receiver on the suspect's Isuzu Trooper. Then, using 
satellites and cell-phone technology, they tracked his movements on 
a laptop back at the station. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's neat, neat stuff,'' said Oak Norton, owner of Intelldex  
Inc., a State College private investigation firm that lent the 
equipment to the police. ``It makes your work a lot easier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The companies that sell the GPS trackers are cagey about who  
their police clients are, for fear of blowing a department's cover. 
Law enforcement is also quiet about its use: the FBI would 
``neither confirm nor deny'' employing the technology. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Pennsylvania arson case reveals some the technology's  
power. 
</P>
<P>
	David Beer, 39, became a suspect in the arsons after several  
people said they saw him hanging around Dumpsters that later caught 
fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Police started tracking Beer covertly. But that took a lot of  
manpower, and involved risk. At one point, an officer watching 
Beer's house barely escaped detection after Beer walked right up to 
the van, pressing his face to the glass to peer inside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to stay still,'' Officer Matthew Wilson testified during  
a preliminary hearing. ``Even the chair I was in would have 
squeaked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the GPS tracker, the officer could have been back at  
headquarters keeping an eye on the suspect. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can actually sit at the computer and watch the unit move  
from street to street, town to town,'' Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	In using the GPS, police occasionally tailed Beer to visually  
confirm he was driving the car and that the car was where the 
program said he was. One hitch: Like a cell phone, the tracker went 
off-line when trees, mountains and buildings blocked the signal. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, authorities said, the device helped link Beer to a  
Sept. 2 fire and hastened his arrest on charges of arson, criminal 
mischief and reckless endangerment for 25 fires, including a car 
fire and an apartment building blaze that caused $500,000 in 
damage. He is awaiting trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Beer's attorney, Ron Travis, said he expects to ask the judge to  
suppress the GPS evidence, although he has not thoroughly 
investigated the technology yet. 
</P>
<P>
	An American Civil Liberties Union official said the GPS tracker  
does not concern him any more than normal police surveillance. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that there's some court intervention certainly makes  
it less scary,'' said Larry Frankel, director of the Pennsylvania 
chapter of the ACLU. 
</P>
<P>
	Remote tracking technology has been around for decades, Norton  
said, but most of the receivers could not transmit farther than a 
fraction of a mile. Current systems can track something anywhere in 
the world. 
</P>
<P>
	State College police, who have been promised future access to  
the tracker, are ecstatic about GPS. 
</P>
<P>
	``No. 1, the accuracy of the system is incredible,'' Sgt. John  
Wilson said. ``No. 2, it replaces manpower. This system replaces, 
at a minimum, four people. No. 3 is the covertness of it. The 
target would have no knowledge of this. It reduces the possibility 
of an undercover officer being spotted. And it provides 24-hour 
coverage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The whole system cost $2,400, but Norton lent it to the  
department for free. 
</P>
<P>
	``They wanted it to stay online 24 hours a day,'' said Tom  
Moody, president of Boulder, Colo.-based Tracking Products Inc, 
which custom-built the system for Norton, then tweaked it for the 
police. ``Man, I don't want to see that cell bill.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
