<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock Market 
and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *UAL Corp. rose 6 11/16 to 73 3/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	An industrywide fare increase and a positive earnings outlook  
boosted the parent company of United Air Lines. UAL said it expects 
to exceed analysts' earnings expectations in the first quarter, due 
in part to the February pilots' sickout at rival AMR Corp.'s 
American Airlines. 

</P>
<P>
 *Pioneer HiBred International Inc. rose 4 1/16 to 38 3/8.  
</P>
<P>
 *DuPont Co. fell 1 1/2 to 56 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Chemical giant DuPont will pay $7.7 billion for an 80 percent  
stake in Pioneer, the world's largest seed corn company. Shares of 
Pioneer shot up 40 percent Friday after the companies disclosed 
they were in talks on a possible business combination. 

</P>
<P>
 *America Online Inc. rose 5 7/8 to 102.  
</P>
<P>
 *Netscape Communications Corp. rose 6 1/8 to 91 on Nasdaq 
</P>
<P>
	AOL was the second most heavily traded stock on the NYSE,  
benefiting from the Justice Department's approval of its plan to 
buy Netscape Communications Corp. Netscape shareholders are 
expected to vote on the deal Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
 *Schwab Corp. rose 3 15/16 to 87 15/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The discount brokerage said its first-quarter earnings will  
exceed analysts' expectations, due mainly to strong trading volume. 
The company said average daily trading volume was 69 percent higher 
last month than in February 1998. 

</P>
<P>
                              *Nasdaq    	

</P>
<P>
 *Metamor Worldwide Inc. rose 2 13/16 to 16 15/16.  
</P>
<P>
 *SPR Inc. fell 4 3/4 to 4 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Metamor and SPR canceled their merger pact, saying the deal  
wasn't in shareholders' best interests. In January, Metamor offered 
to pay $315 million for SPR, a rival computer-staffing services 
company. 

</P>
<P>
 *EFax.com Inc. rose 8 7/8 to 21 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The Menlo Park, Calif. Internet communication company agreed to  
provide free fax-to-electronic mail service to members of Xoom.com 
Inc. Xoom is an Internet direct-marketing service that also runs a 
popular Web site. 

</P>
<P>
 *Onyx Software Corp. rose 16 13/16 to 44 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	Chairman and CEO Brent Frei said in an interview broadcast on  
CNBC that Onyx has gained market share from larger competitors. The 
maker of enterprise-management software surged nearly 55 percent 
Friday after Credit Suisse First Boston Corp. initiated coverage 
with a buy rating. 

</P>
