<HEADLINE> FAA OKs Sea-Launched Spacecraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Government officials said Monday they have  
given the go-ahead for the first space launch from a seagoing 
platform. 
</P>
<P>
	Sea Launch, an international consortium that includes the  
U.S.-based Boeing Co. as a 40 percent partner, will use a 
Ukrainian-built booster rocket and a Russian-built upper stage for 
an unmanned demonstration launch in the Pacific Ocean scheduled for 
March 27. 
</P>
<P>
	The launch platform is a converted self-propelled oil-drilling  
platform. The rockets are transported to the launch site and 
controlled afterward from a separate assembly and command ship. 
</P>
<P>
	Sea Launch is designed to launch communications satellites, and  
it gains several advantages by firing them from a midocean location 
at the Equator. 
</P>
<P>
	It benefits from the maximum rotational forces of Earth, which  
give its rockets extra momentum entering orbit. Also, since large 
geostationary communications satellites must orbit over the 
equator, its position can boost them by the most direct route. 
</P>
<P>
	That allows Sea Launch to lift heavier-than-normal payloads.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is the beginning of an exciting new era in commercial  
space launch activity,'' said a statement issued by FAA 
Administrator Jane Garvey. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA's commercial space office had to assess the safety  
aspects of a system comprising components from several nations and 
being launched from a mobile platform 3,000 miles from its home 
port of Long Beach, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	An FAA safety monitor will be aboard the command ship for the  
demonstration launch. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
