<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympic Tickets Go on Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Fans wanting to purchase tickets for  
the 2000 Sydney Olympics will have to wait a little longer. 
</P>
<P>
	Tickets for the games officially went on sale Monday, but people  
were only able to request brochures that will be sent out by Cartan 
Tours Inc., the U.S. Olympic Committee's official travel agent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The brochure is available today and people will get it in the  
mail in a week or two,'' said Don Williams, Cartan's vice president 
of marketing and sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said the United States has been allotted 200,000 of the  
9.6 million tickets, but the company has requested 50,000 more. 
Tickets won't be available in Australia for almost two months. 
</P>
<P>
	Cartan Tours offers packages ranging from a six-night stay in a  
private home for $4,900 to a six nights in a five-star hotel for 
$7,400. The prices are per person. 
</P>
<P>
	Tickets to the events are not included in that price, but the  
packages encompasses round-trip airfare, food and daily 
transportation to and from the events. 
</P>
<P>
	Ticket prices for the events will range from $8 for preliminary  
rounds to more than $1,000 for premium opening and closing ceremony 
seats. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said the demand for tickets has not decreased even  
though the 2000 Summer Games will take place later than usual, in 
September, conflicting with children's school schedules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
