<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SW Mo. St. Fans Loving NCAA Ride </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) -- When Southwest Missouri State superfan  
T.J. Lordis had his silkscreen business print up hundreds of ``Go 
Bears'' T-shirts for the NCAA tournament, he knew he might be doing 
business with his heart and not his head. 
</P>
<P>
	This was a team, after all, that some said got into the NCAA  
tournament through the back door, having to wait for an at-large 
bid after failing to make it to the finals of its own Missouri 
Valley Conference tournament. It would probably be booted right out 
the front door after its first game with Wisconsin, seeded No. 5 in 
the East Regional. 
</P>
<P>
	But all that was forgotten in Springfield on Monday, after SMS's  
Bears not only upset Wisconsin 43-32 but then demolished Tennessee 
81-51 in the second round. That second win puts the Bears into the 
round of 16 for the first time and sets up a showdown Friday with 
No. 1 Duke. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bring on Duke!'' shouted Lordis, laughing Monday as he took a  
quick break between fielding dozens of calls from fans wanting 
shirts from the next batch he was producing, these emblazoned with 
the words, ``Bring on Duke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springfield's beloved Bears had become the little team that  
could. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of exciting when you're watching ESPN or NBC or  
whatever and you see names of big schools like Tennessee, 
Connecticut on the screen. And right up there with them, there's 
little old Southwest Missouri,'' said Angie Curran, assistant 
manager of the Classic Sports Bar, which was packed Sunday with 
patrons cheering on the Bears. 
</P>
<P>
	``Especially after they got the name right,'' laughed Russ  
Robinson, whose father played basketball for SMS in the 1950s. 
``For a while there they had it SWMS every time I looked up. I'm 
glad they got that straightened out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But some folks fretted just a bit at the thought of the world  
finally getting to know SMS just before the Duke game. 
</P>
<P>
	``They play like an NBA team,'' Robinson said of Duke. ``I don't  
how we can beat them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But others, like Lordis, would not be deterred. After all, no  
one but SMS seemed to think it could beat Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're playing like a Big Ten team right now,'' he said. ``We  
can beat anybody right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russ Koeneman, whose Russ' Sports Bar stood nearly empty Monday  
afternoon, reflecting the calm before a storm that would be a 
hundred or more patrons cheering on the Bears against Duke there 
Friday, also was quietly confident. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think they'll embarrass us,'' he said, smiling. ``How  
will they win? Play strong defense. Play hard. Outscore 'em. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the great thing about a basketball game,'' he  
continued, chuckling. ``That's all you've got to do. Outscore 'em. 
You put two teams on the floor and both have to play for 40 
minutes. And we certainly showed over the weekend that we can play 
those 40 minutes with anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a level of play that left even the Bears overwhelmed.  
</P>
<P>
	``What a ride we're on, what a ride,'' said guard William  
Fontleroy afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the ride's biggest beneficiaries in this Ozarks town of  
150,000 is fourth-year coach Steve Alford, who was no stranger to 
criticism when his 20-10 team struggled at times during the regular 
season, then was eliminated from its conference tournament in the 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Alford, 34, had played on a national champion at Indiana in 1987  
and on a USA team that won the Olympic gold medal in 1984. And when 
he arrived in Springfield in 1995 he was expected to bring that 
level of excellence with him. 
</P>
<P>
	When it wasn't seen immediately, the grumblings of discontent  
were heard. 
</P>
<P>
	But then in one weekend he took the Bears farther into NCAA  
postseason play than they had ever been. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now,'' Koeneman said, leaning back behind his bar, ``all of  
Steve Alford's critics, myself included, ought to just shut up. 
He's done something here that nobody else ever did.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
