<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anwar Expects Prison Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Ousted Deputy Prime Minister Anwar  
Ibrahim predicted Monday he would be convicted and imprisoned after 
the defense rested in his five-month sex and corruption trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense closed after the presiding judge dealt it a stunning  
blow by refusing to allow it to call witnesses who claim they were 
tortured by police into making allegations against Anwar. 
</P>
<P>
	High Court Judge Augustine Paul has consistently rejected  
defense attempts to show that a conspiracy of politicians and 
police seeking to wreck Anwar's career is behind the charges 
against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Anwar seemed resigned to a guilty verdict. When asked by  
reporters how long he expected to be sentenced, Anwar replied: 
``Two, four years, it makes no difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trial, which began Nov. 2, now enters its final stage. The  
judge set a March 21 hearing for closing arguments by both sides, 
after which he will pronounce his verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	Anwar, 51, who was sacked and arrested last September, has  
repeatedly said that all 10 charges against him were fabricated by 
his political enemies who worked with the police to end the 
challenge he posed to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad. 
</P>
<P>
	This trial concerns four charges of abuse of power related to  
alleged attempts to cover up his sexual trysts, which the 
prosecution says includes a string of illegal homosexual acts. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the four counts carries a jail term of 14 years and a  
fine of $5,000. If convicted, Anwar will also be barred from 
entering politics for five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense had sought to call a number of witnesses Monday,  
including several who say they were ``coerced, tortured until they 
fabricated stories'' of homosexual relations with Anwar. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of Anwar associates -- including his adopted brother and  
his former speech writer -- have been jailed based on confessions of 
relations with Anwar. But they have since retracted the 
confessions, saying they were coerced. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Paul, however, ruled that evidence by the witnesses  
appeared to have ``absolutely no direct connection'' with the case 
and was inadmissible. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are taken aback,'' said defense lawyer Christopher  
Fernando. ``We feel that crucial relevant evidence has been shut 
out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anwar reacted stoically. ``It's OK. It's not surprising,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul also rejected a request by the defense to allow testimony  
by a U.S.-based Malaysian businessman, who says he was offered a 
bribe by a Malaysian diplomat in Washington to make allegations 
against Anwar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 18:31:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> INS Officer Charged With Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A 12-year-veteran of the Immigration and  
Naturalization Service has been arrested on charges that she 
smuggled an illegal alien from Canada into the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Detention Enforcement Officer Paula M. Jesmer, 34, was indicted  
last week by a grand jury in Boston and arrested Monday. Federal 
prosecutors say that while working at INS' Service Processing 
Center for detainees in 1996, Jesmer got to know a Portuguese 
citizen named Jose M. Cabral-Simnas. 
</P>
<P>
	In December 1997, Cabral-Simnas was deported back to Portugal.  
But six months later he traveled to Montreal, where Jesmer met him 
and drove him across the U.S. border to her home in Medford, 
prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesmer faces a maximum penalty of 5 years in prison and $250,000  
in fines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:41:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DNC Convention Returns to L.A. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- With Democrats firmly back in power in  
California, the Democratic National Convention is returning to Los 
Angeles next year for the first time since John F. Kennedy was 
nominated in 1960. 
</P>
<P>
	Civic leaders and convention boosters said Monday's announcement  
also was proof that the nation's second-largest city had rebounded 
from its much-publicized problems -- such as recession, earthquakes, 
floods and race riots. 
</P>
<P>
	The choice of Los Angeles over 12 other cities that were asked  
to submit proposals, including Boston and Denver, reflects 
California's importance -- with its 54 electoral votes and generous 
campaign donors -- in choosing the next president. 
</P>
<P>
	``California is the big ATM for any national campaign,'' says  
Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political analyst with the Claremont 
Graduate University School of Politics and Economics. ``The 
Democrats will come in here like a vacuum cleaner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic National Committee shied away from the state in  
recent years because it was led by Republicans, said former 
Colorado Gov. Roy Romer, the chairman. He also cited ballot 
initiatives that rolled back affirmative action programs and barred 
state aid to immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	Romer said the party was ready to return to the state now that  
Democratic Gov. Gray Davis is in office, and Democrats control both 
houses in the Legislature and occupy most statewide elected 
offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Andrew, head of the DNC's site-selection team, said  
California's diversity and Los Angeles' unique public-private 
convention bid were also key factors in the party's decision. The 
Republican convention will be in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``California is the ideal place to showcase the positive message  
and vision of the Democratic Party and our presidential nominee,'' 
Andrew said. ``California represents the great diversity of this 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bid, which was put together by an independent host committee  
dubbed LA Convention 2000, proposed that private donors pick up 
much of the convention's $35.3 million cost, contrary to the usual 
practice of having the city back the deal. Although that element 
supposedly was a point of contention between the two sides, Andrew 
praised the unique offer and touted it as a ``model for political 
conventions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Unlike Republicans, the 2000 political convention will be  
sponsored by the private sector with the cooperation of the public 
sector,'' Andrew said. ``Not the other way around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican National Committee spokesman Tim Fitzpatrick  
criticized Andrew's remarks, saying the Philadelphia convention was 
part of an ``unprecedented, privately funded'' package. 
</P>
<P>
	Fitzpatrick also criticized the site, saying, ``The Democrats  
can't seem to get away from Buddhist temples and the Hollywood 
elite,'' in an apparent reference to the Hacienda Heights temple at 
the center of fund-raising allegations against Vice President Al 
Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	State and local governments will provide basic services like  
fire and bus service for the convention, while private donors, both 
individuals and companies, will pick up much of the tab. 
</P>
<P>
	Eli Broad, one of four wealthy businessmen who headed the host  
committee, touted the $150 million the convention is expected to 
bring the state in business and the publicity it will bring the 
city. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in the middle of a Renaissance,'' he said, pointing to  
the city's ongoing bid for an NFL expansion team and efforts to 
revitalize the city's troubled downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Davis, who lived in West Hollywood before being elected  
governor: ``The DNC has reaffirmed that Los Angeles is back. Los 
Angeles is once again ready to resume its role as one of the 
world's great urban centers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the money of donors like Broad and his co-chairs is  
considered one of the greatest benefits of coming to California, 
whose 54 electoral votes are the most in the nation, there's still 
no guarantee the Democratic nominee will win the Golden State. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats have held three presidential nominating conventions in  
California, and each time their nominee went on to lose California. 
</P>
<P>
	James Cox won the Democratic nomination for president in San  
Francisco in 1920, but Republican Warren G. Harding won 
California's then-13 electoral votes by a 3-1 margin four months 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy was nominated in Los Angeles in 1960, but lost the state  
to Republican Richard Nixon. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1984, Walter Mondale won the Democratic nomination in San  
Francisco. But that didn't help him against Ronald Reagan, either 
nationally or in California. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Duke, SW Mo. State Win With Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- The difficulty of what's ahead hit Steve  
Alford even before the end of the party marking the biggest triumph 
in Southwest Missouri State history. 
</P>
<P>
	Alford's Bears rode a stifling defensive performance to an 81-51  
victory over Tennessee on Sunday, putting Southwest Missouri State 
in the NCAA tournament's round of 16 for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears' so-called reward is a date with top-ranked Duke in  
Friday's East Regional semifinals at East Rutherford, N.J. The Blue 
Devils have won 29 games in a row, including back-to-back 41-point 
blowouts to open the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know we've got our hands completely full preparing for the  
best team in the country,'' Alford said with a shrug and a weak 
smile as the last of the Bears' noisy revelers left the Charlotte 
Coliseum. ``But you know what? We'd much rather be doing that than 
not playing at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tulsa was the latest team to find out how imposing Duke can be.  
The Blue Devils (34-1) built a 30-point halftime lead on the way to 
a 97-56 victory over the Golden Hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	``Duke is probably better than advertised from our  
perspective,'' Tulsa coach Bill Self said. ``We don't get a chance 
to see teams like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the Blue Devils overwhelmed the Golden Hurricane by  
forcing 20 turnovers, converting them into 30 points and limiting 
Tulsa to 34-percent shooting, Southwest Missouri State did a 
similar job on Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears (22-10) scored 24 points off Tennessee turnovers and  
harassed the Vols into 30-percent shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second big defensive game in a row for Southwest  
Missouri State, which two days earlier held Wisconsin to 32 points, 
the lowest output in an NCAA tournament game since the introduction 
of the shot clock. 
</P>
<P>
	Danny Moore had 25 points and eight rebounds to lead 12th-seeded  
Southwest Missouri State, which shot 52 percent, had a season-low 
six turnovers and never trailed. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandon Wharton and Isiah Victor had 11 points each for  
fourth-seeded Tennessee (21-9). The Vols were held to their lowest 
point total in more than two months. 
</P>
<P>
	``No explanation. We had a lot of open looks,'' Wharton said.  
``I guess we just hit a cold streak there. They made all the big 
shots and we didn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Vols were seeking their first regional semifinal berth since  
1981. Instead, that slot goes to a team that has become another 
example of Alford's NCAA tournament success. 
</P>
<P>
	He made a then-Final Four record seven 3-pointers to lead  
Indiana past Syracuse in the 1987 championship game, and in his 
first job as a head coach, he led Manchester, a school that had 
never been to the NCAA tournament, to the Division III title game. 
</P>
<P>
	Now in his fourth season at Southwest Missouri State, he faces  
his biggest test yet, and he's trying to face it with humor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll possibly put up some detour signs so Duke maybe gets  
lost and we start the game playing five on nobody,'' Alford joked. 
``We need to get a quick start because Duke has been putting away 
people pretty quick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tulsa can confirm that. The ninth-seeded Golden Hurricane  
(23-10) was held to 28-percent shooting in the first half, and 
Tulsa was unable to challenge the rest of the way. 
</P>
<P>
	Making things even tougher on the Golden Hurricane was the fact  
that Michael Ruffin, Tulsa's best frontcourt player, got into early 
foul trouble. He wound up with eight rebounds and three blocks, but 
was held scoreless. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we got down, most teams let up a little bit, but they  
kept competing the entire game,'' Ruffin said. ``They never gave us 
a chance to come back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Avery had 19 points, Elton Brand 17 and Shane Battier 14  
for the Blue Devils, who made the round of 16 for the 10th time 
under Mike Krzyzewski. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Harrington had 15 to lead Tulsa, which allowed a pair of  
13-0 runs in the first half and fell behind by as many as 43 points 
in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	``It felt like we could stop everything,'' Battier said. ``I  
can't put into words how great it feels.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:17:38 </DATE_TIME>
