<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Jobless Rate Hits Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Unemployment has climbed to a record 6 percent  
as Hong Kong struggles through recession, the government said 
Monday in a report that offered a continued gloomy outlook for the 
near term. 
</P>
<P>
	``As overall economic activity might continue to be slack in the  
early part of the year ... the unemployment rate was likely to 
remain high in the near term,'' said Tang Kwong-yiu, the government 
economist. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest figure, for the three months ending in February, is  
the highest since the government started keeping its current type 
of employment statistics in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	About 206,000 people were unemployed, compared with 202,700 in  
the rolling three-month period that ended in January, when 
unemployment stood at 5.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's joblessness had stood at 2.9 percent from December  
to February of 1998, according to the Census and Statistics 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Tang said more people were thrown out of work around the Chinese  
New Year -- which was in mid-February this year -- when companies 
traditionally review their books and lay off unneeded staff after 
giving them year-end bonuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the newly unemployed were from the construction and  
restaurant industries, while joblessness in the real estate sector 
had eased. 
</P>
<P>
	Most economists expect unemployment to climb steadily in the  
first half of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	As factories continue to leave Hong Kong for cheaper land and  
labor across the mainland Chinese border, the tiny territory is 
vying with other Asian rivals like Singapore and Malaysia to 
transform itself to become Asia's technology hub to fuel economic 
growth and provide jobs for a new breed of skilled workers. 
</P>
<P>
	A recently-announced 13-billion Hong Kong dollar ($1.67 billion)  
Cyberport project and a similar Science Park project are expected 
to provide thousands of jobs, but not until construction starts 
around 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:33:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesian Island Returns To Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMBON, Indonesia (AP) -- The riot-torn island of Ambon, where  
Christians and Muslims have been fighting one another for weeks, 
showed signs of returning to normal today. 
</P>
<P>
	Markets where many shops had been set afire during the fighting,  
which killed more than 200 people, began to reopen, selling fish 
and vegetables to people on the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, soldiers and other security forces continued  
to closely guard the streets of Ambon city and to detain people and 
confiscate crude weapons, such as slingshots, used in the fighting. 
Those taken into custody included a high school boy who was found 
with a cache of homemade arrows and spears. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in a grim reminder of how brutal the fighting has  
been, security forces today found the body of a headless and 
handless victim in Air Salobar village. 
</P>
<P>
	Word also emerged that 15 more houses had been set on fire  
Sunday night in a Muslim area of Soabali village. 
</P>
<P>
	The fierce fighting erupted Jan. 19 in Ambon, 1,500 miles east  
of Jakarta, and spread to five other islands in Maluku Province, 
known as the Spice Islands in Dutch colonial times. 
</P>
<P>
	About 90 percent of Indonesia's 210 million people are Muslim,  
making it the world's most populous Islamic nation. But Ambon's 
311,000 people are nearly equally divided into Christian and Muslim 
communities. It is not clear what started the fighting in an area 
where the two religious groups had generally gotten along well. 
</P>
<P>
	But fighting between Christians and Muslims has broken out in  
other areas of Indonesia too, including Jakarta, since civil unrest 
led to the resignation of President Suharto last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The government that replaced Suharto's is more open and  
democratic and its forces and the military have spent less time 
enforcing longstanding rules that promote religious harmony. 
</P>
<P>
	The country also is suffering through its worst economic setback  
in 30 years -- all part of the Asian financial crisis, which began 
in Southeast Asia about 19 months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990315.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 16:23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- The country's main business group  
on Monday demanded a crackdown on crime in Honduras, saying 
kidnapping, robbery and other assaults have become too common. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the last five years, 104 businessmen have been kidnapped  
and three of them killed by their captors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anti-social elements affect businessmen ... And foreign  
investment will not be consolidated until the government puts an 
end to crime,'' the Private Enterprise Council said in a news 
release. 
</P>
<P>
	It called on President Carlos Flores Facusse to take tougher  
measures to solve the problems. The president in August called for 
constitutional reforms to impose a death penalty and to more 
tightly control weapons, but the plan has not passed. 
</P>
<P>
	Police estimate that most Hondurans illegally carry firearms.  
Criminals, however, often carry military-style automatic weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- President Carlos Menem marked the  
fourth anniversary of his son's death Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Menem traveled to the Islamic Cemetery in Buenos Aires, where he  
laid a floral bouquet at the tomb of his son, Carlos Jr. He later 
held a short mass at the Olivos presidential residence, where he 
was joined by his daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlos Menem died March 15, 1995, when his low-flying helicopter  
crashed into electrical cables near a highway 150 miles north of 
the Argentine capital. The air force ruled the crash an accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Menem's ex-wife, Zulema Yoma, has repeatedly rejected the report  
and insists her son was the victim of an attack arranged by an 
organized crime syndicate. She says bullet holes in the 
helicopter's body is proof someone killed him. 
</P>
<P>
	President Menem, who initially dismissed the possibility, later  
acknowledged it was possible their son was murdered. 
</P>
<P>
	An appeal by both the president and his ex-wife to have the case  
reclassified as a homicide was rejected by a local judge last year. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Scientists have found a naturally formed mold  
of a dinosaur skull in northern Mexico, a discovery that could shed 
new light on the animal's intelligence and behavior, the government 
news agency Notimex reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The mold of the cranium, apparently from a raptor dinosaur,  
formed when a fine sediment filled the skull and petrified over 
time, paleontologist Rene Hernandez River said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez, of Mexico's National Autonomous University, said  
scientists have studied similar molds made of silicon. He did not 
know of any discoveries of other naturally created cranium molds, 
Notimex said. 
</P>
<P>
	The cranium mold was found Saturday in Rincon Colorado, one of  
the world's most important dinosaur fossil fields, in the northern 
state of Coahuila. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
