<DOCNO> APW19990315.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 11:44:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Nev. Gov. Won't Run For Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Former Gov. Bob Miller said Monday he will not  
run for the U.S. Senate, putting a damper on Democratic hopes of 
retaining the seat being vacated by Richard Bryan. 
</P>
<P>
	``After weeks of soul-searching, the final conclusion is that I  
will not be a candidate for Senate in the next election,'' he said 
at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very enticing position, one that I had not previously  
aspired to. The swing balance was I like living in Nevada,'' Miller 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, 53, stepped down in January after 10 years as the  
state's chief executive. He had been considered the leading 
Democratic candidate for Senate, and was wooed by some of the top 
names in his party, including President Clinton, Vice President Al 
Gore and the first lady. He also received a call from Senate 
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., whose party needs a net gain 
of six Democrats in the 2000 elections to capture control of the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said last month he would weigh his options after talking  
to his family. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats were counting on a strong candidate to make the Senate  
race. Former Republican Rep. John Ensign has already announced he 
will seek Bryan's seat. Ensign lost the 1998 Senate race to 
Democratic Sen. Harry Reid by 428 votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jim Gibbons, R-Nev., is also considering the race. Gibbons  
said today he would not let Ensign's plans impact him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never ducked a good fight, no matter who's in the race,''  
Gibbons said. 
</P>
<P>
	During his final term as governor, Miller had been rumored for  
an ambassadorship in the Clinton administration, but he later said 
he wanted to remain in Nevada. The two became friends when Clinton 
was governor of Arkansas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
