<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybean, Other Futures Slide  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Soybean and grain futures prices settled mostly lower Monday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade after a weekend of dry weather in South 
America accelerated the harvest of bumper crops in Brazil and 
Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, pork, coffee and energy futures also fell.  
</P>
<P>
	Traders had already been expecting bumper soybean and corn crops  
in Brazil and Argentina. But good weather is putting even more 
pressure futures prices, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of it had to do with the big harvesting weekend in South  
America,'' said Don Roose, president of Iowa-based U.S. Commodities 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	A strengthening Brazilian currency also may prompt Brazilian  
farmers to sell their crops quickly, further increasing the supply 
and causing worldwide prices to drop further, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Roose said traders also were anticipating end-of-the-month  
reports to show that the number of acres dedicated to soybeans and 
grains would increase. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that weighed on us today too,'' Roose said.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for May delivery fell 1/4 cent to $2.72 1/4 a bushel; May corn  
fell 2 3/4 cents to 2.20 a bushel; May oats dropped 1 1/4 cents to $1.09 3/4 
a bushel, and May soybeans fell 3 1/2 cents to $4.71 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, lean hog futures fell a penny a pound on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange on news that hog slaughter is expected to top 2 
million head this week for the first time in eight weeks. Bad 
weather in some parts of the country had kept farmers from 
delivering hogs to market last week. 
</P>
<P>
	In Monday's trading, April lean hogs fell a cent to 41.07 cents  
a pound; March pork bellies dropped 0.72 cent to 48 cents per 
pound; April live cattle futures fell 0.80 cent to 66.35 cents a 
pound; and March feeder cattle dropped 0.23 cent to 71.57 cents per 
pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, coffee futures fell on the Board of Trade of the City  
of New York amid concerns the Green Coffee Association will 
increase its estimate of U.S. warehouse stocks. May arabica coffee 
fell 1.65 cents to $1.033 a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy futures also slipped a bit on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange. Analysts said warmer weather in some parts of the country 
-- which tends to lower demand for crude and heating oil -- eroded 
Friday's gains, which had been fueled by news of a deal to cut 
production by the Organization of Petroleum Export Countries and 
other nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Light, sweet crude for April delivery fell 4 cents to $14.45 a  
barrel; April heating oil fell 0.65 cent to 38.08 cents a gallon; 
April unleaded gasoline fell 0.17 cent to 45.01 cents a gallon; 
April natural gas fell 0.42 cent to $1.717 for each 1,000 cubic 
feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
