<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 07:23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Faulted in Airport Confusion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- A former U.S. Transportation Department  
official who became a top critic of goverment airline safety policy 
today blamed airport officials for turmoil that followed her 
attempt to put an unaccompanied suitcase on a plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Schiavo said on NBC's ``Today'' show that she was sorry for  
any inconvenience caused when Port Columbus International Airport 
called the bomb squad and closed a runway for four hours Friday. 
``But it was done by the airport with the full knowledge of what 
was going on,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	WCMH-TV reported that it had told an airport official Friday  
morning that it was doing a story on airport security. The station 
said in a statement Sunday that Ms. Schiavo, working with the 
station, had checked in a bag for a flight as part of the story, 
and that airport officials were made aware of the existence of the 
piece of luggage at around the time the flight was to have taken 
off. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard L. Morgan, director of public safety at Port Columbus,  
said Sunday that he could not verify that the suspicious bag that 
shut down the runway was the one left by Ms. Schiavo. He told The 
Washington Post that airport authorities would not have acted as 
they did if they did not believe lives were at stake. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ms. Schiavo told The Washington Post in a story published  
today that she believes authorities created a major incident to 
diminish her role as an airline safety advocate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is pretty clear that the intent was to make a scene to  
stifle my activism,'' she told the newspaper. ``They may have 
succeeded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Schiavo confirmed she was working with the station, and said  
she regretted her involvement and wouldn't do it again but insisted 
she didn't do anything wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not illegal to buy a ticket, check a bag and not get on a  
plane,'' said Ms. Schiavo, the Transportation Department's former 
inspector general. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Schiavo, who resigned her federal post in 1996 in the wake  
of the ValuJet crash that killed 110 people, wrote a book accusing 
the FAA of sloppy inspections, lax airport security and disregard 
for substandard airplane parts. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Schiavo, who lives in a Columbus suburb, said she bought one  
ticket to Washington, D.C., for a 2:58 p.m. Friday flight on 
America West Airlines and checked her bag at noon. But she didn't 
board the plane. She said she was hoping to determine whether the 
bag would be allowed to take off with the flight even though its 
owner was not on board. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the bag was clearly marked with her name and address  
and contained several items including a cellular phone wire and 
sneakers loosely packed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was not constructed to look like a bomb,'' Ms. Schiavo  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI spokesman Frank Scafidi said Sunday the agency is  
investigating. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there are going to be any charges brought, that would be a  
decision made by prosecutors, local or federal,'' Scafidi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Takemoto, FAA spokesman, said Sunday that the FAA was  
looking into whether FAA regulations were involved. Patty Nowack, a 
spokeswoman for America West, said the airline complied with FAA 
rules by not loading the unaccompanied bag. 
</P>
<P>
	WCMH said it is cooperating fully with airport officials.  
</P>
<P>
	Bags are matched to passengers on international flights, but  
checks are not required for domestic passengers. Discovery of the 
unaccompanied bag prompted airport officials to shut down a runway 
for four hours. 





</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
