<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arab-American Claims Israel Torture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department is attempting to assist  
an Arab-American in filing a protest against Israel based on his 
allegations that he was subjected to torture while being detained 
in Israel for six weeks last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman James P. Rubin said Monday that Anwar Mohammed, 27, of  
Miami, was detained on suspicion of membership in Hamas and other 
nationalist activities. 
</P>
<P>
	He was arrested on Oct. 28 and released on Dec. 7 without formal  
charges having been filed. 
</P>
<P>
	When a U.S. consular officer visited him in November, ``Mr.  
Mohammed spoke of mistreatment, specifically being made to sit in a 
low chair with his hands handcuffed behind his back,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	On a subsequent visit by the consular officer on Dec. 3,  
Mohammed spoke of ``violent treatment by fellow prisoners, whom he 
characterized as informants working with Israeli authorities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to Rubin, Mohammed said these prisoners had forced him  
to admit throwing stones during anti-Israeli protests by 
Palestinians when he was 17. He said he wanted to file a protest 
once he was released. 
</P>
<P>
	Attempts by the State Department to reach him during January and  
February were unsuccessful. A meeting was arranged for March 9 but 
was postponed because of bad weather, Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the State Department wishes to reschedule the  
appointment at the earliest possible date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
