<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Meets With Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- His face pale and his voice weak, President Boris  
Yeltsin held a hospital meeting Monday with his prime minister and 
pledged to ``take part'' in the country's two most pressing issues 
-- if absolutely needed. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the latest sign of Yeltsin's increasing distance from the  
day-to-day affairs of his office. 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting in front of a small table at the Central Clinical  
Hospital, where he is recuperating from a bleeding ulcer, the 
68-year-old Yeltsin was shown on television speaking with Prime 
Minister Yevgeny Primakov. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin was hospitalized for two weeks in January, followed by  
rest at home and in a sanitarium. He re-entered the hospital Feb. 
27, after his ulcer started bleeding again. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin says he has no intention of resigning though he has not  
been able to work full-time for the past several months. 
</P>
<P>
	He told Primakov that the two most pressing issues they had to  
discuss were Russia's deteriorating relations with the breakaway 
region of Chechnya and its difficult negotiations with the 
International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin said Chechnya was a ``more complicated'' situation than  
the IMF talks. ``In both cases, in case of necessity, I am ready to 
take part,'' he told Primakov. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin spoke more slowly than usual and gestured without his  
usual forcefulness. He dismissed rumors that he was about to 
dismiss Primakov. 
</P>
<P>
	The news media want to ``drive a wedge between Yeltsin and  
Primakov,'' the president said. ``Nature has not even created such 
a wedge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I absolutely agree with you. Such a wedge cannot exist,''  
Primakov said, nodding. Rumors that Yeltsin was going to fire 
Primakov or shake up his Cabinet have ebbed and flowed for much of 
the past month. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting was the first face-to-face talk between the two  
since the end of February, when Yeltsin and Primakov went on 
television together to say they were committed to remaining in 
their posts until the presidential elections scheduled for the 
summer of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin's illnesses have left Primakov holding most of the  
responsibility for the government's pressing issues, the economy 
foremost among them. The situation in Chechnya has also become a 
major concern following the kidnapping of a Russian police general 
there earlier this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
